<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 00:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton: Giuliani tapping into right-leaning network  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton says Rudolph Giuliani
is piling up a lead over her in fund raising in their Senate race
because he is tapping into a network of right-wing non-New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said during a campaign trip Monday that Elian
Gonzalez should be back with his Cuban father and that any decision
about a return to Cuba should be left up to the father, if the
courts award him custody.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the New York City mayor is utilizing a ''broad
national network of people who are opposed to what I would do in
the Senate'' to raise what her husband on Saturday predicted would
be a ''double-ton'' of money.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is playing on their fears and sending out these direct mail
requests and people that are seeing them are responding to it,''
said Clinton, who is trailing $19 million to $12 million in the
fund-raising competition against Giuliani. ''I don't think it's
very complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's fund-raising letters are ''more in line with the
right wing of America than the mainstream of New Yorkers,'' Clinton
said. On Saturday, the president said Giuliani was benefiting from
a ''right-wing venom machine.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Mrs. Clinton is obviously disappointed in her campaign and its
ability to attract more support, so now she's reverting to that old
Clinton ruse of blaming the vast right-wing conspiracy,'' Giuliani
campaign manager Bruce Teitelbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   During her campaign trip Monday, the first lady also said life
on the campaign trail is harder than expected, especially for
women.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm having a great time, but I'm also seeing how hard it is''
to be a candidate, she told an audience of about 100 people at a
community forum in the village of Coxsackie just south of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm almost embarrassed to think back -- all the times that I
would say to my husband, 'Well, you could have said this
differently, or you could have done that.' Now, I would like to
take all those words back because it's very tough for both men and
women,'' the first lady said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton said ''there are extra burdens that women
(candidates) face around the country.'' She did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   ''The best advice I've ever seen for women in politics came from
one of my favorite predecessors, Eleanor Roosevelt ... She said,
'You must grow skin as tough as a rhinoceros.'
</P>
<P>
   ''So if you look carefully at my skin ...'' Clinton began before
she was drowned out by laughter.
</P>
<P>
   There were serious moments at the forum, such as when one former
Democrat and handgun owner told her he had defected to the
Republicans because of what he perceived as ''no-gun policies''
being promoted by Clinton's fellow Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady said she did not believe in outlawing all guns,
but did want to see them licensed, have required background checks
for owners and action to make sure children could not get at guns.
</P>
<P>
   And while attacking the National Rifle Association for being
stuck on a ''theological view'' about gun control, Clinton also
warned against ''people on the other extreme who want to take
everybody's guns away.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I've gone hunting,'' she said. ''I don't have anything against
guns if guns are used by responsible people.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a message seemingly designed to appeal to more
conservative voters in upstate New York, a key battleground in the
Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton was fielding questions on the campaign trail,
Giuliani took time out from his mayoral duties to take in opening
day at Shea Stadium where the Mets hosted the San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also joined Democrats from the state Legislature at an
appearance at the state Capitol in calling on the state Senate's
Republican majority to pass hate crimes legislation. For several
years, Giuliani has unsuccessfully sought to convince the state
Senate GOP to adopt that very legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reiterated Monday that Elian Gonzalez should be with his
Cuban father, but she stopped short of saying she favored him being
sent back to Cuba. She did complain that the boy was being used
''for political purposes'' and that a ''media circus'' had
developed around him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe personally, this little boy should be with his
father,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson said the first lady
felt the father should be granted custody of the child and that any
return to Cuba should then be up to the father. She said
politicians should stay out of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Both Giuliani and Vice President Al Gore have called on Congress
to approve legislation granting Elian, his father and other family
members permanent residency in the United States so they can stay
here while the court fight goes on and so the family can stay in
this country after it is over, if they wish to.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady has said Giuliani has helped turn Elian Gonzalez
into a ''political football.'' She has refused to say the same of
Gore, although she conceded Monday that the two disagree on the
case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
