<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Gore leads Bush among New York voters  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Al Gore has ended months of being in a
statistical dead heat with George W. Bush and is now ahead by
double digits, a statewide poll shows.
</P>
<P>
   The poll from Marist College's Institute for Public Opinion
showed the vice president leading the Texas governor, 49 percent to
38 percent. Previous polls dating back to March 1999 had shown Gore
and Bush running neck-and-neck when margins of error were factored
in.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has a wide lead over Bush in New York City and its suburbs.
He is ahead in the city 65 percent to 23 percent and 50 percent to
41 percent in the suburbs. But Bush, a Republican, is favored by
upstate New York voters 47 percent to 39 percent for the Democratic
vice president, the poll found.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had an 8-point lead among suburban voters in December but
now trails Gore by 9 percentage points. Among independents, Bush
was ahead by 21 points but is now behind by 6.
</P>
<P>
   Registered Democrats outnumber Republicans by a 5-3 margin in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Marist pollster Lee Miringoff said Monday the shift took place
largely among suburban voters and independents, who were driven
away from Bush when the governor ''moved to the right'' in order to
defeat Arizona Sen. John McCain in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now that the primaries are over, we're seeing some of the more
normal Northeastern voting patterns coming into play,'' Miringoff
said. ''We're seeing the middle-of-the road electorate fighting for
Gore. New York is not on the must-win list for Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said the decline in support for
the governor is ''natural after a competitive primary.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We've always realized that New York is going to be a
competitive state, but we still think that Governor Bush's
compassionate conservative message appeals to a lot of different
people and we'll make sure we keep delivering that message,''
Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president ''isn't going to take one vote for granted,''
said Peter Ragone, spokesman for Gore's New York campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's going to fight his heart and soul out for every vote in
the state and continue to talk about issues that matter most to New
York state,'' Ragone said.
</P>
<P>
   The Marist poll also found that having Gov. George Pataki as his
running mate won't help Bush much in New York, with only 28 percent
of voters saying they'll be more likely to vote for Bush vs. 42
percent saying they're less likely to vote for the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly there's not a big sense in the numbers that Pataki
would make a huge difference here,'' Miringoff said. ''He doesn't
bring any inroads to Democrats and independents, which he clearly
needs to do if he's on the ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates are in a statistical dead heat among male
voters, with 46 percent supporting Gore and 42 percent for Bush,
but Gore leads Bush among women, 53 percent to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone poll of 561 registered voters was conducted March
27-28 and has a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percentage
points. Forty-two percent of those polled were Democrats, 31
percent were Republicans and 21 percent independents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
