<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton lobbies for passage of Albany hate crime bill  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton had no better luck
than her expected opponent for the U.S. Senate in urging state
Senate Republican Senators to pass a hate crimes bill.
</P>
<P>
   After a heated debate Monday, Republicans blocked a Democratic
attempt to force the hate crimes legislation passed by the Assembly
onto the floor of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said ''it's embarrassing'' that New York is one of only
nine states without hate crime measures.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are making clear that New York can no longer lag behind the
rest of the country in the emphasis ... on stopping hate wherever
it rears its ugly head,'' Clinton said in a state Capitol news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrat-led state Assembly has passed the bill for 11
straight years, most recently in February. But the state Republican
majority has repeatedly ignored the legislation, arguing that such
a bill would discriminate against the victims of non-bias crimes by
creating a special class of victims.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph Giuliani, a Republican, has also unsuccessfully tried to
convince the Senate GOP to adopt the legislation. Clinton said
that's because the New York City mayor never came to Albany to
directly address the hate crimes issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''He needs to come here and look into the eyes of the Republican
senators who he's expecting to support him and tell them that they
should do this because this is the right thing to do,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno said Republicans were voting
against the procedure, rather than the legislation, and promised
that GOP senators would deal with the issue on their own terms.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an important issue that should be addressed and discussed
on the Senate floor and we intend to do this,'' Bruno said.
</P>
<P>
   But tempers on both sides of the aisle in the Senate were short,
with Republicans accusing Democrats of grandstanding and Democrats
complaining that they were not being allowed to discuss the issue
openly.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno said Democrats were prohibited from talking about the
merits of the legislation they were trying to get out onto the
floor through a ''motion to discharge.'' When the presiding officer
in the Senate, Republican Lt. Gov. Mary Donohue, upheld that
interpretation of the chamber's rules, Senate Democratic leader
Martin Connor complained that his members were being muzzled.
</P>
<P>
   ''No presiding officer that I know of has ever, ever ruled hat
members cannot discuss underlying bills,'' Connor said. ''How could
one possibly explain a motion of discharge ... and why it was
important to bring the bill to the floor now, without discussing
the merits?''
</P>
<P>
   Donohue later gaveled and shouted Connor down when he yelled
that the Democrats were facing unprecedented obstacles to debating
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed hate crimes bill would increase penalties for
crimes motivated by race, color, gender, sexual orientation,
religion, national origin or disability.
</P>
<P>
   The hate crime offense would be a class C or D felony and would
be imposed separately from other offenses by an attacker, such as
murder or assault. Conviction could add as much as 15 years to an
offender's sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Howie Katz, chairman of the Hate Crimes Bill Coalition, said
with Georgia passing a hate crimes bill two weeks ago, New York and
South Carolina are now the only states on the East Coast without
such a measure.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's particularly embarrassing to stand in the company of a
state that still flies the Confederate flag over its capitol,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
