<HEADLINE> State ended 1999-2000 fiscal year $1.5 billion in black  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- New York was in the black as its last fiscal
year ended, the fifth straight year of surpluses under Gov. George
Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   The state recorded a $1.5 billion surplus in the 1999-2000
fiscal year budget in which it spent $73.3 billion, officials said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   State Comptroller H. Carl McCall said the balance sheet for the
just-completed fiscal year shows that a ''lack of resources'' is
not an issue in the failure of Pataki and the state Legislature to
have a new budget when the 2000-01 state fiscal year began on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Late budgets are the result of a lack of leadership and a
flawed budget process,'' McCall said. ''It's time for the governor
and the Legislature to enact meaningful budget reform and end this
cycle of ineptitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The year-end budget figures released Monday were interpreted in
different ways by the players in Albany's budget game.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's budget director Carole Stone urged caution, saying
surpluses are ''one-time resources'' which should not be depended
on to fund recurring programs.
</P>
<P>
   State Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno said years of tax cuts
championed by his Republican chamber have helped create recent
years' surpluses. He reiterated his insistence on enacting further
deep tax cuts in the 2000-01 budget.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leader in the Assembly, John Faso, said the
surplus should be used to repeal the state's gross receipts tax on
energy.
</P>
<P>
   McCall, a Democrat who may run for governor in 2002, also
accused Republican Gov. Pataki of operating a ''shell game'' of
sorts with the surplus. McCall said his office has started to send
out more than 1 million state income tax refunds which were held up
for at least three weeks because there was technically no money to
cover the checks.
</P>
<P>
   McCall said the state could have paid for the refunds, but
accused Pataki of holding up the money so the $500 million or so to
cover the checks would be counted toward the year-end surplus for
fiscal 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki budget aides denied that any refund checks were held up
to intentionally pad the 1999-2000 surplus numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Previous years' budget surpluses under Pataki have totaled $1.8
billion in fiscal 1998-99; $2.04 billion in 1997-98; $1.42 billion
in 1996-97 and $445 million in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Monday, the finger-pointing continued over the late
budget for fiscal 2000-01, with Bruno and the Democratic speaker of
the state Assembly, Sheldon Silver, blaming each other for the 16th
straight failure to adopt an on-time budget.
</P>
<P>
   Silver continued to insist that Bruno is so miffed at Pataki
because of a spat between the two Republicans that the Senate is
refusing to join productive talks that have been taking place
privately between Pataki and Silver.
</P>
<P>
   Silver said Bruno is intent on ''political paybacks'' against
the governor for firing Bruno-recommended workers on the state
payroll and other difficulties between the two men.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Sen. Bruno wasn't so upset about his loss of patronage then
we would have a budget,'' Silver said on Albany radio station
WROW-AM Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno, meanwhile, said Silver continues to harp on the dispute
between the majority leader and governor to deflect attention away
from Silver's desire to negotiate as much of a high-spending budget
in private as he can. Bruno said he remains prepared to immediately
convene conference committees to discuss a budget publicly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
