<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Employees Buy Canton Paper Mill  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL NOWELL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, N.C. (AP) -- Tim Smather had the look of a contented man,
even though he took a $7,000 pay cut in 1999 at his job of 24
years.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a year ago, he and more than 1,000 other workers at the
old Champion International paper mill jumped off the career path
followed by their parents and grandparents, who punched a clock
every day at the Haywood County plant.
</P>
<P>
   They bought the place.
</P>
<P>
   The historic purchase of the Canton mill and several other
plants owned by Champion came with a hefty price: a 15 percent cut
in pay and benefits for the length of their seven-year union
contract. In return for financial backing by a New York investment
group, the employees got stock in the company and a profit-sharing
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Now named Blue Ridge Paper Products, Inc., the new company
operates mills in Canton and Waynesville and five finishing plants
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   For Smather, he hopes it means there will be stability at the
mill, which has seen its share of volatility and controversy since
it opened in 1908.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's more laid back in there than it's ever been,'' said
Smather, now 42, pointing back over his shoulder to the sprawling
factory that has provided his income since he was 18. ''Now we can
worry about what other paper companies are doing instead of
worrying about our jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   As part-owners, the workers have to deal with the same problems
that compelled Champion to sell it in the first place: cheap
foreign imports, uncertain markets and antiquated equipment.
Moreover, the industry is undergoing rapid consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   Smather said morale is high at the Canton plant.
</P>
<P>
   ''We earned a small profit last year,'' he said proudly. ''I got
$1,000 back from the $8,000 I lost in wages.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's buyout resolved nearly 18 months of uncertainty that
followed Champion's announcement that it planned to sell the
Haywood County mills and plants in Georgia, Iowa, New Jersey, Ohio
and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, the plant was harshly criticized by environmental
groups from Tennessee for polluting the Pigeon River. Champion
invested about $250 million several years ago to comply with
stringent environmental regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Once the mills went on the selling block, the local paperworkers
union stepped up as the only potential buyer. After months of
negotiations, the New York-based KPS Special Situations Fund
investment group backing the deal said it had reached a formal
agreement to buy the seven factories for $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Employees now control 40 percent of the company's stock, while
KPS and its investors control 55 percent. Five percent was retained
by senior management.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-member board of directors hired industry veteran Gordon
Jones as its president and chief executive officer. His first major
move was to acquire Westvaco's liquid packaging division.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the acquisition would increase Blue Ridge's market
share. Based in Richmond, Va., the division has about 100 employees
and includes two state-of-the-art web offset presses used to make
high-quality juice and milk cartons.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although it's not a huge acquisition, it's a significant step
for us to grow our business,'' said Jones, who managed 85 plants
for Chicago-based Smurfit-Stone Container Corp., one of the world's
largest makers of paperboard and paper-based packaging products.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has made it clear he plans for the employee buyout to have
a happy ending. Distinctly aware of the mill's long history in
western North Carolina, he bought some old photographs of the plant
and its workers dating to 1910.
</P>
<P>
   The prints were enlarged and framed, and now hang in the
company's headquarters in the BB&AMP;T Bank building in downtown
Asheville. Jones likes to point out details in some of the photos,
such as the huge piles of pine and hardwood trees that were cut
down and stacked neatly by hand.
</P>
<P>
   ''It shows just how much more productive paper mills are today,
because we'd never have that kind of volume on hand in our yard,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like the rank-and-file, Jones is invigorated by the challenge of
making Blue Ridge Paper successful. He also is proud of the
experienced management team he assembled.
</P>
<P>
   It will be tested in the rough-and-tumble markets in which Blue
Ridge will have to compete. Making their challenge even tougher is
a spate of recent mergers and acquisitions that make the Asheville
company a much smaller player.
</P>
<P>
   ''These deals make us the aberration as a $500 million
company,'' Jones said. ''What we need to do is to take advantage of
our size and be quicker to bring new products to the market.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one motive behind his decision to buy Westvaco's liquid
packaging division. The high-end cartons produced by the new
presses bring in a higher profit margin.
</P>
<P>
   While Champion was often reluctant to make major changes to the
plant's product line, Blue Ridge is looking for ways to enter new
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we talk about changes coming to this company, we're not
just talking about changing the color of the paint in the
bathrooms,'' Jones said. ''We want to do things better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
