<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Ally Threatens Violence  </HEADLINE>
By RON KAMPEAS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FATIMA GATE, Israel-Lebanon Border (AP) -- Israel's top ally in
Lebanon on Monday invoked the fall of the ancient hilltop fortress
of Masada -- the bloodiest last stand in Jewish history -- to
describe what may be in store for his men after Israel's scheduled
withdrawal in three months.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Antoine Lahad's rhetoric, however, was at odds with
predictions by Israeli officials -- and of some of the 80,000
Lebanese in his charge -- of an uneventful transition, with some
militiamen going into exile with their families, and others coming
to peaceful terms with the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has pledged to withdraw his
troops from south Lebanon by July, making good on an election
promise to end an increasingly unpopular occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Barak would prefer to pull out as part of a peace agreement with
Syria, the main power in Lebanon, but the two sides seem
intractably at odds over territorial issues. Without an agreement,
Lahad's South Lebanese Army faces an uncertain future.
</P>
<P>
   Lahad told reporters Monday that his 2,600 fighters would only
relinquish control of south Lebanon if given assurances by the
Lebanese government that they will not be punished for cooperating
with Israel. He also demanded that his men be absorbed into the
Lebanese army.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the Lebanese government has offered lenient
treatment to lower-ranking South Lebanon Army members considering
defection. However, Lahad and other senior officers have been
sentenced to death in absentia, and it was not clear if they would
get the same deal.
</P>
<P>
   Lahad said Beirut's failure to meet his conditions would mean
''the government does not want to come south.''
</P>
<P>
   Without assurances from the Lebanese authorities, ''just like
you at Masada, we will fight for our land,'' he told reporters at
an Israeli army base on the border.
</P>
<P>
   The reference was to a hilltop fortress in the Judean desert
where Jewish rebels and their families resisted Roman soldiers for
years. When they saw the Romans were about to breach their
defenses, 960 people killed themselves rather than surrender in
A.D. 73.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some of Lahad's militiamen are already quietly moving
to avoid a cataclysm. Some speak of accommodating themselves to
Lebanese rule; others say they will seek refuge in Israel from a
vengeance promised by the Hezbollah, the Islamic militia that is
Israel's main enemy in the south.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would prefer to live in my land,'' said Issa Karim, an SLA
mechanic who was crossing into Lebanon at the ''Good Fence,'' the
transit point for the many Lebanese who shop and work in Israel.
''But if the Hezbollah comes to try and take me and my children, I
would come to Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Israelis, feeling an allegiance to a militia that has
helped their troops police the buffer zone Israel has occupied for
18 years, have lobbied their government hard to absorb the SLA men
and their families -- about 10,000 people altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are their last hope,'' said Miriam Hod, a hotelier in the
border town of Metulla who has been working on behalf of about 100
Lebanese families.
</P>
<P>
   The top Israeli army commander in Lebanon said his troops were
ready to offer refuge in Israel to any or all of the SLA men and
their families -- the first official Israeli acknowledgment of such
a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ''Israel is obligated to them,'' Brig. Gen. Benny Ganz said.
</P>
<P>
   Ganz said he was ''optimistic'' that the post-pullout period
would be relatively free of bloodshed. He cited the SLA withdrawal
from Jezzine, a town on the northern tip of the buffer zone, last
year as an example.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the SLA troops who remained in Jezzine -- and who had
supposedly faced death sentences for treachery -- instead spent a
few months in prison and were released to their old jobs and
families.
</P>
<P>
   Ganz grimaced each time Lahad, who is recovering from an
undisclosed illness, warned that his men were prepared to ''die on
their land.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of those under Lahad's control are sure it will come to
that.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would like Israel to stay,'' said Yusuf Salih, a 73-year-old
Lebanese returning from a day's work in the peach and cherry
orchards along the border.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he also looked forward to reuniting with two sons in Beirut.
Even the prospect of imprisonment did not daunt him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will see them when I get out of jail,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said Monday that
the United States will not deploy troops in south Lebanon as part
of an international peacekeeping force after Israel withdraws.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, speaking after a meeting with Cohen, said he did not
expect the current U.N. peacekeeping force in the area to be
expanded significantly after an Israel pullback.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said no decisions have been made about the future of U.N.
peacekeepers in south Lebanon. ''I do not anticipate that the
United States will be a participant should there be such a
UNIFIL,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
