<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Row Inmate's Son Charged  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL GRACZYK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- The 21-year-old son of an infamous Texas death
row inmate has been jailed on a capital murder charge stemming from
a shooting death in Houston last week, authorities said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   If prosecutors choose to seek the death penalty in the Gary
Hawkins case, conviction could result in Gary Graham and Hawkins
becoming the only father-son duo among the more than 450 condemned
murderers in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before we had the arrest warrant we believed he was Gary
Graham's son,'' Brian Harris, a Houston police homicide
investigator, said Monday. ''Obviously Gary Graham's been gone for
a whole lot of time and hasn't had an influence.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham, 38, who now prefers to be known as Shaka Sankofa to
reflect his African heritage, has been on death row since November
1981 when he was condemned for the shooting death six months
earlier of Bobby Lambert, 53, of Tucson, Ariz., during a robbery
outside a Houston supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   His case has been one of the most highly publicized in Texas,
serving as a lightning rod for both death penalty opponents and
proponents. It has been reviewed more than 35 times by the courts
and remains in the federal appeals courts.
</P>
<P>
   Graham and his supporters have produced what they say are
witnesses who place him elsewhere at the time of the shooting or
contend someone else was the gunman. Such witnesses previously have
been ruled by courts as vague or not credible.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins was hiding in a motel along Interstate 10 in east
Houston when he arrested without incident Sunday for the fatal
shooting of Melvin Ray Pope, 32, whose body was found on the side
of a road March 29. Pope was shot in the back of the head.
</P>
<P>
   A second man was arrested Friday and charged with aggravated
robbery in the Pope case.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe Hawkins was the triggerman. They say robbery was
the motive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
