<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Silvester probe nets fourth guilty plea  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- A fourth person has pleaded guilty in
connection with the corruption investigation of former state
Treasurer Paul J. Silvester.
</P>
<P>
   George Gomes, who worked as Silvester's assistant treasurer,
pleaded guilty in U.S. District Court Monday to a single count of
mail fraud. Federal prosecutors say Gomes, 33, laundered money for
Silvester's failed 1998 re-election bid.
</P>
<P>
   ''(Gomes) disguised an influx of cash to Paul Silvester's
campaign as legitimate contributions,'' said Assistant U.S.
Attorney Nora Dannehy.
</P>
<P>
   Gomes could receive a maximum 5-year prison sentence, but will
likely serve less time because he has cooperated with the
government and has accepted responsibility for his actions. He also
faces a $250,000 fine. He is scheduled to be sentenced June 22.
</P>
<P>
   Gomes admitted that an intermediary for Silvester gave him
$4,500 in October, 1998. Dannehy and Gomes' lawyer, Harold James
Pickerstein, refused to say who gave Silvester that money or who
funneled the cash to Gomes.
</P>
<P>
   Gomes then gave $1,600 to an individual who turned the money
over to Silvester's campaign. With some of the remaining money,
Gomes made two contributions to Silvester's campaign -- one in his
name and one in someone else's. Dannehy and Pickerstein would not
identify the other people involved in the scam, and their names
were not mentioned in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, campaign contributions for treasurer are capped
at $1,500 and contributors are not allowed to make payments in the
name of someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Gomes also mailed a statement to the secretary of the state
which falsely listed the source of contributions to Silvester's
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''We agree that if the case were to go to trial, the government
would be able to prove that beyond a reasonable doubt,''
Pickerstein said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 23, Silvester, his brother Mark, and brother-in-law
Peter Hirschl pleaded guilty to federal charges stemming from a
multi-million-dollar racketeering and kickback conspiracy during
Silvester's tenure from mid-1997 to January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The three have agreed to testify against others. They are
scheduled to be sentenced June 19, and investigators are still
probing the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Since at least last summer, federal authorities have been
investigating the hiring of Gomes in early 1999 as a lobbyist with
the New London law firm of Glenn T. Carberry. Carberry is a former
Republican congressional candidate with ties to Gov. John G.
Rowland.
</P>
<P>
   When Silvester left office in January 1999, he tried to find
jobs for a number of his displaced appointees.
</P>
<P>
   Late in his term, Silvester gave a $27.5-million state pension
deal to Philadelphia-based Keystone Venture Capital Management Co.,
which Carberry had represented in talks with Silvester's office.
Keystone agreed to make payments totaling $275,000-- 1 percent of
the investment-- to Carberry's firm for lobbying services through
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Carberry has denied any link between Silvester's approval of the
Keystone deal and Gomes' job with the firm. Gomes has since left
the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Carberry could not be reached for comment by The Associated
Press. A telephone message was left at his firm Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Gomes' name was brought up last fall by J. Vincent Chase, the
man Rowland picked to become state treasurer in mid-1997 and then
dumped a few days later in favor of Silvester.
</P>
<P>
   Chase said that Gomes approached him with the idea of using the
treasurer's office as a 1998 campaign fund-raising machine for
Rowland and the state Republican Party. Chase thought his refusal
to go along with that idea contributed to Rowland's decision not to
support his appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland has denied the charge, and his spokesman Dean Pagani
would not comment on the Gomes case Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-04-00 0107 </TRAILER>
