<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands turn out to welcome returning champs  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA TOMMELLEO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. (AP) -- In her last home game at Gampel Pavilion,
senior forward Stacy Hansmeyer sang the national anthem before
10,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
   She hit all the high notes.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, when she held the microphone at Gampel rally for
the NCAA national champs, she struggled through tears.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have made my four years so special,'' she told the crowd.
''What a way for us to go out.''
</P>
<P>
   Her teammates made sure that Hansmeyer and fellow senior Paige
Sauer finished their collegiate careers on a high note. A very high
note.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies routed perennial power Tennessee 72-51 for their
second national title in five years. The crowd of about 5,000
cheered wildly Monday as highlights of the title game were flashed
across the large scoreboard screen.
</P>
<P>
   Junior All-American Svetlana Abrosimova didn't need to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everytime I close my eyes I see the game,'' she said. ''And
especially the last couple minutes when we were on the bench and
Stacy and Paige were on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Sauer and Hansmeyer, both top recruits out of Oklahoma four
years ago, have had limited playing time in their final year,
making way for a talented sophomore squad.
</P>
<P>
   ''They brought so much to the team,'' said Abrosimova.
''Everyone was crying because we knew it was there last game. I
love them. They're my best friends.''
</P>
<P>
   All over Connecticut on Monday, school principals politely
looked the other way as parents pulled their kids out early for
''dentist appointments.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, more than a few employees skipped out early with a
sudden fever.
</P>
<P>
   Husky fever, to be exact.
</P>
<P>
   The Hossack sisters -- Ashley, 12 and Shauna, 10 -- of Storrs
sported blue and white face paint and waved their signs to the beat
of the pep band. They weren't in school Monday because ''we said we
had a dentist appointment,'' said Ashley.
</P>
<P>
   ''But we wanted to celebrate their victory,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Their mother, Colleen, knew they were playing hooky. She was
sitting right next to them.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm really proud of the team,'' she said. ''I'm hoping maybe
my kids will go to UConn and maybe they'll want to play
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn (36-1) has won seven straight Big East titles and breezed
through this year's tournament. Coach Geno Auriemma was able to
play every player on his bench in all six tournament games.
</P>
<P>
   University President Philip Austin called the rally ''an
official reaffirmation of what we have known for a long time --
we're Number One.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second straight year the state and campus embraced a
national champion. The UConn men won it all last year and a few of
the men's players attended the rally, cheering as the women were
introduced.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very proud of both the men and women. They are true
ambassadors in every way,'' said Wayne Locust, director of
admissions. ''They represent the university in the light that we
want them to represent us.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, hundreds of fans greeted the team at Bradley
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Ginnie Christiansen, who on Sunday was battling a very real,
101-degree fever, stood in the rain to celebrate the homecoming.
She and her daughter find the Huskies ''truly inspiring,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They bring more joy than anything else,'' said her daughter,
29-year-old Traci Christiansen. ''They are so phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Gampel rally, the team was presented with NCAA trophy and
the Women's Coaches Basketball Association trophy. Auriemma
accepted his AP Coach of the Year award.
</P>
<P>
   ''You all can take a little bit of satisfaction for taking these
kids to where they want to be,'' Auriemma told the crowd. ''Not
everybody gets to accomplish their dreams. We're the lucky ones.
</P>
<P>
   ''(Sunday) night we won a lot of awards, a lot of accolades and
a lot of honors,'' said Auriemma. ''But the honor that we have is
to coach these guys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
