<HEADLINE> Colonel charged with ignoring wife's drug scheme  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A U.S. Army colonel commanding the military's
anti-drug operation in Colombia knew his wife was laundering money
but failed to turn her in, federal prosecutors have alleged.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter written Monday to a Brooklyn federal judge,
prosecutors revealed that Col. James Hiett faces criminal charges
of ignoring a felony committed by his wife, Laurie Hiett. The
charge carries a maximum sentence of 3 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Hiett, 36, pleaded guilty to drug conspiracy charges in
January, saying she shipped packages containing $700,000 worth of
drugs to New York City. She also admitted traveling to New York to
collect the illicit proceeds to take back to Colombia -- an act
falling under the legal definition of money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, she told reporters she purposely kept her husband
in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   ''At one point, he may have asked me why I was going to New
York,'' she said. ''I just told him, 'Don't ask me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors refused to detail the case against the colonel. His
attorney, Abraham Clott, did not return a telephone call.
</P>
<P>
   Army spokesman Harvey Perritt said that James Hiett, 48, a
24-year veteran, remains on active duty at Fort Monroe, in Hampton,
Va., where he was transferred after allegations arose against his
wife. Military officials would not comment further on the case.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation by the Army Criminal Investigation Division in
Panama had cleared Hiett, saying he had ''no prior knowledge'' of
his wife's crimes. Brooklyn prosecutors, meanwhile, had insisted
their investigation was not over.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Hiett, an admitted cocaine addict, surrendered to
authorities last August after they intercepted two 1.2-kilo
packages of heroin that she allegedly mailed to Queens and
Manhattan from a post office at the U.S. Embassy in Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   The parcels had her return address. But she claimed that she
sent them for Jorge Ayala, a civilian driver for U.S. military
commanders in Colombia, and that they contained books, candy,
coffee and Colombian artifacts. She pleaded innocent and was freed
on bond.
</P>
<P>
   One of her co-defendants, Hernan Arcila, 54, pleaded guilty on
Jan. 5 to drug conspiracy, admitting that he accepted shipments
from Colombia at his Queens address. Ayala, who also was named in a
13-count indictment, was arrested in Bogota in February, and his
extradition is pending, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of her plea, Laurie Hiett told a federal magistrate she
shipped six packages from Bogota to New York City, believing they
contained cocaine. Tests on the two seized shipments revealed they
were heroin.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant also described flying to New York City two times
to pick up cash. Assistant U.S. Attorney Lee Dunst said the woman
once took another trip to Miami carrying a half-kilo of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Still free on bond, Laurie Hiett faces up to nine years in
prison at sentencing April 28. Her husband is to enter his plea on
April 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
