<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defense claims accused killer was with victim night before wedding  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The man accused of killing Gladys Ricart on her
wedding day was her registered husband, his defense team said.
</P>
<P>
   Agustin Garcia, 47, claims to have spent the previous evening
with the woman he's charged with shooting to death.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, of North Bergen, N.J., is accused of killing Ricart, 39,
of Ridgefield, N.J., on Sept. 26, 1999, just as she prepared to
marry another man.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia is jailed on $5 million bail. His attorneys claim he knew
nothing about the wedding until he walked in on it and found Ricart
in a wedding gown.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to debunk the notion that Garcia was stalking Ms.
Ricart,'' attorney Fernando Oliver said Monday at a news conference
at a Manhattan law office.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver described Garcia's involvement with Ricart as ''an
ongoing, loving relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   As to whether Ricart ''was living a double life or not, it
certainly appears from the course of the investigation that she
was,'' Oliver said.
</P>
<P>
   A former FBI agent hired by the defense to investigate the case,
Maurice Roussell, said four witnesses saw Garcia and Ricart
together in North Bergen, N.J., the day before the shooting -- at 6
p.m., 8 p.m. and 10 p.m. and then again at 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ricart's sister has contended that a videotape showing the pair
at a Pathmark at 2 a.m. the day of the shooting only proved that
Garcia was following her.
</P>
<P>
   Roussell, the former FBI agent, said Garcia and Ricart had also
''registered as husband and wife'' in 1997 on the membership roster
of a church they continued to attend until shortly before the
shooting. He acknowledged that they were not legally married, and
he would not say where the church was.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, the lawyer, and Roussell also said that in August,
Garcia had discussed buying Ricart a new car as a wedding gift for
marrying him.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver said he had no evidence that Ricart was afraid of Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know why somebody would be showing affections in
public if they're in fear of somebody else,'' Oliver said. ''Dozens
of witnesses we have place them together consistently in May, June,
August and September. In many occasions they're introduced as
husband and wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver suggested a wide range of defense theories, from
depicting the shooting an accident or self-defense during a
scuffle, to an act committed in the heat of passion, which would
constitute manslaughter as opposed to premeditated murder.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney also said Garcia had provided a $50,000 down
payment for Ricart's home and was giving her $500 a week for the
mortgage. Oliver said the pair had lived together between 1992 and
1995 but were living apart because Ricart did not want to care for
Garcia's children.
</P>
<P>
   As for reports that Garcia wore a tuxedo to fake his way into
the wedding, Oliver said he was dressed up because he was scheduled
to speak that evening at an art opening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
