<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Long Island congressman fuels talk of possible Senate run  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAY SHORE, N.Y. (AP) -- Rick Lazio knows there are a lot of
people who love the idea that the U.S. Senate race between Hillary
Rodham Clinton and Rudolph Giuliani is shaping up as a
personality-driven contest.
</P>
<P>
   ''They think it's fun and entertaining and it sells copy,'' the
Long Island congressman said Monday. ''But it's not good for the
people of New York, and they don't have to live with the
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who last summer toyed with the idea of challenging
Giuliani for the GOP nomination, has resurrected the notion that he
may be a better candidate than the New York City mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not trying to be difficult, I am not trying to be
defiant,'' Lazio said at a hastily called press conference at his
district office. ''I am simply trying to be what I think is a good
public servant and good Republican in saying I think we have had a
wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   As he did during a national television appearance on Sunday,
Lazio noted that Giuliani is not likely to receive the backing of
the Conservative Party. No Republican has won statewide office
without Conservative Party support since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that Republicans need to join with the Conservative
Party in order to have a winning combination,'' Lazio said. ''I
think the landscape has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio had been an active contender for the GOP nomination until
last August, when he yielded to the wishes of Gov. George Pataki
and delayed an official announcement of his candidacy. He said
Monday that he backed off last summer out of respect for the
governor and that if Pataki asked him again not to run, he would
likely agree.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki spokesman Mike McKeon said Monday that ''the governor
strongly supports Mayor Giuliani and believes he is the best
candidate to defeat Hillary Clinton in November, and he would urge
Congressman Lazio and all Republicans to get behind the mayor's
candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said he had not spoken directly with the governor but
expected that conversation would take place soon. He repeated that
he has no intention of running for the Senate as the Conservative
or any other third-party candidate but would accept Conservative
backing if he won the GOP nod.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has set no timetable for deciding but noted that
Conservative James Buckley didn't enter the U.S. Senate race in
1970 until June and still won. He conceded his campaign warchest is
dwarfed by those of both Clinton and Giuliani, but he didn't think
it would be difficult to ''raise a lot of money quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has raised $19 million for the race to Clinton's $12
million. Lazio raised about $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also said he had no fears that a GOP primary fight might
weaken the winner for a November race against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''Primaries aren't inherently bad,'' he said. ''The key to a
good primary, a constructive primary, is to engage on the issues
and for it not to be derogatory; not for us to get down in the
mud.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor seemed unconcerned about a possible primary challenge
during a City Hall press conference on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The last poll I saw we were ahead of the first lady, Mrs.
Clinton, by 3 percent and we were ahead of him by 120 percent, I
think,'' Giuliani said. ''If Congressman Lazio wants to run, he
should.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
