<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial adviser to the stars allegedly made pitch that was all anact  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A Manhattan financial adviser counted some of
Hollywood's top young celebrities, including Leonardo DiCaprio and
Ben Affleck, among his clients even as he swindled customers who
trusted him to make safe investments, federal prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White said the case demonstrated that ''no
one is immune from any kind of scheme, securities or otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Actors DiCaprio, Affleck and Matt Damon and singer Alanis
Morrisette were some of the rich and famous clients of Dana
Giacchetto, 37, a New Yorker accused of diverting $20 million from
clients. Prosecutors say the band Phish and its manager may have
lost as much as $5 million to Giacchetto.
</P>
<P>
   The financial adviser also is accused of failing to return at
least $4 million maneuvered through the accounts in his investment
business, The Cassandra Group, which he ran from a loft in the
city's SoHo section.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors brought criminal securities charges against
Giacchetto in U.S. District Court in Manhattan on Monday while the
Securities and Exchange Commission charged him in a civil lawsuit
and obtained a freeze of his assets. They alleged that the
financial security Giacchetto promised his clients was all an act.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal and civil actions threaten Giacchetto's lifestyle,
which has included an increasing share in his clients' spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   An article in April's issue of Vanity Fair noted that Giacchetto
had won the trust of some of Hollywood's biggest stars, such as
Cameron Diaz, Courtney Cox Arquette and R.E.M. singer Michael
Stipe.
</P>
<P>
   And a story published in The New York Times Magazine last May
described an interview in Giacchetto's loft in which he introduced
two large white birds.
</P>
<P>
   ''That one's for Leo,'' he told the writer. ''And that one's
mine.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, as Giacchetto's financial world seemed to collapse,
he came across as part of the jet set. His lawyer, Andrew Levander,
told Judge Lawrence McKenna that his client was returning from a
trip abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Outside court, Levander said he couldn't comment further because
he had not yet had a chance to read the court papers or talk to his
client.
</P>
<P>
   He said Giacchetto, who was expected back in New York today,
sent a letter to his customers a week ago telling them he was
getting out of the investment business.
</P>
<P>
   As for his client's next move, Levander said to ''stay tuned.''
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, prosecutors and the SEC said Giacchetto stole
from clients to pay for his apartment, hotels, travel, dining and
entertainment and sometimes lent money to third parties, including
$12,000 to a law enforcement officer for a down payment on a
Mercedes Benz. Giacchetto is also accused of using money belonging
to entertainment's A-list to make unauthorized donations such as
$90,000 to the New York Arts Academy and $5,000 to the New York
Police Scholarship Fund.
</P>
<P>
   According to the SEC, Giacchetto failed to tell clients he was
suffering severe financial difficulties that threatened his ability
to pay them back.
</P>
<P>
   Company literature promised a ''conservative investment
strategy'' focused on large companies, but Giacchetto ''knowingly
or recklessly'' deposited more than $20 million of his clients'
money in bank accounts permitting him to pay the expenses of his
business and himself, the SEC said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission accused Giacchetto of issuing fake portfolio
statements or other false documents to clients who wanted proof of
their purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors charged Giacchetto with securities fraud,
fraud and making false statements to the SEC. They said in court
papers that he signed an affidavit in December admitting he
misappropriated $3.9 million from Phish and another $968,900 from
accounts held by the band's manager.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Giacchetto faces a maximum of 10 years in prison
and $1 million or twice the gross gain or loss resulting from the
crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
