<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 02:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. County Janitors Begin Strike  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HARRIGAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Thousands of janitors seeking higher pay went
on strike Monday, a walkout that could affect about 70 percent of
the commercial office space in Los Angeles County.
</P>
<P>
   Contracts between 18 cleaning contractors and 8,500 janitors
expired Friday night. Both sides said they were so far apart that
further negotiations would be pointless.
</P>
<P>
   About 3,000 union members authorized the strike Monday, an
action that could be a precursor to nationwide disruptions as
contracts covering 100,000 janitors expire in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a nationwide movement of the poorest and most
exploited workers,'' said Stephen Lerner, director of the building
services division for the Service Employees International Union.
</P>
<P>
   Union Local 1877 planned a ''rolling strike'' in which members
walked off their jobs in one downtown building after another, union
representative Blanca Gallegos said.
</P>
<P>
   ''By the end of the week, the entire county will be impacted,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Unionized janitors make an average of $6.90 an hour and are
demanding a $1-an-hour pay increase each of the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   During a rally following the strike vote, janitors received
support from state Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa -- a
candidate for Los Angeles mayor -- and Los Angeles County Supervisor
Zev Yaroslavsky, who said the janitors' wages amount to ''virtual
slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday night, groups of janitors demonstrated around
downtown, marching, shouting and waving picket signs. The largest
appeared to involve about 60 people. In one instance, television
footage showed police briefly shoving a group of picketers.
</P>
<P>
   No protesters were arrested, however.
</P>
<P>
   Contractors said they doubled their offer Friday. It included
two 40 cents-per-hour boosts in the second and third years. The
union said the majority of members would have had their wages
frozen in the first year, with only downtown and Century City
workers getting a 50-cent raise the first year.
</P>
<P>
   The rejected contract offer represented an 18 percent pay
increase by the third year, said Dick Davis, chief negotiator for
the companies.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's double the national average of wage increases,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The strike will have minimal effect on many buildings because
contractors have hired temporary workers, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
