<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 03:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nationl Zoo Raises $8M for Pandas  </HEADLINE>
By CARL HARTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Completion of a major addition to the Air and
Space Museum is one of the projects the new head of the Smithsonian
Institution has in mind for $1 billion he is trying to raise in
donations. Most of an estimated $8 million needed to bring a pair
of pandas to the National Zoo has already been raised, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence M. Small said the $1 billion also will pay for
completion of the new Museum of American Indian and refurbishing of
the old Patent Office which houses the Museum of American Art and
the National Portrait Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   These days, he said, it's not so much a matter of setting goals
and collecting smaller contributions, but of waiting for the big
donations that have become more common in recent years -- tens and
even hundreds of millions at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Small said Monday in an interview with reporters and
editors of the Associated Press that China in the future likely
will rent pandas to foreign countries, not loan them or give them
away like Hsing-Hsing, a gift to America after President Nixon's
visit to China in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   He said it would probably cost an estimated $8 million to rent a
new pair of pandas from China for 10 years. Any offspring, he said,
could be kept though they would still belong to the Chinese
government. But he said he believed it would take protracted
negotiations to work out the details.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a team over there now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, panda lovers concerned about the remains of the
zoo's last giant panda, Hsing-Hsing, who died in November, can also
relax. His remains will not be stuffed for display.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are too many people who care,'' Small said. ''They felt
the panda was part of their lives. To say you were going to display
it was just not a smart thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Small was especially enthusiastic about prospects for the
addition to the Air and Space Museum -- the world's most visited --
due to open in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have what I think will probably be the most spectacular
museum interior in the history of the world,'' he said. ''We have a
176{ acre site. ... This is going to be two-and-a-half football
fields long, and 10 stories high. It's going to have 178 airplanes
inside the one room.''
</P>
<P>
   Small also sees great significance in the American Indian
museum.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a museum that's been developed with the total support of
hundreds of American Indian tribes and it will give the nation ...
a place of reconcilement for an issue that's been a troubling one
in American history,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since he took over the Smithsonian's 16 museums and zoo in
January, Small has been working to spread more of the 141 million
objects it owns to affiliates all over the 50 states. Only about 2
percent of the objects are now on display, and almost all those in
Washington. Many have never been seen by the public.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, there are 25 suits of Samurai armor than
American ships brought back when they opened Japan to trade before
the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   ''Museums are hot,'' he said. ''Culture is hot. People want more
than just entertainment. They want to have enriched experiences,
and they're getting used to have (private) enterprise go after that
and improve their experiences. So you go to Starbucks for coffee
and you pay 10 times more for coffee than you might have done 15
years ago, but you want to be in an environment that stimulates
you.''
</P>
<P>
   He estimated that there are 8,500 to 10,000 museums of all kinds
in the United States, and only 29 affiliated with the Smithsonian.
The affiliates can enrich their own collections with supplements
from Washington, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you went to Bisbee, Arizona, for instance, they have a
museum of mining,'' he said. ''They had everything but the kind of
ore that came out of the mines. Their mines were totally played
out, so they had mining equipment. We sent them the ore.''
</P>
<P>
   Small pointed out that the Northeast is not an area of growing
population. The West and Southwest are.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the things can't be seen by the American public, what good
are they?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   He said museums in the rest of the country are eager to display
the authentic materials that the Smithsonian has.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't just invent something of George Washington's or
Thomas Jefferson's,'' he said, ''you either have it or you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   But he believes borrowing museums should not be ''little
Smithsonians.'' The Smithsonian museums have been largely financed
by taxpayers' money and he wants admission to remain free, but
others have different degrees of public and private ownership and
the Smithsonian does not want to dictate what their charges should
be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 0326 </TRAILER>
