<HEADLINE> Amsterdam Takes 'Doo' Measure  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- It's a dirty job, but someone's
got to do it.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest attempt to rid the streets of the Dutch capital of
dog excrement, city officials are offering to pay people $4.30 an
hour to collect dog droppings in their neighborhoods, a spokesman
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   There is an ongoing debate about how to solve the messy problem
in the Netherlands, where the population of nearly 16 million owns
1.4 million dogs and 2.5 million cats.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier initiatives have included pooper scooper laws and
cleanup stations, equipped with plastic bag dispensers and garbage
cans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 0917 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000404.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 09:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stock Prices Close Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks closed moderately lower today, falling
from a three-year high, amid political uncertainty in Japan. The
dollar edged higher against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 132.06 points,
or 0.64 percent, to close at 20,594.93 on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
On Monday, the average closed up 389.67 points, or 1.92 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 105.06 yen in late trading on the Tokyo
foreign exchange market, up 0.20 yen from Monday and also above its
late New York level Monday of 104.85 yen.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock exchange, traders said investors remained cautious
amid expectations of the resignation of the cabinet of Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi, who remains in a coma after suffering a
stroke. The resignations came at an emergency cabinet meeting after
markets closed.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshiro Mori, secretary-general of the Liberal Democratic Party,
is viewed as the front-runner to succeed Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
   With Obuchi's ruling party firmly in control, the changes were
not expected to lead to any significant alterations in the nation's
basic political or economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   But acting Prime Minister Mikio Aoki convened an emergency
Cabinet meeting to accept the resignations because it had become
clear Obuchi would not be able to resume his duties. ''We cannot
allow a political vacuum to form,'' Aoki said in announcing the
resignations.
</P>
<P>
   Prices started lower today on profit-taking following recent
gains. Investors in Tokyo were also discouraged by steep declines
Monday in U.S. high technology stocks on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section fell 18.16 points, or 1.05 percent, to close at
1,714.29. The TOPIX closed up 26.51 points, or 1.55 percent, the
day before.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite index plunged 349.15 points
to close at 4,223.68. It was the Nasdaq's worst one-day point drop
in history, surpassing a 229-point fall on Jan. 4, and its
fifth-biggest daily percentage decline. But the Dow industrials
soared.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar was higher against the yen in
narrow trading amid continued concern of another central bank
intervention to stem any drop by the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese importers and U.S. and Canadian banks were among early
players who bought the greenback after Finance Minister Kiichi
Miyazawa reiterated his determination to be ready to take action
against the yen's excessive upsurge.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said today that Japan is ready
to take necessary action to contain disruptive foreign exchange
moves.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Bank of Japan intervened in the market to weaken
the yen, whose recent rise has alarmed Japanese financial planners.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese finance authorities have intervened several times this
year to stem gains by the yen, which make Japanese exports more
expensive overseas, and thus less competitive.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 100.33 yen, up from
100.14 yen late Monday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell
to 1.7800 percent from Monday's finish of 1.8050 percent. Its price
rose 0.22 point to 101.03.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
