<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down 9.01; Dow Up 138.60  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened mixed today, with battered
technology stocks falling once again and continuing the dramatic
decline of the Nasdaq composite index.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq was down
9.01 to 4,214.67, failing to mount even a modest recovery from its
349-point swoon yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 138.60 at 11,360.53,
extending Monday's 300-point gain.
</P>
<P>
   Broader indicators were slightly higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 12.94 at 1,518.91, nearing its March 24 closing
record of 1,527.46.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks tumbled even as the catalyst for their rout
yesterday -- Microsoft -- stabilized somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   After plunging 15] to 90~ yesterday, Microsoft slipped just 3/16
to 90 11/16 today. After the close of trading yesterday, a federal
judge ruled the company violated U.S. antitrust laws by mounting a
''deliberate assault'' on competition in the Internet browser
market. The ruling could lead to drastic punishment, including a
breakup.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller technology shares, which have fallen prey to investors'
worries that their prices ran up too quickly in recent months, slid
once more today.
</P>
<P>
   Veritas Software fell 10| to 100~, Exodus Communications fell 4
37/64 to 118 15/64 and Amazon.com fell 2 5/16 to 61\.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq, which rose nearly 86 percent in 1999, started out
the year at the same extraordinary velocity, rising 24 percent from
the close of 1999 to March 10. But since closing at a record
5,048.62 on March 10, the index has fallen 16.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investors have returned to blue-chip stocks. Today,
DuPont rose 2\ to 59 13/16 and Merck rose 2 11/16 to 69 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 145.30 million
shares, ahead of Monday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 3.93 to 512.11.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.6 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's Xetra DAX index was up 1.4 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.5 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
up 1.5 percent.
</P>
