</P>
<P>
   Gates Pledges To Fight Ruling
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates is vowing to
fight a federal court decision that his company violated U.S.
antitrust laws by mounting a ''deliberate assault'' on competition
in the Internet browser market. The ruling could lead to drastic
punishment, including the breakup of one of the world's major
corporations. The judge issued his ruling Monday after the stock
market closed, but word that it was coming caused Microsoft stock
to drop by more than $15 a share. It declined a fraction this
morning. Gates has promised to appeal, and said he feels the
company has a strong case. He said the court ruling ''...turns on
its head the reality that consumers know: That our software has
helped make PCs accessible and more affordable to millions of
Americans.'' Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., chairman of the Senate
Commerce Committee, said on NBC's ''Today'' that he will hold
hearings on the case.
</P>
<P>
   German Co. To Bid on Thomson Travel
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Germany's C&AMP;N Touristic AG plans to make a cash
offer $2.08 billion for Thomson Travel PLC, Britain's biggest
chartered tour operator. Thomson's board met today to consider the
announcement from C&AMP;N, a joint venture between Kardstadt-Quelle AG
and Deutsche Lufthansa AG, and said it would advise shareholders as
soon as possible of its recommendation. The German company,
Europe's third-largest tour business, already owns 2.9 percent of
Thomson stock. C&AMP;N cited Thomson's poor financial performance in
disclosing earlier in the day that it plans to make a cash offer of
130 pence, or $2.08, a share that would value Thomson at $2.08
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Most Asian Markets Close Lower
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed lower today on
the back of an overnight tumble in the Nasdaq composite index. The
Japanese 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 132.06 points, or 0.64
percent, to close at 20,594.93. Singapore stocks also closed lower
as the slump in the Nasdaq led to selling in local technology
shares, dealers said. The Straits Times Index fell 13.14 points, or
0.6 percent, to 2,058.54. Markets in Taiwan, Hong Kong and Jakarta
were closed for holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Recess Called in Northwest Talks
</P>
<P>
   EAGAN, Minn. (AP) -- Federal mediators have called a recess in
talks between Northwest Airlines and its flight attendants' union.
No further negotiations were scheduled. However, Teamsters Local
2000 President Billie Davenport said yesterday she was hopeful
talks will resume later this month. Davenport said the union and
the airline are divided on pay, retirement and domestic partner
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Sega Unveiling Plan For Web Access
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Realizing online gaming will play a big role in
the future of the video-game market, Sega Enterprises Ltd. is
stepping up its Web presence with the launch of a new Sega-branded
Internet service provider this fall. Sega is expected to unveil
today its plans for a new online entertainment company that
includes SegaNet, a high-speed Internet service provider with
multiplayer gaming as well as chat capabilities and information
about its video games. The company is the first of the video-game
manufacturers to give a defined blueprint of how it will use the
Internet to enhance playtime.
</P>
<P>
   Renault, Samsung Extend Their Talks
</P>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- French carmaker Renault SA and
creditors of Samsung Motors Inc. agreed today to extend their talks
on a plan to rescue the bankrupt Korean carmaker, bank officials
said. They reported no significant progress in the latest round of
talks but they agreed to continue discussions for 15 more days,
said an official at Hanvit Bank, Samsung's main creditor. Today had
been the deadline for the discussions. The Hanvit official,
speaking on customary condition of anonymity, declined to give
further details except that the sides will meet again later this
week.
</P>
<P>
   March Is Mixed for Automakers
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Gas prices and higher interest rates did little
to dampen Americans' demand for new cars and trucks in March, as
nearly all major automakers reported sales gains. Ford Motor Co.
said yesterday that its sales for the month jumped, while General
Motors Corp. reported flat results and the Chrysler half of
DaimlerChrysler AG reported a small gain. Many foreign automakers
reported larger sales increases. Ford said its overall sales were
up 10 percent, with car sales up 19 percent and truck sales up 5
percent. The spike in car sales came mostly from newer models: the
redesigned Ford Taurus/Mercury Sable sedan, the Ford Focus compact
cars and the Lincoln LS sedan.
</P>
<P>
   Economic Reports
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Economic reports:
</P>
