<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down 145.34; Dow Up 134.96  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today, with battered
technology stocks falling once again and continuing the dramatic
decline of the Nasdaq composite index.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq was down 145.34 to
4,078.34, failing to mount even a modest recovery from its
349-point swoon on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 134.96 at 11,356.89,
extending Monday's 300-point gain.
</P>
<P>
   Broader indicators were slightly higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 2.82 at 1,508.79.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks tumbled as the catalyst for their rout on
Monday -- Microsoft -- slipped again.
</P>
<P>
   After plunging 15] to 90~ on Monday, Microsoft fell another 2
7/16 to 88 7/16 today. After the close of trading Monday, a federal
judge ruled the company violated U.S. antitrust laws by mounting a
''deliberate assault'' on competition in the Internet browser
market. The ruling could lead to drastic punishment, including a
breakup.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller technology shares, which have fallen prey to investors'
worries that their prices ran up too quickly in recent months, slid
once more today, lending credibility to analysts' belief that
Microsoft wasn't solely responsible for the technology selloff
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''In hindsight, technology shares had been ripe for a further
correction,'' said Scott J. Brown, chief economist at Raymond James
&AMP; Associates in St. Petersburg, Fla. ''The Microsoft news merely
provided a handy excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Veritas Software fell 11 1/16 to 100 7/16, Exodus
Communications fell 15 7/16 to 107] and JDS Uniphase fell 11| to
100.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq, which rose nearly 86 percent in 1999, started out
the year at the same extraordinary velocity, rising 24 percent from
the close of 1999 to March 10. But since closing at a record
5,048.62 on March 10, the index has fallen 16.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investors have returned to blue-chip stocks. Today,
DuPont rose 2 11/16 to 60\ and Merck rose 2 5/16 to 69 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow got a boost from the Conference Board's Index of Leading
Economic Indicators, which fell 0.3 percent in February, the
biggest monthly drop in more than four years. The decline in the
index, a gauge of future U.S. economic activity, suggested that
rising interest rates have begun to take a toll.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve policymakers have raised rates five times since
last June to prevent the fast-growing economy from giving rise to
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market has been dying for any sign of potential slowdown
and I guess they are taking this as that,'' said David Orr, chief
economist at First Union Corp. in Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 366.78 million
shares, ahead of Monday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 12.66 to
503.38.
</P>
<P>
