<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Makes Telecom Accusations  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER, AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration today accused
Mexico and seven other nations of erecting unfair barriers to keep
American telecommunication companies out of their markets.
</P>
<P>
   The administration set deadlines for later this year for the
barriers to be removed and raised the prospect that cases would be
brought to the World Trade Organization if the most objectionable
barriers are not dealt with.
</P>
<P>
   The other nations named in the annual review of
telecommunication practices were Germany, South Africa, Britain,
Canada, Peru, Israel and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the administration issued a separate report accusing
Japan of violating its WTO commitments by refusing to lower high
interconnection fees that U.S. telecommunication companies complain
are designed to keep them out of the Japanese market.
</P>
<P>
   The administration today set a deadline of July 28 for resolving
both the Japanese case and a separate case against Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ''In Mexico, it appears that progress towards a level playing
field for telecommunications carriers now is stalled,'' U.S. Trade
Representative Charlene Barshefsky said. ''I view the situation in
Mexico as extremely serious. The United States will determine by
July 28 whether additional action, including in the WTO, would be
appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The complaint against Mexico was brought by a group of U.S.
companies including AT&AMP;T and MCI Worldcom. The U.S. companies
contend that the Mexican government and the nation's largest
telephone company, Telmex, have engaged in unfair practices aimed
at restricting access by foreign competitors to the Mexican market.
</P>
<P>
   Other review deadlines set by the administration today included
June 15 for Germany, South Africa and Britain, and Oct. 2 for
Canada and Peru.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the administration said it would also be watching
to see that Israel lives up to commitments to terminate
objectionable telephone barriers by Dec. 31, 2001, and to see that
Taiwan carries forward with the elimination of certain exclusive
licensing arrangements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 1139 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000404.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Freeh Denies Job-Hunting Reports  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A senior FBI official denied a published
report that FBI Director Louis Freeh is job-hunting and expects to
leave office before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ''He hasn't decided when he's leaving,'' the senior official
said of the 51-year-old FBI chief whose tenured term runs through
2003.
</P>
<P>
   ''For some time he said he wouldn't leave any sooner than the
end of the year, and everyone here expects him to stay longer than
that,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   This official, who spoke Monday night on condition of anonymity,
said Freeh has made commitments to give speeches and make
appearances as FBI director through the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Freeh does not want a change in the FBI
directorship to be linked to a change in U.S. presidential
administrations, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who appointed Freeh, but whose relations with
the bureau chief have soured, leaves office early next year. The
tenured term was designed by Congress to make the FBI director
independent of any one White House administration. Freeh does not
want to undermine that, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post reported in today's editions that
intermediaries for Freeh have been sounding out legal and financial
services firms here and elsewhere on his behalf, telling them Freeh
is expected to leave office in the last several months of this
year.
</P>
<P>
   But the senior official said, ''Freeh has not approached any
companies seeking employment nor has he authorized any others to do
so on his behalf.''
</P>
<P>
   This official said Freeh reiterated that to him on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After 25 years as a public servant -- FBI agent, federal
prosecutor, federal judge and FBI director -- Freeh faces some
financial difficulty in paying college tuition for his six boys.
</P>
<P>
   As FBI director, Freeh makes $141,300 annually. The senior
official said Freeh has declined more than one offer of a legal job
paying more than $1 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The senior official said he understood ''one of Freeh's friends
trying to look out for him'' was making unauthorized inquiries
about whether companies would be interested in hiring Freeh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 1140 </TRAILER>
