<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT  </HEADLINE>
By L. ANNE NEWELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The state's highest court this morning ruled
that the state Legislature properly rescinded New York City's tax
on commuters living in New York last year, and the judges also said
the tax cannot be imposed on residents of other states.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by the state Court of Appeals will cost the city $360
million a year. About 500,000 people live in New York state and
commute to jobs in the city and about 300,000 others who work in
the city live in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for New York City argued the tax was illegally rescinded
by the state Legislature and governor in May 1999 without the New
York City Council asking Albany to do so in a ''home rule''
message.
</P>
<P>
   But the Court of Appeals unanimously said that no such message
was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although the State appropriately authorized the city to
implement the commuter tax, it never ceded its taxing authority to
the city,'' wrote Judge Richard Wesley.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Connecticut and New Jersey residents, as well as the
state of Connecticut, argued that since the tax was being
eliminated for New York state residents, it violated the federal
Constitution to impose it on people from Connecticut and New Jersey
who work in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ''The language of the statute plainly and frankly discriminates
against nonresidents,'' Wesley wrote. ''There is little doubt but
that the discrimination is so great that both its purpose and
effect are exclusionary.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Joy Lee, a Manhattan attorney who represented two
commuters from New Jersey, praised the decision. ''It's been
obvious from the start it's the right answer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee also lauded the timing of the decision, since many commuters
still have time to change their income tax returns to reflect the
change in law.
</P>
<P>
   It was no surprise to legislators that the out-of-state portion
of the law was declared unconstitutional. When lawmakers approved
the tax rescinder, they included a ''poison pill'' provision that
said that if part of the law was found unconstitutional, the repeal
of the commuter tax would appeal to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   New York City also argued that the tax rescinder was improper
because its passage was designed to win votes in a hotly contested
special election last spring for a state Senate seat in New York's
northern suburbs. That election was won by Thomas Morahan, a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals said it would put it on a ''slippery and
dangerous slope'' to make judgments about the legality of laws
based on the political motivation of Legislatures and governors.
</P>
<P>
   ''The vortex of the legislative process is often the
intersection of politics and policy,'' wrote Wesley, himself a
former Republican state assemblyman.
</P>
<P>
   Lorna Goodman, a spokeswoman for New York City's corporation
counsel, said city officials were ''extremely disappointed'' by the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think the Legislature acted in a very punitive way toward
New York City,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said she hopes the decision is the end of the case, but
noted that since the Court of Appeals based its decision on the
federal Constitution, New York City could appeal to the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hopefully they won't, because it's not the right thing for New
York,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature approved the commuter tax rescinder on May 17,
1999, and Gov. George Pataki signed it into law 10 days later.
</P>
<P>
   The city stopped collecting the tax from its residents then, but
continued collecting it from out-of-state commuters throughout the
appeal process.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals heard the various challenges to the
commuter tax rescinder at the same time and ruled on them in one
decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
