<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Below 4,000; Dow Up 1.86  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Battered technology stocks dropped sharply again
Tuesday, pulling the Nasdaq composite index below 4,000 for the
first time in two months.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq was down 297.02, or
by 7 percent, at 3,926.66. The technology-dominated index last
traded below 4,000 on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's selloff came a day after the index suffered through a
single-day record drop of 349.15 points, a decline of 7.6 percent.
The technology-focused average now was down 22.2 percent from its
record 5048.62 of March 10 and below where it began the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, which soared 300 points
Monday, was up just 1.86 at 11,223.79 at midday.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks tumbled as the catalyst for their rout on
Monday -- Microsoft -- slipped again.
</P>
<P>
   After plunging more than $15 on Monday, Microsoft fell $2.50 to
$88.38 Tuesday morning. After Monday's trading session, a federal
judge ruled the company violated U.S. antitrust laws by mounting a
''deliberate assault'' on competition in the Internet browser
market. The ruling could lead to drastic punishment, including a
breakup.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller technology shares, which have fallen prey to investors'
worries that their prices ran up too quickly in recent months, slid
once more Tuesday, lending credibility to analysts' belief that
Microsoft wasn't solely responsible for the technology selloff
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's precipitous drop wiped out its spectacular gains
for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ''In hindsight, technology shares had been ripe for a further
correction,'' said Scott J. Brown, chief economist at Raymond James
&AMP; Associates in St. Petersburg, Fla. ''The Microsoft news merely
provided a handy excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
