<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Mostly Up; Gold Down  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was mainly higher against most
other major currencies in late European trading today. Gold prices
were lower.
</P>
<P>
   The euro was quoted at 95.57 cents in late European trading,
down from $0.9566 Monday. Later, in midday trading in New York, the
euro traded at 95.58 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with Monday, included
105.38 Japanese yen, up from 104.63; 1.6550 Swiss francs, down from
1.6554; 1.4523 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4522.
</P>
<P>
   The British pound was quoted at $1.5954, down from $1.5958.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 104.43 yen, and
the pound was worth $1.5952.
</P>
<P>
   Based on euro rates, the dollar is worth 2.0463 German marks, up
from 2.0431; 6.8629 French francs, up from 6.8522; 2.3049 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.3022; 2,025.81 Italian lire, up from 2,022.64.
</P>
<P>
   Gold closed in London at $276.30 bid per troy ounce, down from
$278.00 Monday. In Zurich the bid price was $276.15, down from
$277.35.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong, gold and stock markets were closed Tuesday for a
public holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Silver closed in London at $5.03 bid per troy ounce, up from
$5.01.
</P>
</TEXT>
