<HEADLINE> Rain Likely; Grains, Soybeans Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures declined in early
dealings today on the Chicago Board of Trade, pressured by rainy
forecasts for the central United States.
</P>
<P>
   While the Midwest is expected to remain dry for most of this
week, new forecasts for rain Friday and Saturday helped send prices
lower in a slide that also was attributed in part to carryover from
Monday's weak finish.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat opened higher but then retreated as investors concluded
that frosty weather in part of the winter wheat belt overnight
won't necessarily harm the crop.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture reported dry soil conditions
in Illinois and Iowa that could hinder development of the nation's
leading crop -- corn. But investors have already long factored that
into the price, and corn fell victim today to the across-the-board
decline in agricultural commodities.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for May delivery fell 1} cent to $2.56 a bushel; May corn
fell 1} cent to $2.32{ a bushel; July oats fell { cent to $1.20{ a
bushel; May soybeans fell 2} cents to $5.43} a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef and pork futures retreated in early trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle fell .03 cent to 69.12 cents a pound; May
feeder cattle fell .05 cent to 83.85 cents a pound; June lean hogs
fell .45 cent to 72.70 cents a pound; May pork bellies fell .65
cent to 96.70 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
