<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boxers Punched In and Out of Ring  </HEADLINE>
By TED ANTHONY, AP National Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Most boxing films aren't about boxing, really.
''The Harder They Fall'' wasn't. ''Rocky'' wasn't. And neither is
''On the Ropes,'' a magnificent documentary about three young New
Yorkers trying to touch their dreams by giving and taking punches
for a living.
</P>
<P>
   Airing Tuesday at 9 p.m. EDT on The Learning Channel, ''On the
Ropes,'' an Oscar nominee for best documentary, is a sort of
pugilistic ''Hoop Dreams.'' It's set in the world of up-and-coming
amateur fighters who train at the New Bed-Stuy Boxing Center Inc.
in New York City's rough-and-tumble Bedford-Stuyvesant
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   There is George Walton, one of 15 children, a fast-moving,
ambitious young man being courted by promoters to turn pro. There
is Tyrene Manson, trying desperately to conquer her troubled home
life and be a successful fighter. There is Noel Santiago, a lanky
former drug addict and small-time robber who lost his father to
AIDS and sees boxing as his chance to finally excel.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is Harry Keitt, proprietor of the New Bed-Stuy
gym, a 40-ish man with an affable moon face who turned his
delinquent life around and dedicated it to helping young people
discipline themselves and succeed both in and out of the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know where I'd be if I didn't start boxing,'' Noel
says, and you get the feeling he speaks for all of them, including
Harry.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the sport, while omnipresent, is really only a bit player.
''It's not just about what it seems on the surface,'' says Brett
Morgen, who, with co-filmmaker Nanette Burstein, spent two years
with the four main characters.
</P>
<P>
   As with all good sports movies, ''On the Ropes'' is about life
itself -- about the tough battle to learn the tools like
self-discipline and commitment that produce success.
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour film is whittled down from hundreds of hours of
footage -- and, the filmmakers say, hundreds more hours spent just
hanging out with the four protagonists. The rapport between
subjects and filmmakers is so obvious that at times the
''performances'' are seamless enough to seem like acting.
</P>
<P>
   Tyrene is the most interesting of the young fighters. She is
trying to extricate herself from a house that includes her
drug-addled uncle, a young niece named Ebony whom she's trying to
protect, and -- as she tells it -- various crack-toting vagrants.
</P>
<P>
   As she trains for her dream, Tyrene is charged with possession
of cocaine with intent to sell it -- cocaine that was found when
police stormed the house and searched the room she shared with four
other people. She says the cocaine wasn't hers. And you believe
her.
</P>
<P>
   For Tyrene, the gym and its sparring opportunities offer escape.
''My world is crammed up in me,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The others are fascinating, too.
</P>
<P>
   Noel's tears stream after he takes a hard punch in the face and
loses a fight -- then he battles distractions and inertia as Harry
struggles to keep him on track. George's head swells a bit and he
cuts Harry loose when professional promoters come calling. Then
there's the action at the Golden Gloves tournament, New York's
showcase for young boxers hungry for victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to see how it feels like to be a winner,'' Noel says.
''I never felt like that before.''
</P>
<P>
   And, most interestingly, there's Harry. Harry Keitt is the kind
of character screenwriters dream of inventing. When he was younger,
he drifted from his boxing dream (which included a stint as
Muhammad Ali's sparring partner) and became addicted to crack. Then
he shot his cousin seven times with a .25 automatic, and did two
years in Sing-Sing and Attica for attempted murder.
</P>
<P>
   Now reformed and pushing 40, he uses his gym for athletic
interventions -- snagging kids before they are incorrigible, and
channeling their energy and rage into discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ''My day's over,'' he tells Noel between rounds of one fight.
''I'm trying to make my dream come through you.''
</P>
<P>
   As the film progresses into a natural story arc for each
protagonist, each faces a life challenge. Two of those challenges
are muted and subtle, as life tends to be. Tyrene's is more
dramatic, and the obstacles she faces edge into the closest thing
the film offers to preaching. But even that section is subtle and
never crosses the line to being shrill.
</P>
<P>
   The film ends in 1998. But The Learning Channel airing includes
a new, four-minute epilogue showing what became of the four. It
includes a surprise, so don't be fooled when the credits roll; stay
tuned.
</P>
<P>
   ''On the Ropes'' is documentary filmmaking at its best --
textured and relevant, subtle and genuine. Word has it the
filmmakers recently sold remake rights to Warner Bros. for some
sort of fictional version. It may make them money, but from an
artistic standpoint it's probably not worth it: Whatever they do,
it won't come near the purity of this.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in television ...
</P>
<P>
   'SOUTH PARK': When Cartman discovers that the Tooth Fairy is
paying a premium price for his lost baby teeth, he and his pals
seize the opportunity to make some easy cash. The little
entrepreneurs build a thriving business by appropriating teeth from
the less fortunate -- until they come face to face with Denver's Mob
Boss in the black-market tooth trade. Sink your teeth into this
proudly tasteless half-hour, the fourth season premiere of ''South
Park,'' airing Wednesday at 10 p.m. EDT on Comedy Central.
</P>
</TEXT>
