<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Tumbles 500; Dow Drops 475  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index plunged more than 500
points Tuesday, dropping 25 percent from its record high and
pulling the rest of the stock market into a broad-based decline.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq dropped into what some analysts consider a bear
market. It was down 513.83 at 3,814.95 in early afternoon trading.
Selling pressure was heavy, gathering momentum as the index smashed
through 4,000 for the first time since Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's selloff came a day after the index suffered through a
single-day record drop of 349.15 points, a decline of 7.6 percent.
The technology-focused average was down 23 percent from its record
5048.62 of March 10 and below where it began the year.
</P>
<P>
   A bear market is considered a sustained drop of more than 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, which soared 300 points
Monday, was down 475.53 at 10,764.40 in afternoon trading.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks tumbled as the catalyst for their rout on
Monday -- Microsoft -- slipped again.
</P>
<P>
   After plunging more than $15 on Monday, Microsoft more than $4
to $86.50 Tuesday afternoon. After Monday's trading session, a
federal judge ruled the company violated U.S. antitrust laws by
mounting a ''deliberate assault'' on competition in the Internet
browser market. The ruling could lead to drastic punishment,
including a breakup.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller technology shares, which have fallen prey to investors'
worries that their prices ran up too quickly in recent months, slid
once more Tuesday, lending credibility to analysts' belief that
Microsoft wasn't solely responsible for the technology selloff
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's precipitous drop wiped out its spectacular gains
for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ''In hindsight, technology shares had been ripe for a further
correction,'' said Scott J. Brown, chief economist at Raymond James
&AMP; Associates in St. Petersburg, Fla. ''The Microsoft news merely
provided a handy excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
