<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New tour, new Supremes for Diana Ross  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Thirty years after leaving the group, Diana Ross
will again reign Supreme.
</P>
<P>
   A radiant Ross, joined by a pair of Supremes who joined the
group after her 1970 departure, announced plans Tuesday morning for
a two-month U.S. tour focusing on the group's timeless Motown hits.
</P>
<P>
   It's the latest re-pairing of once-fractured bands -- think the
Eagles or Crosby, Stills, Nash &AMP; Young -- that can still sell out
arenas long after their last hit. Tickets are priced from $39.50 to
$125 for fans eager to hear Ross reprise the Supremes' catalog for
the first time in three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Such reunions are inevitably lucrative. Bruce Springsteen's tour
with the E Street Band generated $61.4 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   But Ross, addressing a crowded news conference inside Grand
Central Terminal, stressed that this was not a reunion. She's
teamed with Lynda Laurence, a Supreme since 1971, and Scherrie
Payne, who joined the group in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   The trio has never performed on stage together; Ross says that
at this point, they know exactly four Supremes songs.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was never called a reunion tour,'' Ross insisted. ''I
never considered it a reunion tour.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, efforts to sign up original Supreme Mary Wilson for the
tour fell through.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wish she was here,'' Ross said of Wilson. ''I think where
the breakdown came was with Mary and the promoters ... I don't
think anyone was willing to go as far as Mary wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Promoter Arthur Fogel refused to discuss specifics of the
negotiations, but confirmed that efforts to add Wilson ended
without an agreement. The third original Supreme, Florence Ballard,
died in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Return to Love'' tour opens June 14 in Philadelphia and
runs through Aug. 5, with a finale at the MGM Grand in Las Vegas.
Tickets for the shows in Philadelphia, Detroit, Chicago, New York
and Boston go on sale next week.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said that fans can expect to hear all the Supreme's
chart-topping hits: ''Where Did Our Love Go,'' ''Baby Love,''
''Stop! In the Name of Love,'' ''Back in My Arms Again'' and many
more.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-show tour may be ''a once-in-a-lifetime chance,'' Ross
said. ''The reason we're doing this is for our fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross, 56, was in high spirits for the announcement. Wearing a
pink leather outfit with matching lipstick, she arrived with her
bandmates in a stretch limousine. Despite falling rain, Ross exited
wearing sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   Later, she joked about the length of her career.
</P>
<P>
   ''I spent 10 years with the Supremes, and 30 years as a solo
act,'' Ross said. ''I've been performing 40 years, and I'm only
38!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-04-00 1413 </TRAILER>
