<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq, Dow Drop 500 Then Recover  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index plummeted more than
500 points today, but bounced back from its earlier lows as bargain
hunters entered the market looking for cheap deals after a steep
two-day selloff.
</P>
<P>
   The weakness in the Nasdaq derailed the Dow Jones industrials,
pulling the blue-chip index down sharply in afternoon trading.
</P>
<P>
   Computer-programmed sell orders sent stocks tumbling once the
Nasdaq plunged below 4,000 for the first time since Feb. 1. Then
programmed buy orders lifted stocks from those lows.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq was off 273.40
at 3,950.28. At its low point, the Nasdaq fell 574.57 to 3,649.11
and was down more than 923 points in two days, having dropped
349.15 Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The selloff knocked the Nasdaq 27.7 percent below its March 10
peak of 5,048.62. Historically, Wall Street has considered a drop
of 20 percent from a peak the hallmark of a bear market. For the
moment, however, analysts were reluctant to predict whether the
current decline means that the end of the long bull market in
high-tech stocks is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the bottom may be in place. That's not to say that we
won't go back down and test these levels,'' said Brian G. Belski,
chief investment strategist at George K. Baum &AMP; Co. in Kansas City,
Mo.
</P>
<P>
   While the breadth and sharpness of the technology selloff
ultimately pulled the broad market into a powerful decline. The Dow
Jones industrial average was down as much as 503 points before
recovering to a loss of 174.98 at 11,046.95.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 47.23 at 1,458.74.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies, which nearly
matches the Nasdaq in its heavy weighting of technology stocks,
plunged 35.48 to 480.56.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the Nasdaq was long overdue to drop from the
heights it reached early this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''As hard as it is to believe, this is a good thing,'' said Pete
Anderson, chief investment officer at American Express Financial
Advisors in Minneapolis. ''One sector of the market was insanely
overvalued. The rest was deeply undervalued. Now we are reversing
that.''
</P>
<P>
   A broad range of technology stocks sustained crushing losses.
Veritas Software fell 16 1/16 to 95 7/16, Exodus Communications
fell 12 13/16 to 110 and JDS Uniphase fell 12| to 99.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best-known names, which some investors had been
clinging to as a safe haven, collapsed early today, but then erased
some of those losses. Cisco Systems was down 2 1/16 to 70~, and
Oracle fell 4~ to 70~.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst for Monday's rout -- Microsoft -- slipped again.
</P>
<P>
   After plunging 15] to 90~ on Monday, Microsoft fell another 4]
to 86{ today. After the close of trading Monday, a federal judge
ruled the company violated U.S. antitrust laws by mounting a
''deliberate assault'' on competition in the Internet browser
market. The ruling could lead to drastic punishment, including a
breakup.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller technology shares, which have fallen prey to investors'
worries that their prices ran up too quickly in recent months, slid
once more today, lending credibility to analysts' belief that
Microsoft wasn't solely responsible for the technology selloff
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''In hindsight, technology shares had been ripe for a further
correction,'' said Scott J. Brown, chief economist at Raymond James
&AMP; Associates in St. Petersburg, Fla. ''The Microsoft news merely
provided a handy excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 1.07 billion shares,
compared with 643.69 million at the same time Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
