<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Watchdog groups file complaint against Clinton, Giuliani campaigns  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Alleging that special party accounts
established to benefit Hillary Rodham Clinton and Rudolph Giuliani
are illegal, a pair of good government groups on Tuesday filed a
complaint with the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Common Cause and Democracy 21 also asked the Justice
Department's campaign finance task force to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   The groups' complaint targets accounts set up by the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee and the National Republican
Senatorial Committee to accept unlimited contributions, known as
''soft money,'' from unions, corporations and deep-pocketed
individuals who are not permitted to give directly to individual
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say soft money allows candidates to bypass campaign
donation limits.
</P>
<P>
   ''The campaigns of first lady Hillary Clinton and Rudy Giuliani
are thumbing their noses at the federal campaign finance laws and
treating the voters of New York as if they were fools,'' Democracy
21 President Fred Wertheimer said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Common Cause President Scott Harshbarger said the Clinton and
Giuliani camps were ''clearly in violation of the spirit and
explicit letter of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   But party officials defended the fund-raising agreements, which
they say have been used in U.S. Senate elections for several years
now.
</P>
<P>
   The DSCC currently has seven joint fund-raising agreements with
candidates. The NRSC has similar agreements with several
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   DSCC political director Jim Jordan called the complaint
''frivolous, disingenuous, and utterly without merit.''
</P>
<P>
   ''These mechanisms are entirely appropriate and legal as a
settled point of campaign law,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger and Wertheimer said they targeted the New York race
because of the documented connection between the parties and the
campaigns. They pointed to remarks made by top Clinton adviser
Harold Ickes who said the campaign had reviewed and provided input
for a DSCC-funded commercial featuring the first lady last year.
And the advocates said the parties have become more brazen, now
attaching the names of candidates to accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The parties are barred from specifically earmarking soft money
for candidates. They say they set up the accounts to keep a tally
of how much candidates help raise for the party.
</P>
<P>
   Wertheimer scoffed at that explanation saying, ''Clinton and
Giuliani are soliciting these soft money contributions for the
purpose of having them spent to directly influence their Senate
races.''
</P>
<P>
   The NRSC did not return a telephone call seeking comment.
Neither did the Clinton and Giuliani campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   But the DSCC sought to discredit Harshbarger, a fellow
Democrat,by distributing press releases Tuesday detailing how he
had received soft money himself when as Massachusetts attorney
general he ran for governor in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger said the soft money used in his race was ''a
completely different kind.''
</P>
<P>
   The complaint came as Giuliani stumped in New York with Arizona
Sen. John McCain, the most visible booster of campaign finance
reform. McCain's plan would ban soft money.
</P>
<P>
   With seven months to go before the election, the
Giuliani-Clinton contest is on track to become the most expensive
contest in New York history. Giuliani has raised $19 million and
Clinton $12 million. Recent polls show the two in a dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties are expected to pour soft money into New York for
television advertisements as Election Day draws nearer.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money cannot be spent on advertisements that specifically
advocate voting for a candidate but can be used for general issue
ads as well as get-out-the-vote and other party-building
activities.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's New York Senate 2000 account had raised more than
$700,000 in soft money by the end of February. The Giuliani Victory
Committee was set up just weeks ago and has not reported yet. A
March 23 fund-raiser held in New York City to kick off soft money
donations to Giuliani asked for $50,000 donations.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC had no comment Tuesday. The Justice Department did not
immediately return a phone call seeking comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-04-00 1442 </TRAILER>
