<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel Votes on Visa Waiver  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A House panel voted Tuesday to make permanent
a pilot program that waives visa requirements for travel between
the United States and 29 other countries.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation passed the House Judiciary Committee by voice
after Democrats on the panel inserted language to ensure that
racial and ethnic profiling are not used to exclude nations from
the program.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would make permanent a visa-free program that was
inaugurated in 1986 and now is used annually by 17 million people,
more than half those visiting the United States every year for
business and travel.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for the program, a country must extend reciprocal
visa-free entry privileges to American citizens, have a
nonimmigrant visa refusal rate of less than 3 percent and commit to
fully develop a machine-readable passport by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, sponsored by Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, chairman of
the Judiciary immigration subcommittee, also seeks to tighten
controls over visitors by requiring the Immigration and
Naturalization Service to develop a fully automated system for
tracking the entry and departure of visa waiver travelers entering
by air or sea.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's spokesman, Allen Kay, said the United States is the only
industrialized nation that does not record departures of visitors,
a practice that has made it harder to prevent overstays.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is supported by the tourism and travel industry, and in
a letter to the committee, Assistant Attorney General Robert Raben
said the administration backs a permanent waiver program. He
expressed some concern that time frames for putting automated
databases in place were overly ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the panel noted that not one African or Caribbean
country has qualified for the program because of high visa refusal
rates, and they alleged some U.S. consular officials have used
racial or ethnic factors in denying visa requests.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Conyers of Michigan, the committee's top Democrat,
offered an amendment to preclude from calculations of refusal rates
any denials based on race, sex, sexual orientation or disability.
</P>
<P>
   The language was accepted, although Smith said it could subject
consular officials to second-guessing by anyone claiming
discrimation.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also approved by a voice vote a bill, sponsored by
Rep. Christopher Smith, R-N.J., that would create a new class of
visas for victims of sex trafficking or slave labor.
</P>
<P>
   Visas would be extended to those victims and their families who
cooperate with law enforcement and who would face persecution or
extreme hardship if repatriated.
</P>
<P>
   Those under the program, which would be capped at 5,000 a year,
would be able to apply for permanent residence after three years.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The visa waiver bill is H.R. 3767.
</P>
<P>
   The trafficking visa bill is H.R. 3244.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Rep. Lamar Smith, immigration subcommittee chairman:
http://www.house.gov/lamarsmith
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
