</P>
<P>
   Leading Indicators Fell in February
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A key gauge of future U.S. economic activity
fell 0.3 percent in February, the biggest monthly drop in more than
four years, suggesting that rising interest rates have begun to
slow economic growth somewhat. The Conference Board's Index of
Leading Economic Indicators dropped to 106 in February after rising
a revised 0.2 percent in January to 106.3, the private
business-financed research group said today. Economists had
expected a 0.1 percent drop. ''Signals for the immediate future
point to continued expansion, although not at the breakneck pace of
the fourth quarter of 1999,'' when the U.S. economy grew at a
sizzling 7.3 percent annual rate, Ken Goldstein, the Conference
Board's chief economist, said.
</P>
<P>
   Startups Ponder Microsoft Effects
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Entrepreneurs see both opportunity and
potential disaster if severe penalties are levied at Microsoft in
an antitrust case, particularly if a breakup of the company is
ordered. At Spring Internet World 2000 yesterday, several small
company representatives looked with trepidation at a judge's ruling
that the world's largest software maker violated federal law. In
the short term, a major defeat for Microsoft could scare investors
away from technology stocks, drying up much-needed capital for
startups looking to market the next big Internet idea. That fear
has been lent credence by the Nasdaq's sharp falls yesterday and
today. Others, however, said firms struggling against the
proverbial 800-pound gorilla could benefit from a smaller
Microsoft, especially if it is broken up into a series of more
focused companies. Microsoft owner Bill Gates says he will appeal
the verdict and believes the company has a strong position for an
appeal. Microsoft stock was down 4\ at 86| this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   EU Reserves Comment on Microsoft
</P>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Commission declined to
comment today on a U.S. federal court ruling finding Microsoft
Corp. guilty of violating antitrust laws by mounting a ''deliberate
assault'' on competition in the Internet browser market. EU
spokesman Michael Tscherny said the EU executive ''does not comment
on decisions by other judicial authorities. U.S. authorities are
doing their job and we are doing ours.'' He also said it was too
early to say whether the U.S. ruling would have any impact on EU
antitrust investigations of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon Is New Wireless Giant
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Bell Atlantic Corp. and Vodafone AirTouch PLC
plan an initial public offering to sell stock in their newly named
wireless venture, Verizon Wireless, which is the biggest mobile
phone and paging company in the nation. The announcement today
accompanied the introduction of a national flat-rate plan for
mobile calling and the launch of an aggressive branding and
marketing campaign for Verizon, a name choice that has puzzled many
observers. The companies also announced plans to invest $3 billion
this year in upgrading and expanding their national wireless
network to increase capacity and add new services such as instant
text messaging between mobile phones and handheld devices. Bell
Atlantic stock was up down 5/16 at 62}.
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco Explores Possible Sale
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Nabisco Group Holdings Corp. shares climbed
sharply today in the wake of its disclosure that it is exploring
selling the company or its majority stake in the maker of Ritz
crackers and Oreo cookies. In yesterday's announcement, the Nabisco
Group board also rejected as inadequate Carl Icahn's declaration
that he was prepared to start a tender offer of $13 a share, or
$1.3 billion, for 100 million shares of Nabisco Group under certain
conditions. The Nabisco board said that price ''does not come close
to reflecting the underlying value of the company's business.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorola Invests in Net Tissue Bank
</P>
<P>
   SCHAUMBURG, Ill. (AP) -- Motorola Inc. has invested in a
fledgling company that is developing computer databases aimed at
helping find new treatments for diseases such as diabetes, breast
cancer and Alzheimer's disease. The amount of the investment in
TissueInformatics Inc., a private firm based in Pittsburgh, was not
disclosed. TissueInformatics plans to introduce the first of what
it calls ''virtual tissue banks'' in December. It says the
multi-dimensional databases will let researchers compile scientific
conclusions from advanced microscopic images of human and plant
tissues.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Makes Telecom Accusations
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration today accused
Mexico and seven other nations of erecting unfair barriers to keep
American telecommunication companies out of their markets. The
administration set deadlines for later this year for the barriers
to be removed and raised the prospect that cases would be brought
to the World Trade Organization if the most objectionable barriers
are not dealt with. The other nations named in the annual review of
telecommunication practices were Germany, South Africa, Britain,
Canada, Peru, Israel and Taiwan. Last week, the administration
faulted Japan on communications.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel Selling Plants to Solectron
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Nortel Networks Corp. is taking a step away from
brick and mortar, transferring its manufacturing plants in North
America and Asia to Solectron Corp. The Brampton, Ontario-based
telecommunications company said today it will sell its
manufacturing plants in Calgary, Research Triangle Park, N.C.;
Monterrey, Mexico; and Istanbul, Turkey, to Solectron. The 4,200
workers at Nortel's plants will keep their jobs, both companies
said. Nortel, which expects to make $900 million from the sale,
will sign a four-year, $10 billion supply deal with Solectron.
</P>
<P>
   Sega Unveils Plan For Net Service
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Realizing online gaming will play a big role in
the future of the video-game market, Sega Enterprises Ltd. is
stepping up its Web presence with the launch of a new Sega-branded
Internet service provider this fall. Sega introduced today its
plans for a new online entertainment company that includes SegaNet,
a high-speed Internet service provider with multiplayer gaming as
well as chat capabilities and information about its video games.
The company is the first of the video-game manufacturers to give a
defined blueprint of how it will use the Internet to enhance
playtime.
</P>
