<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Groups Lobby for Increased Privacy  </HEADLINE>
By JANELLE CARTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With increased protections to safeguard
drivers' license information set to begin in two months, consumer
advocacy groups Tuesday hailed its implementation and urged
Congress to do even more.
</P>
<P>
   But states' motor vehicles administrators said further
clarification is needed of the laws aimed at curbing states'
ability to sell the license information to businesses and political
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clarification would help ensure that state practices are more
uniform,'' Roger D. Cross, administrator of the Wisconsin Division
of Motor Vehicles, told the Senate appropriations transportation
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   On June 1, most states will begin implementing provisions that
allow consumers to ''opt in'' to state programs that market their
personal information, a change from the current ''opt out''
provision. Under the change, consumer confidentiality is
essentially assumed unless otherwise notified.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of states whose state legislatures did not meet this
year were given extensions to comply.
</P>
<P>
   Cross said states are confused about the interpretation of
''express consent'' and many may close records for marketing
purposes to avoid the costs of the new restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups hailed the changes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government does not own its listings of our name, address,
phone number, Social Security number, photograph or other personal
information just because we are required to provide them for
specific purposes,'' said Phyllis Schafly, president of the
conservative Eagle Forum. ''It's bad enough when private interests
invade our privacy, but it's positively offensive when the
government does this.''
</P>
<P>
   Some consumer advocates say further changes should include a
permanent ban on the sharing of information or building of
databases and tough enforcement of states that don't comply.
</P>
<P>
   ''There should be no options,'' said Susan Herman, executive
director of the National Center for Victims of Crime. ''Drivers'
personal information should never be released except as outlined in
the act.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's changes strengthened the 1994 Driver's Privacy
Protection Act, which required states to give licensed drivers the
option to keep their contact information confidential. Disclosure
was limited to instances such as for law enforcement officials,
courts, government agencies and private investigators. States
responded by requiring consumers to ''out'' to prevent marketing of
their information.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., the subcommittee chairman who
authored last year's amendments did not directly comment on the
push for more restrictions but said, ''American citizens should
have the power to put 'doors' on all aspects of their private lives
and to expect that anyone who wants to enter must seek and gain
consent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 1509 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000404.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Claims Unfair Telecom Practices  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER, AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration on Tuesday accused
Mexico, Canada, Britain and five other nations of erecting unfair
trade barriers to keep American telecommunications companies out of
their markets.
</P>
<P>
   In its annual review of barriers to competition in telephone
services, the administration did not announce that any immediate
cases would be filed with the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it set a series of upcoming deadlines for the countries
to remove the offending barriers or run the risk that WTO cases
would be filed.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky said she was
particularly concerned about Mexico, where she said the situation
was ''extremely serious.''
</P>
<P>
   The other nations named in the annual review of
telecommunication practices were Germany, South Africa, Britain,
Canada, Peru, Israel and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the administration issued a separate report accusing
Japan of violating its WTO commitments by refusing to lower
interconnection fees that U.S. telecommunication companies complain
are designed to keep them out of the Japanese market.
</P>
<P>
   Barshefsky on Tuesday set a deadline of July 28 for resolving
both the Japanese case and a separate case against Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ''In Mexico, it appears that progress toward a level playing
field for telecommunications carriers now is stalled,'' she said in
a statement. ''The United States will determine by July 28 whether
additional action, including in the WTO, would be appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The complaint against Mexico was brought by a group of U.S.
companies including AT&AMP;T and MCI Worldcom. The U.S. companies
contend that the Mexican government and the nation's largest
telephone company, Telmex, have engaged in unfair practices aimed
at restricting access by foreign competitors.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T applauded the administration's decision, saying it sent the
right signal to countries attempting to keep their consumers from
benefiting from greater competition.
</P>
<P>
   ''Policies that promote the care and feeding of monopolies must
end,'' AT&AMP;T said in a statement. ''The USTR's decision to further
investigate these countries sends the right signal and shows it is
prepared to act if the offending policies don't change.''
</P>
<P>
   Other review deadlines set by the administration today included
June 15 for Germany, South Africa and Britain, and Oct. 2 for
Canada and Peru.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the administration said it would monitor Israel's
performance in living up to its commitments to terminate
objectionable telephone barriers by Dec. 31, 2001, and watch to see
that Taiwan eliminates certain exclusive licensing arrangements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 1518 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
