<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Army Pushes $38B Buy of Helicopters  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS, AP Military Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army said Tuesday that 40 percent of its
helicopters cannot be relied on in wartime and disclosed a
blueprint for improvement that includes buying 1,213 new-generation
Comanche helicopters for $38 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The blueprint included stark admissions of problems in Army
aviation, but senior officers who laid out the plan at a Pentagon
news conference expressed confidence that affordable solutions are
at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really don't agree with the fact that we're in crisis,''
said Col. Pat Garman. ''A crisis is you don't have a clue what's
going on, and you don't have a plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan that Garman and other senior officers presented Tuesday
said ''just over 40 percent'' of the helicopters in the Army's
fleet are rated ''red,'' meaning they could not be counted on to
perform their wartime missions.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also cited a ''dramatic decline'' in Army aviator
experience and skill over the past decade. It said today's aviation
battalion commander has an average of fewer than 1,000 hours of
flying time, compared with an average of 2,000 hours 10 years ago.
The drop-off has occurred up and down the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly, aviation is headed in the wrong direction,'' the
blueprint said.
</P>
<P>
   To fix the experience shortfall, the Army plans to redesign its
training program. Basic flight training will be shortened and
advanced aviators given 50 percent more training time.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of Army aviation in the 21st century is supposed
to be the Comanche, an armed reconnaissance helicopter with more
radar-evading stealth technology than any chopper in the current
fleet. It will replace the OH-58 Kiowa Warrior, which will be
retired in 2013, about seven years earlier than planned.
</P>
<P>
   The Comanche is being produced by Boeing Co. and Sikorsky
Aircraft Corp., a subsidiary of United Technologies Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Brig. Gen. Craig Hackett, director of Army requirements, told
reporters that despite recent speculation the Comanche program
would be scaled back or delayed to free money for other
modernizations, Army Chief of Staff Gen. Eric Shinseki decided the
helicopter is vital to the future.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Army is fully committed to the Comanche,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   The first Comanches are to enter the fleet in 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the addition of the Comanche, the overall Army
helicopter fleet will be reduced from six types to four.
</P>
<P>
   The last of the AH-1 Cobras, combat mainstays in the Vietnam War
that now average 30 years old, will be retired this October, and
UH-1 Huey helicopters will be retired in 2004. That will leave the
UH-60 Black Hawk utility helicopter fleet, the Vietnam-era CH-47
Chinook transports and the AH-64 Apache attack helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said the modernization plan will require some new
investments, but he said the Army continues work on estimates of
how much more it will cost than is provided in the current Army
budget plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 1522 </TRAILER>
