<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Witness Takes Stand in Marine Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A Marine captain charged in the
heatstroke death of a reservist once compared his troops to dogs,
an infantry school instructor testified Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony came during the second day of a court-martial for
Capt. Victor Arana, 28, of DuPage County, Ill. Arana is charged
with dereliction of duty and failure to obey an order in the death
last July 7 of Lance Cpl. Giuseppe ''Joey'' Leto, 21, a reservist
from New Milford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Arana marched Leto's 180-man unit too fast
without adequate rest breaks in the humid July heat and didn't seem
to care about his troops. Defense lawyers contend Arana wasn't
given proper guidance by his superiors.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Lloyd Freeman, second in command at Camp Lejeune's
infantry school training battalion, said he talked to Arana after
noticing that Arana's sergeant had a negative attitude about
Marines in his company.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said, 'Well, I see them like dogs. You tell them what to do
and you don't worry about their feelings,''' Lloyd testified. ''At
that point I was shocked. ... I think I said, 'I'm glad I wasn't
around as an enlisted man with you as a leader.'''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman also said he felt company commanders at the infantry
school pushed new Marines too hard on conditioning hikes. He said
he was particularly concerned about heat casualties during hot
months.
</P>
<P>
   Arana faces a maximum sentence of nine months in prison and
dismissal from the Corps if convicted of both charges. A judge is
hearing the trial without a jury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
