<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq, Dow Fall 500, Cut Losses  </HEADLINE>
By RACHEL BECK, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index plunged more than 574
points today, sending the broader market on a steep slide, as
investors grew increasingly pessimistic about the future of
technology stocks. Buying from bargain hunters in late trading
helped lift stocks from their early lows.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks tumbled once the Nasdaq plunged below 4,000 for the first
time since Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In late afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq was off
220.62 at 4,003.06. At its low point, the Nasdaq fell 574.57 to
3,649.11 -- its lowest level since Dec. 15 -- and was down more than
923 points in two days, having dropped 349.15 Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day selloff knocked the Nasdaq 27.7 percent below its
March 10 record of 5,048.62. Historically, Wall Street has
considered a drop of 20 percent from a peak the hallmark of a bear
market.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, however, analysts were reluctant to predict
whether the current decline means that the end of the long bull
market in high-tech stocks is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the bottom may be in place. That's not to say that we
won't go back down and test these levels,'' said Brian G. Belski,
chief investment strategist at George K. Baum &AMP; Co. in Kansas City,
Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The breadth and sharpness of the technology selloff ultimately
pulled the broad market into a powerful decline. The Dow Jones
industrial average was down as much as 503 points before recovering
to a loss of 116.73 at 11,105.20.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 39.65 at 1,466.28.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies, which nearly
matches the Nasdaq in its heavy weighting of technology stocks,
plunged 26.93 to 489.11.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the Nasdaq was long overdue to drop from the
heights it reached early this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''As hard as it is to believe, this is a good thing,'' said Pete
Anderson, chief investment officer at American Express Financial
Advisors in Minneapolis. ''One sector of the market was insanely
overvalued. The rest was deeply undervalued. Now we are reversing
that.''
</P>
<P>
   A broad range of technology stocks sustained crushing losses.
Veritas Software fell 10 15/16 to 100 9/16, Exodus Communications
fell 7 13/16 to 115 and JDS Uniphase fell 12 1/16 to 99 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best-known names, which some investors had been
clinging to as a safe haven, collapsed early today, but then erased
much of those losses. Cisco Systems was down 1 15/16 to 71, and
Oracle fell 5 7/16 to 71 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst for Monday's rout -- Microsoft -- slipped again.
</P>
<P>
   After plunging 15] to 90~ on Monday, Microsoft fell another 4
3/16 to 86 11/16 today. After the close of trading Monday, a
federal judge ruled the company violated U.S. antitrust laws by
mounting a ''deliberate assault'' on competition in the Internet
browser market. The ruling could lead to drastic punishment,
including a breakup.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today's pressures came from three M's: Microsoft, margin calls
and mounting anxiety,'' said Alan Ackerman, senior vice president
at Fahnestock &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller technology shares, which have fallen prey to investors'
worries that their prices ran up too quickly in recent months, slid
once more today, lending credibility to analysts' belief that
Microsoft wasn't solely responsible for the technology selloff
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''In hindsight, technology shares had been ripe for a further
correction,'' said Scott J. Brown, chief economist at Raymond James
&AMP; Associates in St. Petersburg, Fla. ''The Microsoft news merely
provided a handy excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   As stocks have fallen, investors who bought securities on
margin, or on credit, have had to sell their shares and repay their
loans to brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-2 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 1.25 billion shares,
compared with 776.26 million at the same time Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
