<HEADLINE> Bebop Innovator Plays for Birthday  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- James Moody, who created one of the best-known
songs of the bebop era, ''Moody's Mood for Love,'' when he
improvised on chord changes in ''I'm in the Mood for Love,'' was
the star performer at his 75th birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   At a sold-out concert at Avery Fisher Hall on Monday, he
introduced his Uncle Louie, who gave him his first saxophone at 16.
He also sang, told jokes and played forceful, melodic sax.
</P>
<P>
   Proclamations were read from President Clinton, among others.
Guest musicians included Paquito D'Rivera, Slide Hampton, and Kenny
Barron, who first worked for Moody in 1961. Bill Cosby joined in on
percussion on one song.
</P>
</TEXT>
