<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stock Fall Pinches Commodities  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean and grain futures fell sharply Tuesday on
the Chicago Board of Trade as investors and funds yanked their
money when U.S. stock markets went into free fall.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans fell more than half the 30-cent-a-bushel limit before
cutting their losses in half by the end of the session as equities
rebounded. Prices also were pressured by followthrough from
Monday's weak close and new forecasts for rain in the still-dry
Midwest late this week.
</P>
<P>
   Corn also took stock market-related losses, with funds taking
profits in commodities to cover losses in equities. The bearish
mood was added to by concerns that foot-in-mouth disease in South
Korea will spread. The additional slaughter of cattle, if needed as
a result of the disease, would cut into demand for both corn and
soymeal as feed.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat trading was lighter but prices also were hurt by the stock
market's decline.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for May delivery fell 2 cents to $2.55} a bushel; May corn
fell 2\ cents to $2.32 a bushel; July oats fell } cent to $1.20\ a
bushel; May soybeans fell 8 cents to $5.38{ a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef and pork futures declined on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, in a slide also accelerated by the stock market selloff.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle fell .48 cent to 68.67 cents a pound; May
feeder cattle fell .73 cent to 83.17 cents a pound; June lean hogs
fell .82 cent to 72.45 cents a pound; May frozen pork bellies fell
1.78 cent to 95.57 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
