<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Market Turmoil Could Hurt Countries  </HEADLINE>
By HARRY DUNPHY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Many developing countries are bouncing back
from the global financial crisis that started 2{ years ago but risk
turmoil again if the flow of capital should become volatile again,
the World Bank said Monday in a new report.
</P>
<P>
   Another threat to these nations' recovery is the possibility of
a sharp economic slowdown in the United States, a major provider of
investment funds. Stronger economic growth in Europe and Japan and
expanded world trade could offset any U.S decline, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   In an annual report called ''Global Development Finance,'' the
World Bank said the global economy would grow by 3.5 percent in
2000, compared with 2.9 percent in 1999. Last December the bank
forecast world global growth at 2.9 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The bank said in developing countries average growth was likely
to reach 4.6 percent in 2000 and climb slightly higher to 4.8
percent in 2001-2002.
</P>
<P>
   But the bank warned that 41 low-income countries, with a
combined population of more than one billion people, will barely
cross the threshold into positive growth.
</P>
<P>
   ''This underscores the still fragile path of reform and recovery
that lies ahead for these countries,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   While the financial crises has abated in Asia, Russia and Latin
America, the report said, ''the next decade may well see another
capital boom to emerging markets, accompanied again by high
volatility of capital flows.''
</P>
<P>
   It said the current pause in flight capital movements could last
for some years, providing developing countries with breathing room
to protect against future chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Uri Dadush, director of the bank group that produced the report,
said developing countries should use this time ''every hour, every
day to improve their economic fundamentals, strengthen their
banking systems and carry out other reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   The report explores short-term safeguards countries can adopt to
guard against rapid capital inflows and outflows such as imposing
controls as Chile and Malaysia have tried in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The bank and its sister institution, the International Monetary
Fund, used to routinely oppose such controls, but in recent months,
both have said such measures can be useful if carefully applied for
a limited period.
</P>
<P>
   But capital controls and bank reform cannot substitute for the
economic fundamentals, the report said. ''For example they cannot
protect countries against the consequences of large fiscal deficits
over overvalued currencies.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank said that despite the financial crises, foreign direct
investment in developing countries continued, rising to $192
billion in 1999 compared with $35 billion eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It recommended that to encourage this investment, developing
countries should rely more heavily on trade, diversify their
economies and achieve greater competetiveness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 1600 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000404.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disney Workers Can Sport Mustaches  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) -- Attention Disney workers: Don't
throw out those razors just yet.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, Walt Disney executives said they were relaxing a
decades-old policy that prohibited theme-park workers from sporting
mustaches on the job.
</P>
<P>
   But the policy has a caveat: You can only grow a mustache on
vacation, and not at work.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney World spokesman Bill Warren said there's nothing
unusual about the caveat in the policy.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very common corporate guideline that you should grow a
mustache on your vacation so you wouldn't have an unkempt
appearance,'' Warren said. ''I'm not a hair expert, but I'm sure
someone can grow a mustache in a reasonable amount of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren said apparent confusion among workers means that
''somebody didn't get the message.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney officials decided to scrap the mustache ban -- which had
been in place since 1957 -- in order to make it easier to recruit
employees in a tight labor market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
