<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Havana Gives Gonzalez Kin Visas  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. officials in Havana issued visas today to
Elian Gonzalez's father and his immediate family, as negotiations
resumed in Miami over how custody of the 6-year-old Cuban boy will
be transferred to his father.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department approved visas Monday for Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, his wife, their infant son, a male cousin of Elian's, a
pediatrician and a kindergarten teacher. U.S. officials in Havana
confirmed today that the visas have been affixed to their
passports.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Gonzalez has said he would come to the United States
only if he could be assured custody of his son, who has been living
with relatives in Miami since he was rescued off the Florida coast
more than four months ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear today when he might travel to Washington or
where a custody transfer might take place. Officials said one
possibility was a reunion between father and son in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The talks in Miami recessed around lunchtime today as usual, and
a family attorney said they had broken down.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have not heard from the attorneys for the relatives in
Miami that they consider the talks to have been broken off,''
Justice spokesman Myron Marlin said this afternoon. ''We continue
to hope that we can all work together to resolve this in a fair,
orderly and prompt manner.''
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department official, requesting anonymity, said that
absent a transfer agreement, the Immigration and Naturalization
Service would send the Miami relatives a letter formally
transferring custody to the father. A second letter shortly
thereafter would provide instructions on how and when that transfer
should occur.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice official rejected the Miami family's suggestion that
Elian's future be decided by a panel of psychologists.
</P>
<P>
   ''We could conceivably see using medical experts to determine
how best the transfer should happen, but not whether it will
happen,'' said the Justice official, who requested anonymity. A
federal judge has upheld the authority of the INS to order Elian's
return to his father.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice official did not anticipate that Elian's father
would arrive in this country today. Immigration officials are still
discussing with the father's lawyer the details of when and how
Elian would be returned to Juan Miguel's custody, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   Marisleysis Gonzalez, a cousin who has been helping care for
Elian, said she still has not told the boy his father is coming.
The last time she mentioned the possibility, she said, the boy
cried through a weekend and the father did not show up.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a precaution, I will not tell him until everything is
certain.'' When someone mentions that his father might be coming,
she said, ''All he asks me is 'please don't let them take me.'''
She was hospitalized today after becoming ill following an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 protesters chanting ''Elian is not leaving'' broke
down a barrier today separating them from the home where the boy
has been staying. They linked arms and former a chain around the
home. City of Miami police did nothing to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, who has taken heat from some fellow
Democrats for advocating permanent residency for the boy, said
today on NBC's ''Today'' that the father should be allowed to
return the son to Cuba ''if the father says on free soil that he
believes that the son should go back to Cuba with him.'' However,
he said the boy's fate should be left to a family court -- not to
the INS.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who unsuccessfully sought the
Republican presidential nomination, told ''Today'': ''The ideal
arrangement would be dual citizenship.''
</P>
<P>
   It was expected that Juan Miguel Gonzalez and his party would
initially come to Washington and remain at the home of Fernando
Remirez, Cuba's top diplomat here.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said it was reviewing visa requests from 22
other Cubans, including 12 classmates of Elian. One request was
from Ricardo Alarcon, who is president of the Cuban National
Assembly and a top adviser to President Fidel Castro on U.S.
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, asked today why the six
were chosen, said, ''The point was to try to make it a group that
was useful for the child. We have to keep the interest of the child
central here.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost two-thirds of Americans approve of the government's
decision to send the boy back to Cuba to be with his father,
according to a Gallup Poll released today. Just over half of those
polled said the Clinton administration is making its decision based
on what it feels is in the best interest of U.S. relations with
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department threat to order Elian's deportation by
today unless his relatives in Miami agreed to accept the outcome of
pending court action was dropped in anticipation of the arrival of
the father. Robert Wallis, the Immigration Service's director for
the Miami district, said Monday, ''Once Mr. Gonzalez comes, the INS
will begin transferring parole care from Lazaro Gonzalez to the
boy's father.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallis said that ''does not mean that the child will be
immediately removed from the home of the great-uncle. Instead it is
our hope to begin a smooth and orderly process that will create as
little disruption as possible to Elian.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez said Monday night, ''If the father comes or not
we don't know, but he is welcome here. Don't ever doubt the
Gonzalez family has their door open for their family.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the great-uncle's home, protesters practiced forming a
human chain and vowed they would stop at nothing to keep the boy
from returning to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Many protesters stamped their feet as Ramon Saul Sanchez, leader
of the Miami-based anti-Castro group Democracy Movement, used a
bullhorn to call for Cuban-Americans to come to the home to protect
Elian. The Miami area has nearly 800,000 Cuban-American residents.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Gov. Jeb Bush met with safety officials to determine how
to respond to possible unrest if Elian is removed from the Little
Havana home.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Miami-Dade County Mayor Alex Penelas' statement last
week that local authorities would not assist the federal government
if it attempted to remove Elian, the county police department said
it is ready to respond to protests.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Justice Department reporter Michael J. Sniffen
contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: INS: http://www.ins.usdoj.gov
</P>
<P>
   Miami relatives: http://libertyforelian.org
</P>
<P>
   Cuban newspaper Granma: http://www.granma.cu
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
