<DOCNO> APW20000404.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African, European Leaders End Summit  </HEADLINE>
By RAF CASERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- With little action but lots of hugs,
handshakes and warm words, African and European leaders promised
Tuesday to mend their lopsided relationship and not let old
colonial grudges spoil their inaugural goodwill summit.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the 67 nations promised to improve cooperation to
help Africa escape the spiral of debt, disaster and war which has
turned the continent into the world's poorest.
</P>
<P>
   But the two-day summit -- where delegates in colorful African
dresses known as ''boubou'' mixed with counterparts in stern gray
suits -- was short on concrete commitments to alleviate Africa's
staggering debt and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ''This summit has united us formally for the first time,'' said
Javier Solana, the European Union's foreign policy chief. But he
warned that ''we need to know each other better if we are to build
a true partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   Summit host, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, said the summit
broke new ground. ''We witnessed the birth of a new partnership,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A century of colonial exploitation could not be fully expelled
from the meeting, held in a sprawling conference center between the
Nile and the desert, as Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi lashed out at
Europe for lecturing and trying to divide Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ''Stop looking at us as slaves,'' Gadhafi told the leaders late
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday however, Gadhafi received a host of European and
African leaders including Germany's Gerhard Schroeder and Spain's
Jose Maria Aznar.
</P>
<P>
   With international ostracism of Libya fading after the
suspension of U.N. sanctions in April 1999, Gadhafi has appeared
willing to build ties with Europe, which is equally keen to do
business with Libya given its vast oil and gas potential.
</P>
<P>
   Other African leaders also chided the Europeans for lecturing
them.
</P>
<P>
   President Robert Mugabe reminded Britain Monday that Zimbabwe
was no longer its colony, before going on Tuesday to smooth over
the two countries' dispute over the suppression of protests in
Harare.
</P>
<P>
   Others pointed out that democracy could not come without
development and insisted the old colonial masters should do more to
help.
</P>
<P>
   Germany made a promise of $350 million in debt relief for some
30 of Africa's poorest and most indebted nations and Spain added a
new promise of some $200 million. Africa's overall debt, however,
stands at $350 billion and African leaders left the summit with
little relief.
</P>
<P>
   French President Jacques Chirac chided European businessmen for
not investing more in the underdeveloped nations and accused them
of being ''Afro-pessimists.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst thing that can happen to the world economy, he said,
is for ''a fewer number of rich countries get richer and a growing
number of poor countries get poorer.''
</P>
<P>
   In a joint declaration, the leaders said they ''deplore the
intolerable fact that more than half of all Africans are living in
absolute poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   But to turn this around, EU Development Commissioner Poul
Nielson said, ''doing something credible about corruption is the
best confidence building measure to attract investment.''
</P>
<P>
   However, it was clear that corruption and poverty form a vicious
circle.
</P>
<P>
   ''Human rights must be paralleled by the right to food, water,
health and education,'' said British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders are to meet again in Greece in 2003. That will be
the first summit on Africa held in Europe since the 1884 Berlin
Conference, which set of the colonial ''Scramble for Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Our continent was then the hottest cake in town, and everyone
wanted a slice,'' said Nigerian President Olesegun Obasanjo.
''Africa's condition today is hardly a happy one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
