<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq, Dow End Only Somewhat Lower  </HEADLINE>
By RACHEL BECK, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- In the most volatile day ever for U.S. stocks,
the Nasdaq composite index and the Dow Jones industrial average
each plunged more than 500 points today before reversing course as
buyers flooded back into the battered market.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing pessimism among investors about the future of
technology stocks set off a 574 point slide in the Nasdaq and sent
the index below 4,000 for the first time since Feb. 1. That spurred
a steep selloff in the broader market.
</P>
<P>
   But bargain hunters looking for cheap deals after a two-day rout
entered the market in late trading and helped lift stocks from
their lows.
</P>
<P>
   At its low point, the Nasdaq fell 574.57 to 3,649.11; it climbed
as high as 4,283.45 in the first minutes of trading.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 46.85 to 11,175.08.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 12.91 to 1,493.06, and the Nasdaq
composite index fell 74.79 to 4,148.89.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a nearly 2-to-1 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,065 up, 2,038 down and 381
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume totaled 1.5 billion shares as of 4 p.m., vs. 1.02
billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 15.38 at
500.66.
</P>
<P>
   The 634-point swing was the biggest ever for the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   Today's losses added to a 349.15 drop on Monday. At its lowest
levels today, the Nasdaq was 27.7 percent below its March 10 record
of 5,048.62. Historically, Wall Street has considered a drop of 20
percent from a peak the hallmark of a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts, however, were reluctant to predict whether the decline
meant that the end of the long bull market in high-tech stocks is
imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the bottom may be in place. That's not to say that we
won't go back down and test these levels,'' said Brian G. Belski,
chief investment strategist at George K. Baum &AMP; Co. in Kansas City,
Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The breadth and sharpness of the technology selloff ultimately
pulled the broad market into a powerful decline. The Dow Jones
industrial average was up 196 points in early trading, then fell as
much as 503 before recovering to a loss of about 46.85 at
11,175.08. The 700.46-point swing from high to low was the biggest
on record for the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the Nasdaq was long overdue to drop from the
heights it reached early this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''As hard as it is to believe, this is a good thing,'' said Pete
Anderson, chief investment officer at American Express Financial
Advisors in Minneapolis. ''One sector of the market was insanely
overvalued. The rest was deeply undervalued. Now we are reversing
that.''
</P>
<P>
   A broad range of technology stocks sustained crushing losses,
but managed to bounce higher as buyers flooded the market late in
the session.
</P>
<P>
   Veritas Software fell 1 9/16 at 109 15/16, up from its 23-point
decline. Exodus Communications, down more than 30 early today,
finished the day up 14 7/16 at 137\.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best-known names, which some investors had been
clinging to as a safe haven, plunged early today, but then erased
much of those losses. Cisco Systems, which was down nearly 9, ended
up 5/16 at $73.25, while Oracle recovered from a loss of 12 to
finish down 11/16 at 76 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst for Monday's rout -- Microsoft -- slipped again.
</P>
<P>
   After plunging 15] to 90~ on Monday, Microsoft fell another 2
5/16 to 88 9/16 today. After the close of trading Monday, a federal
judge ruled the company violated U.S. antitrust laws by mounting a
''deliberate assault'' on competition in the Internet browser
market. The ruling could lead to drastic punishment, including a
breakup.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today's pressures came from three M's: Microsoft, margin calls
and mounting anxiety,'' said Alan Ackerman, senior vice president
at Fahnestock &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller technology shares, which have fallen prey to investors'
worries that their prices ran up too quickly in recent months, slid
once more today, lending credibility to analysts' belief that
Microsoft wasn't solely responsible for the technology selloff
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''In hindsight, technology shares had been ripe for a further
correction,'' said Scott J. Brown, chief economist at Raymond James
&AMP; Associates in St. Petersburg, Fla. ''The Microsoft news merely
provided a handy excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   As stocks have fallen, investors who bought securities on
margin, or on credit, have had to sell their shares and repay their
loans to brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
