<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elian Demonstrators Break Barricade  </HEADLINE>
By MILDRADE CHERFILS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Scores of anti-Castro demonstrators surged through
a police barricade and formed a human chain around Elian Gonzalez's
house Tuesday, vowing to resist any attempt by the U.S. government
to remove the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Miami police stood by and watched.
</P>
<P>
   ''Elian won't go!'' demonstrators chanted as they linked arms
around the small white house in Miami's Little Havana neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd grew edgy during the hot day as they learned that a
visa had been granted to Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, so
he can come from Cuba to the United States and be reunited with his
son.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Delrish Moss said the demonstrators would be allowed
to blow off steam for a while and would then be asked to move back.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-year-old boy has been the focus of an international
tug-of-war since Thanksgiving, after his mother and 10 other Cubans
drowned when their boat sank during an attempt to reach the United
States. Elian was rescued from an inner tube and placed in the care
of relatives in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   There have been regular, emotional protests in Little Havana for
months, and anti-Castro groups have called on the Cuban-American
community to prepare to form a human chain around the house if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters surged through the metal barricade because of a
rumor that federal agents were en route in a bus or van to take
Elian away in preparation for a reunion with his father.
</P>
<P>
   While the father and his immediate family were granted U.S.
visas, it was not clear when he might travel or where a custody
transfer might take place.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has been negotiating with the Miami
relatives on a plan for a handover. The talks in Miami recessed
around lunchtime Tuesday as usual, and a family attorney said they
had broken down.
</P>
<P>
   Many demonstrators said they were ready to be arrested for
Elian's sake.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have to take all of us. We will not move,'' said Marta
Lara, 24, a mortgage broker. ''I sincerely hope he feels protected.
I don't want him to feel scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Saul Sanchez, president of the anti-Castro Democracy
Movement, addressed the demonstrators through a bullhorn.
</P>
<P>
   ''Will we commit any kind of acts of violence?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''No!'' the protesters shouted.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want the father to come here to this house and meet with
this family to resolve the issue,'' Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
   Adorning the barricades and nearby utility poles were more than
20 white cardboard signs with the words: ''Pray for Elian.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, the cousin who has been Elian's stand-in
mother, Marisleysis Gonzalez, was hospitalized in stable condition
after becoming faint during a round of morning TV interviews.
Family spokesman Armando Gutierrez said she had been vomiting and
hospital personnel were trying to feed her.
</P>
<P>
   Marisleysis' father, Lazaro Gonzalez, Elian's great-uncle, urged
the government to allow an independent psychological evaluation of
Elian to determine if he might be harmed by a return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have always complied with the law, and will continue to
do,'' he said in a statement. ''What we are not prepared to do is
to participate in any action that will cause harm to the boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian has been kept out of school and taught at home recently
because the Miami relatives fear he may be taken away by federal
officials. The boy spent most of the day indoors but emerged before
noon and played with a small orange football.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
