<DOCNO> APW20000404.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thomson Travel Nixes German Buyout  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Thomson Travel PLC, Britain's biggest chartered
tour operator, on Tuesday rejected a planned buyout offer of nearly
$2.1 billion from Germany's C&AMP;N Touristic AG.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson's board of directors announced the decision after
meeting to consider the expected bid from C&AMP;N, a joint venture
between Kardstadt-Quelle AG and Deutsche Lufthansa AG.
</P>
<P>
   ''The board is unanimously of the view that such an offer, if
made, would be wholly inadequate, and the board would recommend
that shareholders reject any such offer,'' Thomson said.
</P>
<P>
   C&AMP;N, citing Thomson's poor financial performance, said earlier
Tuesday that it plans to make a cash offer of 130 pence ($2.08) per
share that would value Thomson at nearly $2.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The offer would represent a 37 percent premium to Thomson's
closing share price Monday of 95.25 pence ($1.52).
</P>
<P>
   ''Thomson's performance as a quoted company has been
disappointing, and in the last year shareholders have suffered a
collapse in the company's share price and have seen a marked
deterioration in its financial performance,'' C&AMP;N said in a
prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a result, the business is in a vulnerable position and
shareholder value remains exposed.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the company said it was eager to gain a foothold
in Britain, where it currently has no presence.
</P>
<P>
   The German company, Europe's third-largest tour business,
increased its holding of Thomson stock to 4.8 percent on Tuesday,
up from 2.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson Travel shares closed 36 percent higher at 129.5 pence
($2.07).
</P>
<P>
   Thomson, founded in 1965, was one of the first tour groups to
fly large numbers of Britons to Mediterranean resorts. It issued
three profit warnings last year, the most recent because of poor
sales related to millennium New Year's holidays.
</P>
<P>
   C&AMP;N was formed from a merger in 1998 of Lufthansa's charter
airline Condor Flugdienst GmbH and Karstadt Quelle's tour operator
NUR Touristic GmbH.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
