<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Treasury Targets Illness Tax Shelter  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON, AP Tax Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A charitable tax shelter cannot be based on
the life expectancy of a seriously ill person unless that person is
directly related to the beneficiaries or donors, under regulations
announced Tuesday by the Treasury Department.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the current practice ''ghoulish and grotesque,''
Treasury officials said these charitable trusts are being marketed
to help the wealthy escape taxes by inflating the amount of
interest that can be deducted on federal income, gift and estate
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The problem involves so-called charitable lead trusts in which
part of the money goes to a charity and part goes to other
noncharity beneficiaries. All of the interest of such trusts can be
deducted.
</P>
<P>
   Under the tax code, some of these trusts are linked to the
length of a certain person's life -- someone selected in advance to
serve as a kind of measuring stick. The value of the trust is based
on how long this person is expected to live.
</P>
<P>
   A taxpayer can select any person, so long as they are not
''terminally ill'' under the definitions in the law -- that can
include someone who is seriously ill but not immediately in danger
of dying. In such a case, the trust's value for tax purposes is the
same as if that person was completely healthy.
</P>
<P>
   If that seriously ill person dies prematurely, the charity
ultimately will receive far less than the amount of money on which
the tax deduction was based. And the other beneficiaries will
receive far more than the amount subject to taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury officials say the trusts are even being marketed in
packages that include the name and medical records of a seriously
ill person, who often receives a token payment. In some cases, a
charity interested in that person's particular illness is also
given some benefit from the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations proposed Tuesday would end that practice,
permitting only a donor, a donor's spouse or a direct ancestor of
any beneficiaries to be used as the ''measuring life'' for the
trust. If given final approval, they would apply to any transaction
made on or after April 4, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ''Marketing schemes that exploit the misfortunes of some for the
benefit of others are contrary to public policy,'' Treasury
officials said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Department: http://www.ustreas.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
