<HEADLINE> Gold Up on Stock Slide; Crude Falls  </HEADLINE>
By DAVE CARPENTER, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gold prices rallied strongly Tuesday on the New York Mercantile
Exchange as investors unnerved by Wall Street's bungee-jump plunge
went fleeing into the precious metal in droves.
</P>
<P>
   In other markets, falling gasoline futures dragged crude oil
lower and grains also slid as funds yanked money out of
agricultural commodities to cover their equities losses.
</P>
<P>
   Gold snapped out of the doldrums when the stock markets went
into free fall, rising as high as $291.50 per troy ounce -- a
two-week high and up 4 percent for the day -- before giving up half
that gain in a rollercoaster rally mirroring equities' dive and
climb.
</P>
<P>
   Gold for June delivery finished up $6.20 at $286.60 an ounce.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the changes in the investment environment, even
high-tech hounds and the Internet generation head for the
old-fashioned metal when times are tough, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The gold price is an economic and political barometer of the
well-being of the economic world,'' said George Gero, who follows
metals trading as first vice president of Prudential Securities in
New York. ''In times of great turmoil, people still turn to gold.''
</P>
<P>
   The plunge in stock indexes ''woke up the gold audience,'' he
said, after months of mostly lackluster trading since last fall's
stunning 34 percent climb to $339 an ounce.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just stability that keeps investors and funds coming
back. ''Gold is liquid, has depth, has no political allegiance and
is easily liquidated,'' said Gero.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news for gold bugs: Gold normally retraces its rallies
if they occur solely for reasons of economic turmoil. And there
were no other fundamental reasons for Tuesday's rise, the analyst
said.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere at the New York Merc, gasoline prices tumbled on weak
refining margins and cash markets. The decline put extra pressure
on crude, already weak after OPEC's decision last week to raise
production levels.
</P>
<P>
   May unleaded gas fell 4.23 cents to 79.93 cents a gallon; May
crude fell 98 cents to $25.45 a barrel; May heating oil fell 2.90
cents to 64.36 cents a gallon; May natural gas fell .67 cent to
$2.822 per 1,000 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   On the Chicago Board of Trade, fund managers unsettled by the
stock plunge took profits in commodities to try to make up for
their losses in equities.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans fell more than half the 30-cent-a-bushel limit before
cutting their losses in half by the end of the session as stocks
rebounded. Prices also were pressured by followthrough from
Monday's weak close and new forecasts for rain in the still-dry
Midwest late this week.
</P>
<P>
   Corn and wheat also declined because of stock prices, which were
still down significantly when the Chicago exchange closed.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for May delivery fell 2 cents to $2.55} a bushel; May corn
fell 2\ cents to $2.32 a bushel; July oats fell } cent to $1.20\ a
bushel; May soybeans fell 8 cents to $5.38{ a bushel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
