<HEADLINE> Tennessee Court Stays Executions  </HEADLINE>
By TOM SHARP, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- A federal appeals court Tuesday stayed
the planned executions this week of a convicted cop killer and a
child murderer. They would have been Tennessee's first executions
in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   The 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals stayed the execution of
Robert Glen Coe just 15 hours before he was to die by lethal
injection early Wednesday. The court also stayed the execution of
Philip Workman, who was set to die early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Coe, 43, claims he is insane and shouldn't be executed for
raping and killing 8-year-old Cary Ann Medlin in 1979. His
execution had been delayed twice since October, but on Monday the
Tennessee Supreme Court refused to delay the execution further.
</P>
<P>
   Workman, 46, argues that there is new evidence showing that he
did not fire the fatal shot that killed Memphis police Lt. Ronald
Oliver in 1981. He had confessed to the shooting but now says an
X-ray shows Oliver was killed with a bullet other than his.
</P>
<P>
   The stays came as Coe and Workman seemed close to exhausting
their legal options after two decades. In issuing the two stays
moments apart, the court said it would review both men's claims. In
Workman's case, a petition for clemency was pending with Gov. Don
Sundquist.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think these judges need to quit messing around and get on
with it,'' said Mickey Stout, Cary Ann's stepfather.
</P>
<P>
   Coe has said he lured the girl into his car and raped her. After
she told him, ''Jesus loves you,'' he said he decided to kill her,
first trying to strangle her and then stabbing her with a pocket
knife.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Paul Summers said the state will continue to
pursue both cases aggressively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
