<HEADLINE> Clinton Meets With Yemen President  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton on Tuesday commended the
leader of the Middle East nation of Yemen for changing travel rules
to let thousands of Jews of Yemeni origin return to their ancestral
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States appreciates the religious tolerance of
Yemen, especially the right accorded to Yemini Jewish communities
worldwide, including those in Israel, to visit Yemen,'' Clinton
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   President Ali Abdullah Saleh met for about 30 minutes with
Clinton, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and other senior
administration officials. The meeting commemorated the coming 10th
anniversary of the unification of Yemen.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1950s, many of the 50,000 Jews living in Yemen
emigrated to the new state of Israel, leaving behind synagogues and
property in the impoverished Arabian Peninsula nation.
</P>
<P>
   Yemen, which has a Jewish population of about 400, has said that
it will not establish ties with Israel without an overall Middle
East settlement in place. And while Yemen is not a direct player in
the peace negotiations, its decision in February to ease travel
restrictions is seen as a move toward easing relations among
nations in the region.
</P>
<P>
   P.J. Crowley, a national security spokesman for the White House,
said the new rules promote greater freedom of travel to Yemen by
all people of Yemeni descent.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is of most significant impact to Israelis of Yemeni
descent who wish to travel back to their homeland, and the Yemeni
government has responded and made it easier to do that,'' Crowley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Yemen's president thanked the United States for its help in
instituting democratic change. He also said his country appreciates
U.S. help in achieving needed improvements in health care and
higher education, removing dangerous land mines left from war and
providing food assistance and U.S. Agency for International
Development programs that have educated and trained Yemenis.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton praised Yemen for its democratic change, including
guaranteeing constitutional rights for women for full political and
economic participation.
</P>
<P>
   Crowley said the issue of terrorism did not surface.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not aware that it did come up, but it's something that we
are working with the Yemeni government to see in ways in which we
can cooperate to combat terrorism in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Tribesmen in Yemen, a rugged mountainous country once ruled by
the Queen of Sheba, have kidnapped about 300 foreigners, including
Americans, since independence. Generally hostages are used as
negotiating pawns in disputes with the government or other tribes,
as the kidnapped Polish ambassador was last month to gain freedom
for an arrested sheik.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 1749 </TRAILER>
