<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000404.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attempt Made To Change Flag Law  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN HUGHES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- When Cliff Graves died fighting a house fire,
his buddies in Rocklin, Calif., gave him a hero's send-off, flying
the U.S. flags at City Hall and at the volunteer fire station at
half-staff.
</P>
<P>
   That's when George Magnuson learned he was violating the Federal
Flag Code, a 1942 law that says only presidents and governors can
order U.S. flags lowered to half-staff on public property.
</P>
<P>
   The violation has bothered Magnuson, a volunteer firefighter,
ever since he helped with Graves' funeral arrangements in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   When Magnuson was elected to the City Council of the Sacramento
suburb in 1991, he launched an effort to amend the code so local
officials can order U.S. flags lowered in tribute to firefighters,
police officers and other public safety officials killed in the
line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   ''The last act you do for somebody shouldn't be something that
is not a legal act,'' Magnuson said. ''I really firmly believe that
when somebody dies helping to protect fellow citizens that the
citizenry should have the right to honor them.''
</P>
<P>
   Many local officials ignore the code intentionally or out of
ignorance, and there are no criminal or civil penalties for
violations.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Magnuson raised the issue at a National League of
Cities meeting but got nowhere. League officials said not enough
members expressed an interest.
</P>
<P>
   Magnuson now is lobbying Congress, which, along with President
Clinton, has authority to amend the code.
</P>
<P>
   And Magnuson may be making headway.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Doolittle, R-Calif., is considering legislation or a
resolution to allow local officials to lower U.S. flags to honor
public safety officers, said Richard Robinson, Doolittle's
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   National police and firefighter groups say no one has ever
approached them about trying to change the code, but that
Magnuson's idea has promise.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can think of no higher honor'' for slain police officers,
said Craig Floyd, chairman of the National Law Enforcement Officers
Memorial Fund, a Washington group that commemorates officers killed
in the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   George Burke, spokesman for the International Association of
Fire Fighters, said amending the code to include firefighters
''would be wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Others argue there is no need to amend the code. Brian Humphrey,
a spokesman for the Los Angeles Fire Department, said he believes
the code, which allows flags to be lowered ''in accordance with
recognized customs or practices not inconsistent with law,''
already gives fire officials the authority to fly Old Glory at
half-staff.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gormalley of the Veterans of Foreign Wars' national
office in Kansas City, Mo., said there is no reason to change the
code because it already calls for flying the flag at half-staff on
Peace Officers Memorial Day each May 15. Gormalley recommends local
officials lower a local flag or fly a black ribbon or drapery below
a fully raised U.S. flag to honor local heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Buss of the American Legion's national office in
Indianapolis says local officials who want to honor slain police
and firefighters can call their governor's office and seek an
official declaration to lower the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Magnuson doesn't like those alternatives. Peace Officers
Memorial Day doesn't cover firefighters, he said, and contacting
the governor is inconvenient.
</P>
<P>
   ''It should be an authorized procedure,'' Magnuson said. ''Just
say, 'This is OK, you don't have to worry about it.'''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   American Legion: http://www.legion.org/flagcode.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
