<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Artist's Plan Sparks Debate  </HEADLINE>
By BURT HERMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- An artist's plan to place a neon sign reading ''To
the Population'' inside Germany's Reichstag -- a contrast with the
building's old, historically-charged inscription -- has sparked a
controversy over what it means to be German.
</P>
<P>
   German artist Hans Haacke's proposal consists of a wooden
trough, 23 feet wide and 70 feet long, to be filled with dirt
brought by each of the 669 legislators from their hometowns.
</P>
<P>
   On top, the words ''Der Bevoelkerung,'' or ''To the
Population,'' will be lit up in white neon letters of the same
typeface and size as those above the Reichstag's entrance, which
read ''Dem Deutschen Volke,'' or ''To the German people.''
</P>
<P>
   The word ''Volk'' has long been linked with German nationalist
movements.
</P>
<P>
   The artist's contrasting of the words ''Volk'' vs.
''Bevoelkerung'' goes to the heart of current debates over
immigration and citizenship: whether those who live within
Germany's borders are a ''people'' or a ''population.''
</P>
<P>
   It poses the question of whether being German means ''being of
German descent,'' or whether it includes anyone who feels at home
here.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives insist Germany is not a country of immigrants,
even though almost 10 percent of its 83 million people being
foreigners. New laws that went into effect this year cut the
decades-old link between blood and citizenship, but only after much
heated debate.
</P>
<P>
   Norbert Lammert, a conservative lawmaker and leading opponent of
the artwork, said the artist's concept is ''more political than
aesthetic'' and has forwarded a motion to be voted on Wednesday to
block the work.
</P>
<P>
   Haacke sees the project as a statement against xenophobia.
</P>
<P>
   ''The population includes everybody who is living in Germany,''
he said in an interview Tuesday under the Reichstag's new dome,
where he was lobbying legislators to support the project.
</P>
<P>
   ''Millions lost their lives because of an understanding about
who belongs or does not belong to the German people,'' he said.
''We know that there are again people in this country who attack
passers-by on the street if they don't look German enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Haacke, who lives in New York, is no stranger to controversy.
</P>
<P>
   His piece ''Sanitation,'' part of the Whitney Museum of American
Art's current Biennial exhibition, depicts New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani as a fascist and links him to the Nazis for trying to deny
public funds to an art museum over an exhibit the mayor considered
anti-Catholic. Giuliani and Jewish groups have criticized the piece
as trivializing the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Even supporters of his Reichstag piece concede its political
overtones.
</P>
<P>
   The work ''is inseparable from the political message,'' said
lawmaker Franziska Eichstaedt-Bohling, a member of the art
committee. ''Everyone that votes for this votes on this political
message too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nazis used the word ''volk'' in their slogans and in the
title of their newspaper. The dirt from across Germany involved in
Haacke's plan has also reminded some of the ''blood and soil''
rituals that were part of the Nazis' nationalistic fanaticism.
</P>
<P>
   Lammert, however, argues that it's wrong for Haacke to assign a
negative connotation to the word, noting that ''Volk'' is used in
Germany's liberal, postwar constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why connect this with nationalism? It makes no sense,''
Lammert said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Already 180 legislators from across party lines have pledged to
vote Wednesday for the motion to block Haacke's $175,000 piece from
being placed in the Reichstag's northern atrium.
</P>
<P>
   A group of artists, museum directors and gallery owners from
across Germany sent an open letter Tuesday to parliament members
urging them to stand by the committee's approval of the work.
</P>
<P>
   If the piece does make it past lawmakers, Lammert said he has no
plans to bring soil from his own hometown to contribute.
</P>
<P>
   Haacke said he has no plans to fill the trough with soil from
elsewhere if not enough lawmakers participate, but instead will
leave it to future generations of lawmakers to complete the work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 1818 </TRAILER>
