<HEADLINE> Appellate Court hears Wendt v. Wendt multimillion divorcesettlement arguments  </HEADLINE>
By JUDITH FORMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Lorna Wendt, who won more than $20
million in a divorce from former General Electric executive Gary
Wendt, asked the state Appellate Court Tuesday to give her more
money.
</P>
<P>
   Wendt deserves a better settlement because Gary Wendt's assets
appreciated by about $23 million between December 1995 -- when the
couple first separated -- and Dec. 1997 -- when the divorce decree
was handed down, her lawyers argued.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Wendt ''got the benefit of everything,'' while her client
got no part of the then unmatured and unvested assets, said
attorney Kathleen Hogan.
</P>
<P>
   Lorna Wendt is seeking over $35 million from her ex-husband, her
lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Wendt's attorneys argue that Lorna Wendt received a fair,
mathematically-calculated share of his appreciated assets.
</P>
<P>
   ''She received 50 percent of the assets based on her
contributions at the time of the separation,'' attorney Kurt
Hansson said.
</P>
<P>
   It's time, Hansson said, for Gary Wendt to just '' move on with
his life.'' Tierney's decision should stand, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The previous settlement was based on the separation date. But
Hogan said there is no evidence that the 31-year-old marriage
actually dissolved in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ''He might as well have picked a baseball score,'' Hogan said of
Superior Court Judge Kevin Tierney, who heard the original case.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1997 divorce proceedings, Gary Wendt, the former GE
Capital Services chief convinced Tierney that those assets -- a
supplementary retirement allowance, unvested options, restricted
stock, and a long-term performance plan -- were of no value, Hogan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Oldham, another of Lorna Wendt's attorneys said the case
''sets a terrible precedent,'' allowing the major breadwinner in a
family to manipulate the date of separation based on future
financial gains of which only he is aware.
</P>
<P>
   ''Women are going to be left impoverished,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Wendt resigned from the Stamford-based financial arm of
General Electric in December 1998 after a turbulent relationship
with company chairman John F. Welch and the fallout from the very
messy and very public divorce. Wendt since has remarried and now
lives in Greenwich.
</P>
<P>
   Lorna Wendt has established the Foundation for Equity in
Marriage and advocates for fair divorce settlements.
</P>
<P>
   The Appellate Court is not expected to reach a decision for
several months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-04-00 1829 </TRAILER>
