<DOCNO> APW20000404.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen: US To Sell Missile To Egypt  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- In a move that will upgrade Egypt's air
defenses, Defense Secretary William Cohen said Tuesday that the
United States has agreed in principle to sell the Mideast nation a
version of the Advanced Medium Range Air-to-Air Missile.
</P>
<P>
   He said the proposed sale of the short-range, surface-launched
version the missile will ''update and modernize'' Egypt's system by
replacing the SA-6, an old Russian short-range missile.
</P>
<P>
   However, Cohen told reporters in Cairo after talks with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak that a sale price had not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen later arrived in Jordan on the third leg of his Middle
East tour, which has already taken him to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   He also praised ''contacts'' between Egyptian and Israeli
military personnel at the Army War College in Carlisle, Pa., last
year during a seminar on non-war military exercises like responding
to natural disasters and peacekeeping duties.
</P>
<P>
   The contacts, he said, ''will hopefully lead to cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to Libya, Cohen said that Washington's policy on the
North African state it has been at loggerheads with for years has
not changed, despite a visit by a U.S. delegation to Tripoli last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, he said, was obliged to send officials there to
determine whether Libya was a safe travel destination in accordance
with an American law governing the foreign travel by Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. policy toward Libya will remain the same until
''there is a renouncing of support for terrorism and until there is
a full compensation for the Pan Am 103,'' victims, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 270 people died when the Boeing 747 airliner exploded
over Lockerbie, Scotland in 1988. Two Libyan men, believed to be
connected to the Tripoli government, are being tried in the
Netherlands in connection with the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   In Jordan, Cohen said there was also no change in Washington's
policy toward Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ''We intend to continue our containment policy and hope there
can be a regime change so the Iraqi people can have a new
leadership and be fully integrated in the international
community,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen was specifically critical of Saddam Hussein, and blamed
him for the suffering of the Iraqi people under U.N. sanctions
imposed in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is only one person inflicting harm on the Iraqi people
and that is Saddam Hussein,'' Cohen told reporters after separate
meetings with Prime Minister Abdur-Ra'uf S. Rawabdeh and the
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Lt. Gen. Mohammad Malkawi.
</P>
<P>
   Talks with King Abdullah II, the Jordanian monarch, were
scheduled for later Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 1833 </TRAILER>
