<DOCNO> APW20000404.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Lowers Suspects Charges  </HEADLINE>
By RODRIQUE NGOWI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAR ES SALAAM, Tanzania (AP) -- Tanzanian prosecutors reduced
charges Tuesday against a man who had been facing 11 counts of
murder in the 1998 bombing of the American embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Rashidi Salehe Hemed, a Tanzanian, now faces one count of
conspiracy to commit murder, which carries a maximum penalty of 14
years in prison. A conviction on the murder charges could meant
death by hanging.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an admission that the prosecution has no evidence
against the accused,'' defense lawyer Fauz Twaib told reporters on
Tuesday at the Kisutu magistrate court in the Indian Ocean port of
Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate comment from prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven people, all Africans, were killed and 86 injured in the
August 7, 1998, attack of the U.S. Embassy in Dar es Salaam. A
near-simultaneous bombing of the U.S. Embassy in neighboring Kenya
killed 213 people, including 12 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   On March 20, authorities dropped all charges against alleged
Hemed accomplice Egyptian Mustapha Mahmoud Said Ahmed, and deported
him to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining charge against Hemed alleges that he conspired
with five others to carry out the bombing. Four of those are at
large. The fifth, Tanzanian Khalfan Khamisi Mohamed, faces charges
in the United States in connection with the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   No date has been set for Hemed's trial.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution will present statements by 63 witnesses, three
forensic reports from the FBI and 11 death certificates to support
the charge against Hemed, court documents filed by the prosecutors
show.
</P>
<P>
   The United States accuses Saudi dissident Osama bin Laden of
masterminding and funding the twin embassy attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 1835 </TRAILER>
