<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rivals Facing Off in Venezuela  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA HERNANDEZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- They were comrades in a failed coup
against a government they both thought corrupt. But now Hugo Chavez
and Francisco Arias are facing off in a battle over who will rule
this oil-rich but poverty stricken nation.
</P>
<P>
   And Arias is doing the unthinkable: gaining support in a
presidential race many believed Chavez had already won.
</P>
<P>
   Because Arias is not linked to the old political parties that
Chavez's leftist coalition has all but destroyed, he is making
inroads as an independent candidate free from ties to the
discredited politics of Venezuela's past.
</P>
<P>
   Many in this South American nation of 23 million people believe
Arias is the only man who can unseat Chavez in the May 28 election.
</P>
<P>
   A new constitution pushed through by Chavez last year requires
most public offices, including the presidency, Congress,
governorships and local councils, to be ''re-legitimized'' through
the May elections.
</P>
<P>
   While Chavez speaks of ''revolution,'' Arias emphasizes good
management. Soft-spoken Arias' call for reconciliation between rich
and poor stands in sharp contrast to Chavez's rousing speeches
attacking the news media, the Roman Catholic Church and business
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Arias was one of three of Chavez's fellow coup leaders who
recently broke with the president, saying he had betrayed the goals
of their 1992 rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   He rarely refers to Chavez by name, instead calling him ''the
caudillo'' -- or strongman -- and accusing him of becoming an
autocrat.
</P>
<P>
   ''He wants to have all the power,'' said Arias. ''He is moving
this country toward anarchy and pitting rich against poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Chavez and his supporters are busy painting Arias as
the candidate of the oligarchy, someone who would roll back the
''social revolution'' started by Chavez when he became president a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   A poll taken in mid-March gave Chavez a mere 11-point lead in
the race for the presidency, indicating unexpectedly strong support
for Arias. The poll had a margin of error of 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   However, El Nacional newspaper showed Chavez 28 points ahead in
a private poll published Tuesday. That survey had a margin of error
of 2.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The two polls were taken within days of each other, and the
reason for the wide discrepancy was not immediately clear.
</P>
<P>
   Born in San Cristobal, in the western state of Tachira, Arias
was groomed for a life inside the Catholic Church, not politics.
</P>
<P>
   ''My mother was very old fashioned and believed the first born
was always either a doctor or a priest,'' Arias, sitting in a
sparsely furnished office in the upscale Caracas neighborhood of
Chuao, told The Associated Press on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Arias's mother enrolled her son in a seminary hoping he would
become a priest. But by 19, he had joined the army, where he spent
the next 20 years rising through the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 Arias and four other military commanders led some 15,000
rebel troops in an ill-fated attempt to overthrow then-President
Carlos Perez Andres.
</P>
<P>
   Arias and Chavez both spent two years in jail before being
pardoned in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   After his release, Arias joined his wife and two children in
Zulia where he successfully ran for governor of the oil-rich state
in 1995 and was re-elected in 1998. He left that job last month to
run for president.
</P>
<P>
   Like Venezuela's last presidential campaign only 16 months ago,
this one is dividing Venezuelans.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed at what they see as Chavez's anti-democratic tendencies
and his failure to heal the economy and control crime, several
former Chavez supporters have flocked to Arias.
</P>
<P>
   ''The entire process of democracy was derailed by Chavez,'' says
William Izarra, a former lieutenant colonel who also took part in
the coup attempt. ''The president makes all decisions without
consulting the people.''
</P>
<P>
   But Arias's critics say he isn't as squeaky clean as he claims.
He is under investigation by Venezuela's pro-Chavez interim
legislature for misuse of state funds.
</P>
<P>
   Arias has denied the charges, saying the investigation is
politically motivated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
