<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7 Sentenced To Death For Genocide  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- A Rwandan court sentenced seven people to
death for their involvement in the 1994 genocide here, state-run
Radio Rwanda reported Tuesday, as the country observed a national
week of mourning for the victims.
</P>
<P>
   The sentences were handed down Monday in the southwestern town
of Cyangugu, where last week eight other defendants were given
death sentences.
</P>
<P>
   All were convicted of genocide and crimes against humanity in
the three-month slaughter of more than 500,000 minority Tutsis and
politically moderate Hutus.
</P>
<P>
   Flags were lowered to half-staff and nightclubs closed
throughout the tiny central African nation this week, as part of
the annual week of mourning for the genocide.
</P>
<P>
   The observance will culminate Friday, when the remains of
thousands of Tutsis hacked or shot to death in a Kigali suburb will
be excavated from a mass grave and given a proper burial. Similar
reburial ceremonies will be held countrywide.
</P>
<P>
   After the Tutsi-led Rwandan Patriotic Front ousted the former
extremist Hutu government and stopped the massacres in July 1994,
victims were quickly buried in mass graves to avoid the danger of
infection, often without identification or the knowledge of their
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   So far, more than 2,500 people have been tried, from among the
125,000 genocide suspects crowded inside Rwandan jails. About 300
have been sentenced to death; 22 were executed in public on April
24, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A U.N. tribunal is trying top genocide suspects separately in
the northern Tanzanian town of Arusha. The maximum sentence it can
impose is life in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
