<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Blasted for Aid Delay  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration blasted a plan by
Senate leaders to delay a $13 billion emergency spending bill that
includes money for combating drugs in Colombia, peacekeeping in
Kosovo and cleaning up after Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   ''I firmly believe that any action to delay consideration of
these pressing needs would impose unnecessary cost to Americans at
home, to our interests abroad and to our military readiness around
the world,'' President Clinton said in a statement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the top U.S. military commander for Latin America
implored Congress not to delay action on the portion of the package
that would help Colombia and its neighbors fight drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Marine Gen. Charles Wilhelm, commander in chief of the U.S.
Southern Command, told the Senate Armed Services Committee that the
House-passed spending measure, which designates $1.7 billion for
drug interdiction, ''is crucial to ... plans that, if executed,
will strike at the heart of the illicit drug trade.''
</P>
<P>
   The package would ''contribute to the overall security and
stability of a region of rapidly growing strategic importance to
the United States,'' Wilhelm said. He noted that Colombia is now
the world's largest producer of cocaine and fourth among heroin
producers.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the State and Defense Departments joined
Wilhelm in urging Congress not to delay action on the anti-drug
package.
</P>
<P>
   The administration plan ''is not perfect, it's subject to
change. But we are very concerned that if it is voted down, or
endlessly delayed, we will have lost an opportunity to cap this
drug production, which is right now out of control,'' said Brian
Sheridan, assistant secretary of defense for special operations.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would help Colombia's hard-pressed government battle
drug traffickers and the leftist rebels who protect them. The money
is mainly for training and equipping Colombian troops and police
with equipment including 63 helicopters, along with intelligence
operations, incentives for farmers to grow other crops and
assistance for neighbors Peru, Ecuador and Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., decided
to indefinitely postpone votes scheduled by the Senate
Appropriations Committee on the overall emergency spending package.
</P>
<P>
   John Czwartacki, Lott's spokesman, defended the decision
Tuesday. He told reporters Lott supports the spending but doesn't
see a need to consider the legislation on an ''emergency'' basis,
as the House did. ''We can use the regular appropriations
process,'' Czwartacki said.
</P>
<P>
   Lott spoke to Clinton on Monday about the delay. After Clinton
issued his criticism on Tuesday, Lott released his own, saying that
''in fact'' Clinton had offered to help ''in getting the process
moving along'' so the money for Colombia and the other items could
be provided in Congress' regular spending process.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said Lott's decision
was ''a mistake. The House passed (the package) quickly for a
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   The House bill includes $9 billion for the military, including
$2 billion to reimburse the Pentagon for costs of Kosovo
peacekeeping. It also would provide $2 billion for Hurricane Floyd,
which battered the East Coast last fall, and other disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Wilhelm and other witnesses before the Armed Services Committee
portrayed the drug-trafficking problem in Colombia as steadily
worsening.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm convinced that we're on the right path in Colombia,'' the
Marine general said. ''The (spending package) is an important and
timely step in the right direction. Colombia is a worthy cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman John Warner , R-Va., spoke of the effect of
the narcotics trade on fledging and fragile democratic governments
in the region. ''The spillover effect from the narcotrafficking in
Colombia could prove enormously destabilizing to the surrounding
nations,'' Warner said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska,
told reporters that delaying a vote on the emergency bill could
only make it grow larger, particularly with a spring recess coming
up.
</P>
<P>
   Senators go home to their states and come back wanting to add
millions to help cover economic problems faced by their
consituents, Stevens said. ''Every time they go home, they face
disaster,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 1848 </TRAILER>
