<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Promotes Saving  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration, worried that
Americans aren't saving enough, is launching a new effort aimed at
helping people become more financially fluent.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department with the support of financial education
groups, banks and others is forming a national coalition, called
the National Partners for Financial Empowerment, to help people
sharpen their financial skills and educate them about ways to save.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans in Congress took the administration to task for
vetoing their efforts to help people save.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House
Ways and Means Committee, criticized President Clinton's veto of a
big tax relief bill last year that included provisions that would
have provided tax breaks for a variety of savings options.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the best ways to encourage savings is not to tax it,
but every time we send a bill to President Clinton to cut taxes on
savings, he vetoes them,'' Archer said in a statement. Similar GOP
proposals offered this year also face a possible veto.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition will create an Internet Web site to provide people
with resources to become financially literate, Treasury Secretary
Lawrence Summers said in remarks prepared for delivery Tuesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the coalition will set up national
conferences featuring experts to discuss subjects such as personal
financial management, saving for retirement and ways employers,
schools and other institutions can help educate consumers about
their finances.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the rate of personal savings, or savings as a
percentage of after-tax income, fell to 0.8 percent, a record low.
That rate isn't as dire as it would seem because it doesn't include
gains realized on savings from such things as rising stock market
values and higher real estate values from homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is critical to our economic health that we raise personal
saving,'' Summers said in his prepared remarks. ''And it is
critical for families because it influences their capacity to
manage what is new in the New Economy: not least, the fact that
people are living much longer than before.''
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the new coalition include the American Savings
Education Council, the Consumer Federation of America, Chase
Manhattan Bank, Bank of America and Fidelity Investments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
