<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Bush Trails Gore on Education  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush has gained public trust in
handling several key campaign issues, but slipped behind Al Gore on
the issue he has given the most emphasis in his campaign --
education, says a new poll.
</P>
<P>
   Education topped the list when people were asked how important
different issues were to them in the presidential race, according
to an ABC News-Washington poll on the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   When asked who they trust to do a better job of improving
schools and education, 48 percent said Gore, the likely Democratic
nominee, and 39 percent said Bush, the expected GOP candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates were tied on the issue a month ago, and
Republicans see a strong showing on education as a key for Bush to
cut into the traditional Democratic advantage among women.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had a 10-point lead among men and Gore had a 10-point lead
among women in the poll that showed the two in a dead heat, 47
percent for Gore to 46 percent for Bush among registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also appeared to hold the upper hand on several specific
education policies -- from increasing federal funding to penalizing
poorly performing schools and subsidizing private school tuition in
districts that perform poorly.
</P>
<P>
   -- Almost two-thirds of Americans said federal spending on
education should be increased, with the majority saying it should
go up ''a great deal.'' Gore's proposals are more sweeping.
</P>
<P>
   -- Six in 10 oppose cuts in federal funding to school districts
whose students don't improve on standardized tests. Such a proposal
is a cornerstone of Bush's education portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   -- About half oppose giving federal money to parents to help send
their children to private schools in areas where public schools
aren't improving. Bush supports this idea, Gore opposes it.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Bush rolled out a $5 billion reading program to
combat illiteracy in elementary school students and a $3 billion
plan to help train and retain teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has gained an advantage in public trust on issues such as
taxes, crime, the death penalty, the economy, campaign finance and
moral standards. Gore leads on the issues of education, the
environment, women's issues, abortion rights and patients' rights.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bush were about even on the issues of Social Security,
foreign affairs, the federal budget and gun control in the poll of
1,083 adults taken Thursday through Sunday. It has an error margin
of plus or minus 3 percentage points, larger for subgroups.
</P>
<P>
   Gore had a lead over Bush in a New York poll out Monday, while
Bush had a double-digit lead in a survey in traditionally
Republican Indiana. The two were tied in a Wisconsin poll.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 1859 </TRAILER>
