<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Program Trading Not To Blame  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- What looked like a freefall in U.S. stock
markets Tuesday turned out to be a bungee jump. It's easy to blame
the whiplash effect on program trading, but experts say
computer-driven buying and selling was not a primary factor in the
500-point swings in the Nasdaq composite index and Dow Jones
industrials.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes, the markets have been volatile recently, but not because
of program trading,'' said Charles Jones, a finance professor at
Columbia University's Business School.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, experts said margin calls -- when investors must sell
stock that was bought with borrowed money -- and investor psychology
played a bigger role in Tuesday's volatility.
</P>
<P>
   ''Program trading'' became an evil phrase following the 1987
stock market crash.
</P>
<P>
   Program trading is the computer-driven buying or selling of
baskets of 15 or more stocks with a total value of at least $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   In one type of computer trading known as index arbitrage, a
trader uses computers that constantly monitor stocks, futures and
options markets. The computer gives buy and sell signals when there
is an opportunity to profit from a spread in price.
</P>
<P>
   When the stock is worth more in the current market than the
futures market, for example, the arbitrageur sells the stock and
buys the future, pocketing the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of the official reports really exonerated program trading
back then,'' Jones said. ''And if anything, it's less important now
... There's less money to be made from index arbitrage.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the NYSE introduced ''collars'' in 1998 that kick
in when the Dow Jones industrial average rises or falls by 200
points or more within an hour as it did Tuesday. The collars
restrict a index arbitrageurs from accelerating the market's move.
</P>
<P>
   But experts point out that index arbitrage accounts for just 13
percent of all program trading and about 3 percent of the volume on
the Big Board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 1900 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000404.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Students arrested for takeover of president's office  </HEADLINE>
By HADLEY PAWLAK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- State University of New York at Albany
students protesting cafeteria workers' conditions and a ban on a
kitchen workers' union took over the school president's office and
had a small altercation with university police Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 students charged with trespassing after occupying the
president's office for more than four hours are members of
SweatFree SUNY, an anti-sweatshop group that blames three recent
cases of E. coli that were traced to a campus cafeteria on
''sweatshop-like conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the university professor's union and Local 471, a
hotel and motel employees union, also passed out flyers supporting
a unionized cafeteria and ''Union Yes'' buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Sodexho-Marriott, the food service provider at SUNY Albany, has
refused to recognize the SUNY Albany cafeteria workers' desire to
organize, said Tim McHugh, an organizer and Local 471 board member.
He said dining hall employees work without health benefits and
pension plans, and are not allowed to talk about work conditions
while on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ''Is Sodexho-Marriot against the constitution?'' McHugh asked.
''This is stuff the Gestapo pulled.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Skidmore College students occupied the president's
office on that campus to demonstrate Skidmore's contract with
Sodexho-Marriott.
</P>
<P>
   SUNY officials, saying they were speaking for Sodexho-Marriott,
would not comment on the student's charges. But SUNY-Albany
President Karen Hitchcock released a statement saying the sit-in
and a chanting protest outdoors were ''not responsible student
activism.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of SweatFree SUNY entered Hitchcock's office around 8:30
a.m. and said they would not leave until the school agreed not to
renew its contract with Sodexho-Marriot. They also called for the
president to sign a code of conduct prohibiting sweatshop labor in
the production of goods bearing the SUNY Albany name.
</P>
<P>
   While the students occupied Hitchcock's office, a group of about
25 other students, many wearing red headbands, assembled below the
second story office window. Some students beat bongos while others
sang: ''As students united, we'll never be defeated.''
</P>
<P>
   Students inside the president's office flashed peace signs out
the window and punched the air.
</P>
<P>
   When one student from Hitchcock's office yelled to the crowd
below at 12:30 p.m. that police had called with ''their first of
three warning, the third resulting in police action,'' the group
below began a chant of ''hell no, we won't go.''
</P>
<P>
   The SUNY Albany police department locked administration doors to
prevent more protesters from entering the building and arrested the
students in Hitchcock's office shortly before 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Kozlowski, a member of SweatFree SUNY, said she was
outraged by the administration's actions.
</P>
<P>
   Two students claimed that police struck them when they tried to
enter the administration building to watch the arrests. And while
the arrested students left peacefully, the university said two
officers went to the emergency room with minor injuries following
an altercation with protesters outside the building.
</P>
<P>
   The university police department is investigating the
altercation.
</P>
<P>
   The students charged in the sit-in were told to appear in Albany
City Court Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
