<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Condor Flies To Freedom  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FILLMORE, Calif. (AP) -- Nearly 14 years after she was captured
to help save her species from extinction, a California condor
spread her wings Tuesday and soared to freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Known only as Adult Condor No. 8, or AC-8, the vulture hopped
out of a pen and extended her wings to their 9-foot span in the
warm sunshine bathing remote cliffs of the Sespe Condor Sanctuary,
northwest of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ''It looked like she knew right where she was,'' condor recovery
team leader John Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, two younger condors raised in the Los Angeles Zoo
took off to join AC-8 and experience life in the wild for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   California condors once roamed North America. Their numbers fell
as human settlements reduced food sources. Others were shot or
poisoned by lead fragments in carcasses left by hunters, and poison
bait and pollutants killed more. By the 1970s there were only a few
dozen left.
</P>
<P>
   There are now 49 California condors flying free in California
and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Before she was captured in June 1986, AC-8 was the last female
and the one of only six California condors remaining in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   While at the San Diego Wild Animal Park, AC-8 produced 12
offspring. She is the first condor from the breeding program to
retaste freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Condors can live for 40 years or more. AC-8 is believed to be
between 28 and 40.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
