<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Praises Md. Gun Bill  </HEADLINE>
By SETH HETTENA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) -- President Clinton said Tuesday he hoped
Maryland legislation requiring built-in locks for all new handguns
would serve as a national example, while the National Rifle
Association said the process was corrupted to get gun control at
any cost.
</P>
<P>
   ''Maryland joins a growing number of states across the country
that are taking actions to make guns safer and to keep guns out of
the wrong hands,'' Clinton said in a statement. ''I challenge the
Congress to enact gun safety legislation before the one-year
anniversary of the Columbine tragedy on April 20th.''
</P>
<P>
   The Maryland bill, which passed Monday night, ends the sale of
conventional handguns in 2003. After that, new handguns will have
to be equipped with built-in locks. Until then, all guns sold will
have to be equipped with external trigger locks, beginning in
October. No other state has approved such a measure.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, Massachusetts' attorney general said the state
would use consumer-protection laws to begin a ban on cheap
''Saturday night specials'' and require child-proofing devices on
any gun sold in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called Maryland Gov. Parris Glendening to congratulate
him on successfully shepherding the bill through a legislative
maze. Of the 49 Republicans in the General Assembly, only five --
two in the House and three in the Senate, including the minority
leader -- voted for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   A rare parliamentary procedure was used to go around a
conservative committee and force the bill to the Senate floor. The
Democratic governor also said he used his budgetary powers to
garner support for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   James Jay Baker, the NRA's chief lobbyist, said the legislative
process had been corrupted by passage of a bad law in a
''gun-control-at-any-cost political strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard for citizens to be heard when the governor bypasses
normal legislative procedures and unabashedly twists arms with the
state's budget resources,'' Baker said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Baker echoed a criticism from Maryland Republicans who said
Glendening, who leaves office in 2003, was rushing the bill through
to curry favor with Clinton and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Maryland General Assembly: http://mlis.state.md.us
</P>
<P>
   National Rifle Association: http://www.nrahq.org
</P>
</TEXT>
