<HEADLINE> Washn Arts Announces 2 Premieres  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Washington Performing Arts Society will
celebrate its 35th anniversary during the 2000-2001 season with two
world premieres, the group said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   They include a chamber music piece by Pulitzer Prize-winning
American composer William Bolcolm for violinist Isaac Stern's 80th
birthday, commissioned the Kennedy Center's Abe Fortas Memorial
Fund. Stern is set to play the selection March 10, 2001, with
pianist Jonathan Biss and the Emerson String Quartet at the Kennedy
Center Concert Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Bolcolm teaches at the University of Michigan-Ann Arbor.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Nov. 10 and 11, the White Oak Dance Project will
present a work the society commissioned from Choreographer Yvonne
Rainer, her first in more than 20 years. The performances will be
at the Lisner Auditorium of the George Washington University.
</P>
