<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NY GOP Boss: No Support For Lazio  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The head of New York's Republican Party said
Tuesday he has talked to GOP leaders from across the state and
found no support for a possible run for the Senate by Rep. Rick
Lazio as an alternative to New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've taken the pulse of the party and there is nothing there
for Rick Lazio,'' state GOP Chairman William Powers said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lazio said that ''a handful'' of local county chairmen
''have called and pledged their support, so I know he's not
speaking for all county chairmen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Long Island congressman said he would not
identify the county chairmen who are supporting him without
checking with them first.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Lazio said the party might be ''blowing'' the Senate
race against Hillary Rodham Clinton by lining up behind Giuliani.
Lazio said he was ready to run, if the party wanted him to.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's slight lead in the polls over Clinton has evaporated
in recent days amid criticism of his handling of the shooting last
month of an unarmed black man by New York City police.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has said Giuliani, a Republican who supports abortion
rights and gun control, won't get the backing of New York's
Conservative Party. No Republican has won statewide office without
Conservative Party support since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Powers, a Giuliani supporter, said Tuesday that he has not yet
heard from Lazio about his possible entry into the Senate race and
has been too busy himself to call the congressman.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would urge him to support Mayor Giuliani,'' Powers said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Giuliani was campaigning across Long Island with
Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he wants to run, he should run and we'll have a primary,''
Giuliani said. ''But it's up to him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
