<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Camden gives poor response to state charges, officials say  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- With the city's first response labeled
insufficient, Camden now has less than two weeks to correct what
the state calls serious errors with its fiscal management policy.
</P>
<P>
   A day after Mayor Milton Milan was indicted on federal
corruption charges, the state Department of Community Affairs
commissioner said she would consider a takeover if Camden fails to
correct the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Milan respond point by point to the state ultimatum, but his
response failed to address the state concerns, Ulrich ''Al''
Steinberg, director of the division of local government services,
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not just looking at a piece of paper and saying this is
our plan. It's doing it,'' Steinberg said. ''With all that is going
on in Camden, I think it's time to say enough's enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Camden does not keep proper financial records, including a
general ledger and an account of city payouts, all of which are
required by state law, Community affairs Commissioner Jane Kenny
has said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny said she could withhold the state aid that Camden needs to
balance its budget. And without that aid, the city would fail to
meet its payroll and other obligations, Kenny said, one of the
legal criteria to have the state assume city operations.
</P>
<P>
   City officials have until April 15 to meet the deadline; all of
the items ordered by the state are required by state law, Steinberg
said. Each item has been requested since a state financial review
board began overseeing city finances in July, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our goal is to get the Milan administration to address these
issues and get its financial house in order,'' Steinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Milan did not return several calls to his City Hall office
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Now free on $150,000 bail, Milan has denied the criminal charges
against him and has criticized state threats of a takeover of the
city.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a former business partner of Milan agreed to help
build the corruption case against the indicted mayor in exchange
for a plea deal.
</P>
<P>
   Gholam ''Joseph'' Darakhshan, of Mount Laurel, is the third
admitted felon to help in the government's case against Milan, who
last week was indicted by a federal grand jury on 19 charges,
including allegations to which Darakhshan pleaded guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Darakhshan and Milan were partners in Atlas Contracting Inc.
between 1994 and 1996. Milan, a Democrat, was elected to city
council in 1995 and became mayor in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Darakhshan admitted that he and Milan accepted a $65,000 loan
from Jose ''J.R.'' Rivera, although he knew Rivera was associated
with drug dealers. The loan was for a 1994 contract that Atlas had
won to build a housing complex in the city. But authorities said
the loan was actually drug money disguised as a legitimate business
transaction. Rivera, a boyhood friend of Milan, last month was
convicted of conspiracy to distribute cocaine and money laundering
and faces up to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Darakhshan, who is out on $1 million bail, will be sentenced
after Milan's trial. He had faced at least 10 years in federal
prison without parole, but now could receive 12 to 18 months in
federal prison. He also could be sentenced to as little as house
arrest or probation for cooperating.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Caruso, Camden's former municipal prosecutor, also has
agreed to cooperate with prosecutors. Authorities say he and Milan
conspired to extort a $5,000 campaign contribution from the city's
public defender in exchange for his reappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Also cooperating with prosecutors is Ralph Natale, reputed to be
a former head of the Philadelphia-area mob. Natale, formerly of
Pennsauken, is now in federal custody.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-04-00 1950 </TRAILER>
