<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Watchdog Says HUD Report Broke Law  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Department of Housing and Urban
Development's chief watchdog said a report issued by Secretary
Andrew Cuomo broke the law by detailing how proposed Republican
budget cuts would hurt communities.
</P>
<P>
   Inspector General Susan Gaffney said the report, issued last
year and titled ''Losing Ground,'' violated a law barring federal
agencies from using taxpayer dollars to lobby Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''HUD's publication of 'Losing Ground' is only a small part of
the publicity and propaganda capability that the department has
built in the last two years,'' Gaffney wrote in a March 27 letter
to the U.S. Comptroller General obtained by The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office, Congress' nonpartisan
investigative arm, reviewed the report late last year and found no
violation. Gaffney asked the GAO to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   HUD spokesman David Egner said Tuesday that Gaffney was making a
''wild political accusation'' on an issue already resolved by the
GAO.
</P>
<P>
   ''We disagree with the inspector general's claim that the GAO is
wrong on the law,'' he said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gaffney has been sharply critical of various Cuomo initiatives
at HUD. Her office penned a scathing audit of the Community
Builders program, created by Cuomo as a customer service and
outreach arm for the agency. Republicans say the program is a waste
of money and should be scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   ''Losing Ground'' was distributed to Community Builders in
August 1999 with instructions to spread the word about the planned
cuts for fiscal year 2000. It also was mailed to the press, HUD
grantees, public interest groups and historically black colleges,
Gaffney said.
</P>
<P>
   HUD officials told Gaffney they ordered more than 32,000 copies
and spent about $20,600 on printing and mailing.
</P>
<P>
   ''At a time of unexpected national prosperity, Congress should
not rob the poorest Americans to provide reckless tax cuts and
create a new deficit,'' Cuomo wrote in the report's introduction.
</P>
<P>
   HUD officials said the proposed GOP cuts, most of which were not
enacted, would have meant 156,000 fewer housing units for
low-income families and homeless families, and would have cut
housing and other services for people with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The report never specifically asked members to lobby Congress,
but Gaffney said ''the message was understood by its recipients.''
She included an e-mail from one of the report's recipients, the
director of a HUD-funded community program, encouraging members of
her group to write to their members of Congress and urge them to
oppose the cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ''There has never been a report in the over 20 years I've been
in Congress that has raised a red flag the way that this one did,''
said Rep. James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., who asked for the GAO
investigation last November. ''This is something that's unique to
Cuomo's leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Sensenbrenner said he may ask the House Appropriations Committee
to cut Cuomo's next budget.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to send a clear message to any Cabinet secretary ...
that if you use taxpayer dollars to lobby Congress in a way that
violates the law, your personal empire is going to get cut,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Eggner questioned Gaffney's impartiality, saying ''it is a
well-known that the inspector general is a political tool of the
Republicans in Congress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 1951 </TRAILER>
