<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Committee passes MLK holiday bill  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- On the 32nd anniversary of Martin Luther
King's assassination, a key legislative committee approved a bill
which would force the town of Wallingford to close its offices in
honor of the civil rights leader's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   The Appropriation Committee approved the bill Tuesday on a 39-6
vote after defeating an amendment which would have required all
towns to close their offices on the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   King was assassinated in Memphis, Tenn., on April 4, 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Wallingford is the only municipality in the state that has not
voluntarily closed its offices for Martin Luther King Day, despite
a 1986 law making it a state holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Wallingford Mayor William Dickinson has said the controversy is
not about race, but a dispute with the town's labor unions.
Dickinson wants town workers to swap another holiday for King Day,
but union leaders want workers to get the day off as an extra paid
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson and union leaders are currently negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Jan. 17 holiday this year, three people wearing Ku
Klux Klan hoods and robes walked along Main Street in Wallingford.
On the holiday, one of those people stood near a church where a
celebration honoring King was being held.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to thank the Appropriations Committee and the entire
Legislature for dealing with our embarrassment in Wallingford,''
said Sen. Brian McDermott, D-Wallingford. ''Wallingford ... is not
a racist community. Quite frankly, I'm embarrassed that this bill
is here before us.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Alfred Adinolfi said the bill is unfair because it
singles out Wallingford.
</P>
<P>
   ''It discriminates against one town,'' said Adinolfi,
R-Cheshire. ''All I'm asking is that all towns ... observe Martin
Luther King Day.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee killed Adinolfi's proposal to require all towns to
close their offices on the holiday, but McDermott said he will push
for that provision when the bill is debated in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The bill still must clear the General Law Committee before
reaching the Senate, and McDermott said amending it now may hurt
its chances for easy passage.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Thomas Bozek, D-New Britain, said the controversy in
Wallingford was a ''labor issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it's fair for labor to come up and push the
envelope and twist it ... and make it a race type of issue,'' he
said. ''The bill should be defeated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-04-00 2005 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000404.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Watchdog says HUD report violates the law, calls for probe  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo's report
detailing how proposed GOP budget cuts to the Department of Housing
and Urban Development would hurt various communities is illegal,
the department's inspector general alleges.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office reviewed the report ''Losing
Ground'' late last year and found no violation. But Inspector
General Susan Gaffney asked the GAO, Congress' nonpartisan
investigative arm, to reconsider. She said the report violates law
barring federal agencies from using taxpayer dollars to lobby
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''HUD's publication of 'Losing Ground' is only a small part of
the publicity and propaganda capability that the department has
built in the last two years,'' Gaffney wrote in a letter to the
U.S. Comptroller General obtained by The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Gaffney is an independent watchdog within HUD, charged with
overseeing its programs. She was appointed by President Clinton in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   HUD spokesman David Eggner responded that the inspector general
was making a ''wild political accusation that deals with a question
that was already resolved by GAO.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We disagree with the inspector general's claim that the GAO is
wrong on the law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gaffney has been sharply critical of various Cuomo initiatives
at HUD, and her office penned a scathing audit of the Community
Builders program. The Community Builders program was created by
Cuomo as a customer service and outreach arm. Republicans say the
program is a waste of money and have called for it to be abolished.
</P>
<P>
   ''Losing Ground'' was distributed to Community Builders in
August 1999 with instructions to spread the word about the planned
cuts. It was also mailed to the press, grantees, public interest
groups and historically black colleges, Gaffney said.
</P>
<P>
   The report never specifically asked members to lobby Congress
but Gaffney said ''the message was understood by its recipients.''
She included an e-mail from one of the report's recipients, Chandra
Western, Director of the National Community Development
Association, that asked association members to write their members
of Congress to oppose the cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the cuts did not go through.
</P>
<P>
   HUD officials told Gaffney they printed more than 32,000 copies
of ''Losing Ground'' and spent about $20,600 on printing and
mailing.
</P>
<P>
   ''There has never been a report in the over 20 years I've been
in Congress that has raised a red flag the way that this one did,''
Rep. James Sensenbrenner said Tuesday. Sensenbrenner initially
asked the GAO to investigate the report in November 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is something that's unique to Cuomo's leadership,'' the
Wisconsin Republican said.
</P>
<P>
   Sensenbrenner said if it becomes clear that the report violated
the law he would ask the Appropriations Committee to penalize
Cuomo's budget.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to send a clear message to any cabinet secretary ...
that if you use taxpayer dollars to lobby Congress in a way that
violates the law, your personal Empire is going to get cut,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Eggner questioned Gaffney's impartiality saying ''it is a
well-known fact that the inmspector general is a tool of
Republicans in Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   HUD officials said the GOP cuts would have meant 156,000 fewer
housing units for low-income families and 16,000 homeless families
and persons with AIDS who would not receive vital housing and
related services.
</P>
<P>
   ''At a time of unexpected national prosperity, Congress should
not rob the poorest Americans to provide reckless tax cuts and
create a new deficit,'' Cuomo wrote in the report's introduction.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo, son of former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, is considering
running for his father's old job in 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-04-00 2018 </TRAILER>
