<HEADLINE> 2 Plead Innocent To Synagogue Arson  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER COLEMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Two white supremacist brothers already
accused of murdering a gay couple pleaded innocent Tuesday to
federal charges that they set fire to three synagogues and a
medical center that houses an abortion clinic.
</P>
<P>
   James Tyler Williams, 29, and Benjamin Matthew Williams, 31, are
charged with 13 counts of conspiracy to commit arson, arson,
destruction of religious property and the use of fire to commit a
felony.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers were brought to federal court here from the Shasta
County Jail, where they have been held since their July arrests for
allegedly killing Winfield Mowder, 40, and Gary Matson, 50.
</P>
<P>
   Shasta County District Attorney McGregor Scott is seeking the
death penalty in the murder case. Both men have pleaded innocent.
</P>
<P>
   The federal charges carry a maximum penalty of 235 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Magistrate Judge John Moulds read the two defendants
their rights and accepted their pleas. Both requested jury trials.
</P>
<P>
   They are due back in court in Redding on Friday to determine the
date of the murder trial -- the same day a federal judge in
Sacramento will determine a trial date on the arson charges. They
waived their right to appear at the federal hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The Williams brothers are accused of torching Congregation B'nai
Israel, Kenesset Israel Torah Center and Congregation Beth Shalom
early June 18, causing $1 million in damage.
</P>
<P>
   They are also charged in a July 2 arson at the Country Club
Medical Center, which houses the Choice Medical Group abortion
clinic. No one was injured in the attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
