<DOCNO> APW20000404.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seattle Violence Blamed on Adversary  </HEADLINE>
By PEGGY ANDERSEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- The Seattle Police Department concedes it was not
ready for trouble at the World Trade Organization meeting last
fall, though it had ample warning that tens of thousands of
demonstrators hoped to shut the gathering down.
</P>
<P>
   ''In retrospect, SPD commanders put their faith in historical
precedent -- the Seattle tradition of peaceful protest -- in
assessing the needs for policing the WTO event,'' Assistant Chief
Clark Kimerer wrote in the report made public Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The report was given to Chief Herbert V. Johnson, whose
predecessor -- Norm Stamper -- resigned over the handling of the
protests.
</P>
<P>
   Police were overwhelmed Nov. 30 when marches by several groups
converged on the core of downtown. In addition to clogging streets
and hampering the WTO gatherings, the crowds provided cover for a
small number of people who smashed windows and looted stores,
resulting in an estimated $3 million in property damage. More than
500 people were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Some officers ran out of the tear gas and pepper spray used to
disperse crowds. Many officers spent hours without food, water or
rest. Two hundred National Guard troops and 600 state troopers were
enlisted to restore order.
</P>
<P>
   The report recommends better planning next time, noting the city
had only about nine months to plan for the event, rather than the
14 to 24 months considered standard by the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem was that officials based plans on the 1993
Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation conference, held here without
incident, Assistant Chief Ed Joiner said. In future, the WTO
meeting will be the model, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Joiner said he had been confident the 400 officers he assigned
to WTO -- the largest force ever fielded here -- would be sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   But the department was ''taught a hard lesson by a well-trained
and equipped adversary,'' the report says. It cites demonstrators'
use of the Internet, walkie-talkies and cell phones and the
''critical mass achieved with the rapid marshaling of forces from
all directions nearly simultaneously.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point WTO delegates were attacked as they were leaving
their hotels, Joiner said -- while police were out in force at the
meeting sites.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the report's findings, the marches, the number of people
involved and their intention of shutting down the meeting all had
been well advertised.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're unfunded people largely, who do this without pay,'' said
Dennis Moynihan of Direct Action Network, which helped promote the
demonstrations and was one of several groups that met with police
to tell them what to expect. ''I do have a cell phone and a decent
pair of sneakers. That's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The report also says police did not prepare for a worst case
scenario because of ''the lack of outside funding sources'' to
reimburse the State Patrol, King County Sheriff's Department and
other area police agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Direct city costs for the WTO operations are estimated at about
$9.3 million -- $6.9 million of it incurred by the Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   The report notes that there were no deaths or serious injuries,
and that ''much if not all'' of the $17 million in estimated
holiday-shopping business losses was recovered by late December.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis by crowd- and riot-control experts is to be
completed in about three weeks, followed by City Council review.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 2024 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000404.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hastert To Reveal China Trade Vote  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Speaker Dennis Hastert will announce on
Wednesday a late May date for a House vote on granting China
permanent normal trade privileges, supporters of the legislation
said late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert planned a morning news conference to announce floor
action the week of May 22, said supporters, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   However, the dates for the debate are similar to a timetable
outlined this week by House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has been pushing for an early vote on
the legislation, fearful that delaying it into the summer could
make passage more difficult as the fall elections near.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which would end annual congressional reviews of
China's trade status, is being opposed by organized labor. Although
support in the Senate seemed assured, the battle in the House was
viewed as difficult because of divisions among Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Matsui, D-Calif., a leading supporter of the
measure, welcomed the decision of House GOP leaders to schedule a
vote in May as ''good news.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he now counts about 70-80 of the House's 211 Democrats
in support of the legislation. That's below the 90-100 Democrats
that House Republican leaders have said President Clinton should
produce -- but might be enough to produce a victory, given strong
GOP support, Matsui said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said in an interview, ''it will be a tough.''
</P>
<P>
   There remain many undecided votes, both sponsors and opponents
of the legislation said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a whole slew of undecideds. A lot of them still don't
think there's really going to be a vote -- so why commit?'' said
Matsui.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., a leading opponents, predicts that
as many as 150 Democrats will vote against the measure -- a number
Matsui and other sponsors dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is asking Congress to give China the same
permanent low-tariff access to U.S. markets it routinely gives all
but a handful of other trading partners. China's status now must be
renewed annually. The change would ease China's long-sought entry
into the World Trade Organization, the Geneva-based organization
that oversees rules for world trade.
</P>
<P>
   Labor opposes the legislation, citing China's poor record on
workers' rights. Labor unions also fear that expanding trade with
China will hurt U.S. manufacturing jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 2027 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000404.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Thomas Learns Lessons  </HEADLINE>
By VICKIE CHACHERE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas said
Tuesday that it took his younger brother's death to put the rigors
and benefits of public life into perspective.
</P>
<P>
   A grieving Thomas described for a gathering of attorneys an
intensely private moment after his brother Meyers died in January
after collapsing while jogging near his home in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ''I sat there and looked at the lifeless body of my brother, the
body without the spirit.'' Thomas said. ''I tried to make sense of
it.
</P>
<P>
   ''What it did was it put my life in perspective about what's
important. What's the purpose? Is it important to be popular? Is it
important to have agreement, to have unanimity? Or is it more
important to be principled?''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said it became clear to him at that moment that the
permanent things in life -- family, friends and faith, what he calls
the three Fs -- overshadowed all others.
</P>
<P>
   ''Being on the Supreme Court was meaningless suddenly,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, a justice since 1991, endured perhaps the most
controversial confirmation hearings in history when Anita Hill
accused him of sexual harassment. But he told the 300 members of
the Tampa Bay Chapter of the Federal Bar Association that the past
few weeks of work at the Supreme Court also have been difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought the longer I was there the cases would get easier,''
Thomas said. ''But frankly they are harder. They get harder when
you try to get them right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 2033 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
