<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Defends Withdrawal Option  </HEADLINE>
By SARI BASHI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- In the absence of a peace agreement, Israel
alone will decide the scope of its withdrawal from Lebanon, even if
it means a continued occupation of small areas of Lebanese
territory, a senior defense official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh also said Israel will not
disarm its paid Lebanese militias, something the U.N. has said
Israel must do in order to bring peace to southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Other Israeli officials warned that remaining inside even a tiny
part of Lebanon would cost Israel the international support it
seeks for the pullout, promised for July.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no party that can judge what is the border -- we will
decide from where to withdraw,'' Sneh told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Sneh said Israel would more or less pull back to a line to which
it withdrew following its 1978 invasion of Lebanon, marked by a
surveillance fence that approximates the international border.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, Israel reserves the right to retain about
seven outposts along the border, possibly including some located
several hundred yards into Lebanese territory.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Minister Yossi Beilin countered that anything less than
a full withdrawal would ruin attempts to enlist an international
presence to prevent attacks from within Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Europeans told me very clearly that a precondition for
their assistance to both sides is the withdrawal of Israel to the
international border and not to any other line,'' he told the AP.
</P>
<P>
   Israel had hoped to withdraw through a security agreement with
Syria, the main power in Lebanon, but negotiations broke off in
January and show no signs of being renewed.
</P>
<P>
   The Hezbollah group fighting to oust Israel from south Lebanon
said Sunday that even a withdrawal from 100 percent of Lebanese
territory would not guarantee the safety of Israel's border until
an overall Israeli-Arab peace agreement was reached.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman for the U.N. peacekeeping force in south Lebanon,
Timor Goksel, said that if Israel does not disarm the Lebanese
militia it pays and trains, the withdrawal will not be considered
complete, and U.N. troops will not be able to restore peace to the
area.
</P>
<P>
   Sneh said Israel had no plans to disarm the militiamen, who fear
retaliatory attacks from Hezbollah following an Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy Tuesday assured U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan that Israel will cooperate with United
Nations forces during the withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
