<BODY>
<HEADLINE> W. African Troops Begin Withdrawal  </HEADLINE>
By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- West African intervention troops
began formally pulling out of Sierra Leone, officials said Tuesday,
amid fears the withdrawal may leave a security vacuum following the
country's brutal eight-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
   About 150 soldiers from the Nigerian-led multinational force,
known as ECOMOG, flew out of Lungi airport near Freetown on Monday
and Tuesday, and more were to depart this week, senior ECOMOG
officials said on condition of he not be named.
</P>
<P>
   Force spokesman Chris Olukolade has said the withdrawal of the
remaining 2,000 soldiers would be complete by in mid-April. About
2,500 former ECOMOG troops will remain under the command of U.N.
peacekeepers until late June.
</P>
<P>
   ''A dangerous security vacuum may arise when the pullout of
ECOMOG's remaining troops, mostly Nigerians, is finished,''
Freetown's For Di People newspaper in a Tuesday editorial. The
force was first posted here in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah's spokesman, Septimus Kai Kai,
played down the fears, saying rebel and government officials
continued to make peace gains.
</P>
<P>
   ''The pullout not withstanding, I feel positive about the
general situation in the country,'' Kai Kai said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the government and rebels signed a peace accord last July,
ECOMOG's main contributor, Nigeria, has gradually scaled down its
role, complaining it could not afford the commitment.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the U.N. force is expected to be boosted from 6,500
to 11,500 soldiers by July. But many Sierra Leoneans have expressed
skepticism that the U.N. troops can enforce the fragile peace.
</P>
<P>
   While authorized to use force if necessary, the peacekeepers --
mainly Indians, Kenyans, Nigerians -- have avoided confronting
ex-rebels who continue to rape and pillage many rural villages with
impunity, according to human rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, U.N. peacekeeping contingents have themselves
been robbed in broad daylight by rebels, who killed tens of
thousands of civilians and intentionally maimed many more during
the war.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials themselves have said the international force is
intended as ''peacekeepers, not peace-enforcers.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 21,000 pro-government militia and rebel fighters had
disarmed by the end of March, Kai Kai said, adding that rebel and
government officials continued to hold regular talks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet tens of thousands of rebels have so far refused to give up
their guns, U.N. officials say, and some have set up refuge in
remote bases in Liberia, which aided the rebel struggle during the
war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 2129 </TRAILER>
