<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Say Japan Volcano Dangerous  </HEADLINE>
By GINNY PARKER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DATE, Japan (AP) -- As the sun set Tuesday on Mount Usu, clouds
of thick black smoke poured from of one of its gaping craters, and
scientists warned that a massive eruption could be brewing.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,416-foot volcano on the northern Japanese island of
Hokkaido broke its 22-year silence Friday, spouting gas, smoke and
debris. More craters have since burst open on its flanks, and magma
is straining upward against the mountain's skin.
</P>
<P>
   Hokkaido University geologist Tadahide Ui said he and other
experts have seen signs of a developing ''lava dome'' -- a
cone-shaped mass of magma that nudges its way through the Earth's
crust.
</P>
<P>
   The formation of the dome could be accompanied by a huge
eruption of hot gas and rock.
</P>
<P>
   It would dwarf the puffs now spewing from the volcano, racing
down the slopes and incinerating everything in its path, Ui said.
</P>
<P>
   Known as a pyroclastic flow, such an occurrence would be similar
to the eruption of Mount St. Helens in the United States in 1980,
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars were not sure when or even if the huge eruption would
happen, though they said the volcano's history suggested it could
be months away.
</P>
<P>
   Some 13,000 people were still barred from their homes Tuesday as
they waited to see what the volcano would do. Some stayed with
friends and relatives, while others remained in emergency shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Video taken from helicopters showed major destruction in the
scenic resort towns that surround the mountain: buildings smashed
by boulders, a highway torn in half, walls blackened with volcanic
soot.
</P>
<P>
   In the village of Toya, rock and steam burst forth from a crater
that opened up next to a kindergarten, and flying boulders punched
window-sized holes through its walls. Sticky black mud stained the
building's white surface.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Usu is different from the more familiar, picturesque
volcanoes found in Hawaii, which spout fountains of red-hot lava
into the sky.
</P>
<P>
   The magma moving under Usu's surface is very hard, and the
volcano spits rock and gases rather than liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Usu erupts very infrequently -- about once every 30 years,
compared to about once a month for some Hawaiian volcanoes. It is
also a relatively new volcano, its first eruption occurring in
1663. Its last, in 1977-1978, claimed two lives in mudslides.
</P>
<P>
   Locals have watched it drastically change shape over the past
few decades, going from two separate peaks to a squat and rugged
lump.
</P>
<P>
   Usu is the source of numerous hot springs, and soil enriched by
volcanic ash makes its slopes perfect for growing vegetables and
melons.
</P>
<P>
   But farmers, as well as merchants, are unable to tend to their
crops or their businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Local business owners predicted that their difficulties will
continue long after the danger has passed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It looks like I'm hanging in there, but inside I'm crying,''
said Setsuko Hasegawa, 52, who had to close up the three bars she
runs in Toya village and flee to the nearby town of Date.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa worried her staff of some 20 hostesses and dancers will
have found work somewhere else by the time the evacuation order is
lifted, and that regular customers will not have the money to come
back.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hasegawa holds no hard feelings. After 34 years in the
close-knit Usu community, she can't imagine leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ''I love the mountain, and I can't live somewhere else,'' she
said. ''I'll go back to business there eventually. There's no
question about that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 2130 </TRAILER>
