<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Delivers 50 Fewer Jets  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- The Boeing Co. delivered 50 fewer jetliners than
planned in the first quarter because of delays caused by the 40-day
strike by engineers and technical workers, the company reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the aerospace giant still plans to deliver about 490
jetliners by year's end as projected, down from last year's record
620, the company said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's great to have our engineering and technical team back,''
chairman and chief executive officer Phil Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   The 17,000 employees who returned to work March 20 have been
working to get the company back on track, said company spokesman
Larry McCracken.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be some impact in the first quarter, maybe in the
second quarter, but nothing to change our margins for the year,''
McCracken said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing delivered 75 commercial planes, down from the 125
originally planned, in the first three months of the year. Fifteen
planes were delivered in March.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Boeing delivered 26 military aircraft in the
quarter, including three C-17 transports, 14 fighter jets, two
Apache helicopters, one Chinook helicopter, four training jets and
two Delta II rockets.
</P>
<P>
   After the strike ended, Boeing chief financial officer Debby
Hopkins said the company would still meet its year 2000 financial
goals, with revenues remaining at $50 billion and profit margins at
around 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins said deliveries in the second quarter would also be
affected by the strike, but she expected the declines to be offset
by increased commercial deliveries in the year's second half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
