<HEADLINE> France Hunting Reform Bill Advances  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Some 50 hunting dogs joined the protest Tuesday,
but that didn't stop lawmakers tentatively passing a bill that to
revise French hunting traditions so they conform with European
Union standards.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial bill passed by a thin margin -- 275-252. The
five deputies from the Green Party of Environment Minister
Dominique Voynet, sponsor of the legislation, voted for the bill at
the last minute despite reservations so as not to endanger their
minister's standing.
</P>
<P>
   A first reading, the bill must now go to the Senate for possible
modification. However, the government hopes the bill will become
law by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters from the Hunting, Fishing, Nature and Tradition
parties had threatened to turn up in front of the National Assembly
with 577 dogs -- one for each deputy. However, only some 50 leashed
hunting dogs howled while lawmakers cast their votes.
</P>
<P>
   The small but vocal party complains that the bill fails to
recognize the local traditions ''that add to the originality of
French hunting.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill, debated for 25 hours last week, makes concessions to
hunters, like allowing night hunting in 20 regions where it is a
tradition and extending for two hours before dawn and after
nightfall waterfowl hunting.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the bill forbids hunting one day per week in
the hunting season and sets up controls over hunting the finances
of hunting federations so that funds won't go to demonstrations or
Saint-Josse's party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 2212 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
