<HEADLINE> FBI Saves Kidnapped Boy; 7 Charged  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A 3-year-old boy kidnapped from a wealthy
suburb and held for more than two weeks for a $1.5 million ransom
was rescued by an FBI SWAT team.
</P>
<P>
   The San Marino boy was safely returned to his parents Monday
night, and kidnapping charges were filed Tuesday against five men
and two teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was found when FBI agents raided an apartment in South
Central Los Angeles where the kidnappers had left him in the care
of two women, said agent Stephen Wiley. The rescue operation was
peaceful, Wiley said.
</P>
<P>
   Names of the victim and his family were not released.
Authorities would only say the father is a prominent Asian-American
executive in the garment industry.
</P>
<P>
   All of those arrested are of Asian descent.
</P>
<P>
   San Marino Police Chief Arl Farris said the 3-year-old boy was
taken on March 20 by two masked men who forced their way into the
family's home at midafternoon. The police chief said no ransom was
paid.
</P>
<P>
   San Marino is a wealthy enclave northeast of downtown Los
Angeles better known for the Huntington Library than for major
crimes. Almost entirely residential, the city's median home price
is $750,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
