<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Notes From Monday's BB Games  </HEADLINE>
AMERICAN LEAGUE
Royals-Blue Jays
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: The Royals used the same lineup against LHP David
Wells on opening day as they did against RHP Roy Halladay.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: Manager Jim Fregosi turned 58 on Tuesday. ... RHP Roy
Halladay made 18 starts for Toronto last season. He was 5-6 with
3.97 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Red Sox-Mariners
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: Closer Derek Lowe reportedly is close to signing a $10
million, four-year contract with an option year with the team with
the Red Sox. ... All three games of this series will be televised
live on NHK-TV in Tokyo because of the presence of Seattle closer
Kazuhiro Sasaki.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: Jay Buhner, Seattle's regular right fielder who had
been in its opening night lineup for nine straight years, did not
start Tuesday night's opener against Boston's Pedro Martinez. He
was 0-for-8 lifetime with eight strikeouts against the two-time Cy
Young Award winner. Mariners manager Lou Piniella said Buhner would
be back in the starting lineup against the Red Sox on Wednesday and
Thursday nights. ... DH Edgar Martinez took batting practice before
the game and then was put in the lineup by Piniella. Martinez was
hit by a pitch in his left elbow in the final week of spring
training and it has been bothering him. ''We were a little
concerned, but it loosened up,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
White Sox-Rangers
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: The White Sox are beginning their 100th season in the
AL with a 10-game, 11-day road trip that will take them to three
different time zones. After opening with four games in Texas, they
play three in Oakland and three in Tampa Bay before finally playing
their home opener April 14. ... Pitcher Kip Wells made his first
start in his home state of Texas. The native Texan and former
Baylor standout defeated Texas last year in Chicago He was the
first White Sox player from the 1998 draft to reach the majors.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: Rafael Palmeiro was at first base and David Segui was at
designated hitter on Tuesday night, a switch from opening day.
Manager Johnny Oates is alternating the two in those positions for
the first four games. ''After that, we'll just look at the lineup
card and see where they are,'' Oates said. ... Palmeiro won his
third Gold Glove last year despite playing just 28 games at first
base. Segui, acquired in a trade with Toronto during the spring,
needs just 34 more games at first base to join Palmeiro on the list
of top 10 defensive first basemen in major league history. ...
Another change in the starting lineup was Frank Catalanotto at
second base, instead of Luis Alicea, a .201 hitter last year who
had three hits in the opener.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Devil Rays-Twins
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: The Devil Rays are trying to start 2-0 for the first
time in their three-year history. ... How rare was leadoff hitter
Gerald Williams' home run Monday in Tampa Bay's first at-bat of the
season? The Elias Sports Bureau said it has only happened 17 times
in the last 25 seasons, and only three times in the 1990s.
Toronto's Shannon Stewart also homered to lead off the bottom of
the first Monday vs. Kansas City. ... Fred McGriff's grand slam
Monday marked the second game in a row Tampa Bay hit a grand slam --
Randy Winn hit an inside-the-park slam in the final game of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: Twins starter Eric Milton won his last three
decisions of 1999 in the Metrodome, including a Sept. 11 no-hitter
vs. Anaheim. ... Marcus Jensen made his Twins debut starting at
catcher. The other new starter from Monday's lineup is David Ortiz
at first base (for Ron Coomer). ... The Twins are trying to end a
nine-game losing streak dating back to last September.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Tigers-Athletics
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: Since the beginning of last season, the Tigers have the
best save percentage in the major leagues. As a staff, Detroit has
converted 34 of 43 save opportunities, including Todd Jones' save
in Monday night's season-opening 7-4 win at Oakland. ... The
Tigers' Tony Clark finished one RBI shy last year of becoming the
first Tigers player ever to drive in at least 100 runs in each of
his first three full big league seasons. ... Luis Polonia was the
only Tiger to hit above .300 last season (.324). ... Dean Palmer
matched his career high with four hits in Monday night's
season-opening 7-4 win at Oakland. It was the fourth time he's had
four hits in a game but the first time since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: Oakland's Tim Hudson, who went 11-2 last year, had the
best ever win-loss percentage (.846) by an Oakland rookie. He also
had the distinction of beating both of the Cy Young Award winners
on the road, defeating Randy Johnson at Arizona on July 10 and
Boston's Pedro Martinez on Aug. 19. ...
</P>
<P>
   Jason Giambi became the first player in Oakland's history to hit
two homers on opening day. It was the ninth two-homer game game of
his career, his fifth against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Yankees-Angels
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK YANKEES: Third baseman Scott Brosius strained a rib
cage muscle during batting practice Tuesday and was scratched from
the starting lineup. He is listed as day to day. Clay Bellinger
replaced Brosius at third. ... The Yankees are wearing black arm
bands this season in memory of former manager and Hall of Fame
pitcher Bob Lemon, who died Jan. 11.
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: Closer Troy Percival, recognized at Monday's opener as
the reliever on the Angels' all-time team, was honored again
Tuesday morning by his former high school. Percival's No. 14 was
retired by his alma mater, Moreno Valley High, some 40 miles from
Anaheim. The school's baseball field also was dedicated in his
name. ''Much of who I am today was established at that high
school,'' he said. ''It might sound corny to say I'm humbled, but
believe me, that's truly the case.'' ... Anaheim's roster features
players from six different countries, including Jason Dickson of
Canada, Shigetoshi Hasegawa of Japan, Ramon Ortiz of the Dominican
Republic, Bengie Molina and Edgard Clemente of Puerto Rico, and
Benji Gil of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ------
NATIONAL LEAGUE
Brewers-Reds
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: Ken Griffey Jr. sometimes faced an infield shift
while playing for Seattle, with teams moving the shortstop to the
first-base side of second. The Brewers copied it in the opener with
success -- shortstop Mark Loretta threw out Griffey on a grounder up
the middle. ''It's been done before,'' manager Davey Lopes said.
Reds manager Jack McKeon thinks Griffey will see the shift until he
beats it. ''He'll fool them one of these days. He'll hit the ball
right through that hole.'' ... P Steve Woodard got soaked on
opening day and wondered if there was a connection. When the Reds
finished their regular-season schedule in Milwaukee last Oct. 3,
heavy rain forced a five-hour, 47-minute delay. The two teams drew
a deluge and a three-hour delay before Monday's game was called.
''Maybe we should wait until there's a drought before we play
them,'' Woodard suggested.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: Attendance for Tuesday night's makeup game
technically was zero. The attendance figure reflects the number of
tickets sold, and the Reds didn't sell any. Instead, fans who had
ticket stubs from Monday's called game were allowed in. ... Manager
Jack McKeon made two lineup changes, starting Benito Santiago at
catcher and Alex Ochoa in left field. McKeon likes to use his bench
players to keep them sharp. ''We got those guys in shape, we might
as well play them,'' McKeon said. ''You don't want them to sit too
long. I'll try to do it like I did last year, when we rotated
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
Dodgers-Expos
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: Following his grand slam on Monday night, Dodgers
first baseman Eric Karros has 212 career homers, second only to Ron
Cey's 228 on the Los Angeles career list. Karros' homer placed him
one ahead of Steve Garvey. Duke Snider's 389 leads all players on
the Dodgers franchise list, followed by Gil Hodges (361) and Roy
Campanella (242).
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: While the Expos signed a deal with French-language
radio station CKAC just hours before Monday night's season-opening
10-4 loss to Los Angeles, with no deal in place on the English
side, there was no local English language radio broadcast again for
the second straight game Tuesday night. ... Expos pitcher Dustin
Hermanson and general manager Jim Beattie attended a funeral
service in Palm Beach Gardens, Fla., for Cindy Lloyd, the
26-year-old wife of Montreal reliever Graeme Lloyd, who died Monday
as a result of complications from Crohn's disease.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Giants-Marlins
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: Several Giants said Florida's Alex Fernandez
pitched better on opening day than last year, when he was coming
back from shoulder surgery. ''This year I think he has more
velocity on his ball, and he has a better sink,'' outfielder Marvin
Benard said. ... Livan Hernandez, who was traded from Florida last
season, visited the Marlins clubhouse, a day after giving up five
runs and picking up the loss in the season opener. He joked most
with Marlins 1B Kevin Millar, one of Hernandez's five strikeout
victims.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: Manager John Boles had trouble falling asleep after
Monday's 6-4 win over San Francisco in front of a sellout crowd:
''It took a while to calm down after that game. It was exciting.''
... Boles said he won't hesitate to use 1B Derrek Lee and OF Mark
Kotsay as defensive replacements early in games, especially if they
keep hitting. They both got hits in their first at-bats off the
bench Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Astros-Pirates
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: New CF Roger Cedeno was a late scratch Tuesday because
of a sore right elbow. Richard Hidalgo moved from LF to CF, with
Bill Spiers starting in LF. .. Because of Monday night's rainout,
Shane Reynolds' next start was pushed back from Saturday to Sunday.
Dwight Gooden makes his first Astros start Saturday at Enron Field
against Philadelphia. ... Several Astros complained following
Monday's rainout that it always seems to rain in Pittsburgh.
However, the Pirates had only one rainout last season, a mid-April
game against St. Louis. ... Astros president Tal Smith was among
the representatives of six teams attending a presentation about
holding spring training in Las Vegas. Smith said the Astros are
happy with Kissimmee, Fla., and attended the Las Vegas meeting only
to see what was being proposed there. ... Right-hander Scott
Elarton, on a rehabilitation assignment at Triple-A New Orleans,
starts Thursday on opening night against Colorado Springs.
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: How things have changed dept.: Catcher Jason Kendall
was the only opening night starter Tuesday who also started the
1997 opener, the Pirates' first under manager Gene Lamont. Kendall
made his fifth consecutive opening day start. ... Owner Kevin
McClatchy treated construction workers at the new PNC Park to a
lunch of hamburgers, hot dogs and salad, then distributed 200 free
tickets to the Pirates' opener. The stadium workers also will be
saluted before a home game later this season. Most of the new
ballparks have a 27-month construction schedule, but the Pirates
are trying to build PNC Park in 23 months. ... Kris Benson, 3-0 in
spring training, lost two of his three starts to Houston last year.
He starts Wednesday night against the Astros. ... Some Pirates
entertained themselves during Monday night's rain delay by watching
the Penguins game.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Rockies-Braves
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: Tuesday night's start against Atlanta was the first
for Rolando Arrojo in the National League. He came to the Rockies
in a winter trade from Tampa Bay. The right-hander did pitch
against the Braves in 1998 when he won 14 games, giving up three
earned runs in 7 1-3 innings in a loss. This is his first visit to
Georgia since he defected in Albany in 1996 from the Cuban national
team before the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: Tom Glavine is hoping for a better start than last
season. The Braves left-hander went 3-6 last April and May with a
4.99 ERA, but finished the season at 14-11 with a 4.12 ERA. ...
John Rocker worked out with the club Tuesday prior to the game with
Colorado. Rocker, suspended for the first 14 days of the season,
said he will probably leave Wednesday for Orlando to begin extended
spring training. He's eligible to pitch again April 18 when
Philadelphia comes to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Phillies-Diamondbacks	   PHILLIES: Curt Schilling will pitch on opening day,
after all --
on Thursday for Class-A Clearwater. Manager Terry Francona says
Schilling's rehabilitation from shoulder surgery is progressing
well and is hopeful he will join the Phillies by late April. ''I'd
rather have him tonight, but he's doing terrific.'' Francona said.
... In his fifth season with Philadelphia, Francona says this is
the most optimistic he's been. ''We've got a closer (Mike Jackson).
We've got (Andy) Ashby and all our guys are a year older,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   DIAMONDBACKS: Closer Matt Mantei, on the 15-day disabled list
with biceps tendinitis, will begin throwing again Friday, Saturday
or Sunday, manager Buck Showalter said, and then will do some
rehabilitation with one of Arizona's minor league clubs. Until
Mantei returns, Arizona plans a closer-by-committee approach. ...
Left-handed reliever Greg Swindell was on hand for opening night
but leaves Tuesday for Texas and the funeral of his father, Harold,
who died after a long fight with cancer. Showalter said Swindell
will be gone at least Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
