<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan, NKorea Begin Talks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PYONGYANG, North Korea (AP) -- North Korean and Japanese
negotiators on Wednesday began their first talks in eight years on
establishing diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides said they would try to bridge their many differences,
including Tokyo's concerns over a North Korean ballistic missile
that was fired over Japan in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''Difficult problems exist, but I want to achieve mutual
understanding so we can overcome those issues,'' Kojiro Takano,
Tokyo's chief negotiator, told his counterpart, Jong Thae-kwa, as
the meeting began at the People's Palace of Culture. ''We have a
great determination to bring these talks to a conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   In his brief speech, Jong agreed that reaching an accord would
not be easy, but added: ''Where there's a will there's a way.''
</P>
<P>
   The two countries have never had diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
   Similar normalization talks between Japan and North Korea broke
down in 1992, and swift progress now is not expected.
</P>
<P>
   Pyongyang needs help from richer countries to feed its
impoverished people and modernize its decaying infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea also demands compensation and an apology for
suffering caused by Japan during its 1910-1945 colonial rule over
Korea. That obstacle was clear in Pyongyang's state-run media.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
