<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, April 4, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nasdaq, Dow Dive, Recover
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Fueled by an exodus from all things technological, the stock
market went into a stomach-churning rout today, with the Nasdaq composite index
and Dow Jones industrials each dropping more than 500 points before recovering.
The selloff came amid a collapse of the euphoria over high-tech issues that had
driven the Nasdaq to unprecedented gains in recent months. Analysts said they
couldn't point to any one factor in today's massive selling, but most said the
purge was long overdue. The Nasdaq was down 574.57 points at midday, then clawed
back to finish down 74.79 at 4,148.89. The Dow rose 196.31 points this morning
before diving to a loss of 504.15 in early afternoon. It finished down 57.09 at
11,164.84.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mori Elected Japan Ruling Party Head
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Yoshiro Mori was elected president of Japan's ruling party
Wednesday, replacing Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, who was on life support after
suffering a massive stroke. The full Parliament was to meet later Wednesday to
approve Mori as prime minister. Obuchi held both posts, but has been in a coma
since his sudden collapse on Sunday. The entire Cabinet resigned Tuesday, paving
the way for the quick selection of a new prime minister. Mori is expected to be
named to that spot later Wednesday and a Cabinet could be installed shortly
after that. The ruling Liberal Democratic Party president is assured of approval
as prime minister because of the party's majority in Parliament.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan, NKorea Begin Talks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PYONGYANG, North Korea (AP) -- North Korean and Japanese negotiators on
Wednesday began their first talks in eight years on establishing diplomatic
relations. Both sides said they would try to bridge their many differences,
including Tokyo's concerns over a North Korean ballistic missile that was fired
over Japan in 1998. The two countries have never had diplomatic relations.
Similar normalization talks between Japan and North Korea broke down in 1992,
and swift progress now is not expected. Pyongyang needs help from richer
countries to feed its impoverished people and modernize its decaying
infrastructure.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gov't, Elian Talks Suspended
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Negotiations between U.S. authorities and Elian Gonzalez's
Miami relatives ended today with no agreement on turning the boy over to his
father and were suspended until Thursday. Cuban officials said Elian's father,
Juan Miguel Gonzalez, will not come to the United States unless he is assured
his son will be turned over to him while the court battle over the boy plays
out. Outside the home where Elian has lived since he was rescued from a
Thanksgiving shipwreck that killed his mother, the crowd grew edgy in the heat
as they learned of the visa.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Open Down
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell Wednesday amid increasing worries about wild
swings on Wall Street and political uncertainty at home. The Nikkei Stock
Average shed 209.47 points to 20,385.46 in early trading.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Diana Ross Has New Tour, Supremes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Thirty years after Diana Ross left the Supremes, the sexy
diva of '60s pop is back with her girls. In pink leather and lipstick to match,
Ross strutted into a news conference today at Grand Central Terminal where she
and two new backup singers announced plans for a U.S. tour featuring the group's
timeless Motown hits. They're all Supremes -- Ross, Lynda Laurence and Scherrie
Payne -- but it's far from a reunion. The trio has never performed on stage
together.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Magic Zap Spurs 107-97
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- John Amaechi scored 24 points and Darrell Armstrong had
23 tonight as the Orlando Magic beat the San Antonio Spurs 107-97 for their
season-high seventh straight victory. Chucky Atkins, who had 16 points, led a
fourth-quarter surge by reserves who helped Orlando pull away for good. The
rookie had five points and three assists in the 13-4 run that put the Magic up
93-78 with just under six minutes to go. The Spurs, who got 30 points from David
Robinson, cut their deficit to 97-91 with 1:44 left. But Amaechi made a one-hand
runner on the baseline and Atkins followed with a clutch jumper to put the Magic
back in control.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rockies Beat Braves 5-3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Jeff Cirillo hit three doubles, including a three-run drive
in the seventh inning that rallied the Colorado Rockies over the Atlanta Braves
5-3 tonight. The crowd of 26,132 was the smallest ever at Turner Field, which
opened for the 1997 season. The previous low was 26,990 last April 27 against
Pittsburgh. John Burkett, in relief of Tom Glavine and making his first
appearance with the Braves, managed to get only one out before being hammered by
the Rockies in the seventh.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON
</SUBHEAD>
