<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 530 Guerrillas Surrender in India  </HEADLINE>
By WASBIR HUSSAIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAUHATI, India (AP) -- More than 530 separatist guerrillas armed
with guns and explosives surrendered their weapons to authorities
Tuesday, giving up their fight for independence for the eastern
state of Assam.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 532 insurgents belonged to the middle and senior
ranks of the United Liberation Front of Asom, a group that has
fought Indian security forces for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels laid down nearly 100 weapons, including assault
rifles, explosives, pistols, and communication gear in the Rang
Ghar, an amphitheater used from the 13th century by the royalty of
the Ahom tribe, the major ethnic group of Assam.
</P>
<P>
   The surrender in Sibsagar, the former capital of the Ahom
rulers, was the biggest since the United Liberation Front of Asom
was created in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gen. D.B. Shekatkar, the commander leading operations in
Assam, said 1,800 to 2,000 fighters remained in the jungles.
</P>
<P>
   Assam is the biggest of the seven states in India's remote far
east, separated from the rest of India by Bangladesh and linked by
a narrow corridor along the border with Nepal.
</P>
<P>
   More than 5,000 have been killed in the campaign by ULFA. Dozens
of people, especially executives of the area's huge tea
plantations, have been kidnapped for ransom.
</P>
<P>
   ''We shall be providing the surrendered militants with all
possible help and support, including vocational training, to enable
them to lead a normal life,'' said Chief Minister Prafulla Kumar
Mahanta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 2309 </TRAILER>
