<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Attends Fund-Raisers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton extended birthday wishes to
a Senate ally and lent his fund-raising talents to the Democratic
National Committee Tuesday night in back-to-back receptions.
</P>
<P>
   His first stop was at a gathering for Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.
The event was part fund-raiser, part birthday party for Leahy, who
turned 60 on Saturday. Elected to a fifth term in 1998, Leahy has
not announced whether he will run again in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   The reception was hosted by Bobby Muller, president of the
Vietnam Veterans of America Foundation. Leahy and Muller worked
together in the international effort to ban the use of land mines.
Muller's foundation finances the International Campaign to Ban
Landmines, which won the 1997 Nobel Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy and Muller are also allies in an effort to broaden legal
protections for defendants facing the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's next stop was a dinner fund-raiser for the Women's
Leadership Forum, an arm of the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Forty people paid $20,000 each to dine on sea bass and asparagus
and mingle with Clinton, DNC chairman Joe Andrews and event host
Carol Pensky, founder of the Women's Leadership Forum.
</P>
</TEXT>
