<HEADLINE> Russia Arrests Suspect in Bombing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Authorities have detained a suspect in the March
1999 bombing of a Russian market that killed 50 people, the news
agency ITAR-Tass reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The blast devastated the main market in Vladikavkaz, capital of
the Caucasus republic of North Ossetia, and was the worst violence
to hit the republic since a 1992 war with ethnic Ingush.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions from that war occasionally still flare up in
house-bombings and clashes between ethnic Ossetians and Ingush.
Also contributing to tensions is the stated aim of separatists in
neighboring Georgia's South Ossetian region to unite with North
Ossetians.
</P>
<P>
   The report, citing sources in the Federal Security Service, said
the suspect has a Georgian surname and gave his first name as
Gabit, but did not provide further details.
</P>
<P>
   It said he was arrested in Sochi, a Russian resort town on the
Black Sea, and taken to Vladikavkaz for interrogation.
</P>
</TEXT>
