<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Striking LA Janitors Block Streets  </HEADLINE>
By BART JONES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Striking janitors blocked intersections in
downtown Los Angeles on Tuesday, the second day of a walkout that
threatens to leave three-fourths of the county's commercial space
without cleaning services.
</P>
<P>
   Police reported no injuries or arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Police closed an offramp of the downtown Harbor Freeway for 25
minutes starting about 8:30 a.m. as dozens of strikers sat down in
the middle of a nearby intersection.
</P>
<P>
   Later, hundreds of janitors seeking higher pay marched through
downtown and blocked traffic in front of government and office
buildings. The tactics at least drew the attention of harried
rush-hour drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really don't care what the issues are. I'm just trying to
get to work,'' driver Lorecca Jefferson said.
</P>
<P>
   The 8,500 union-affiliated janitors are pressing for a
$1-an-hour raise each year for the next three years. They began
walking off the job Monday night and say their ''rolling strike''
will grow building by building until most of Los Angeles County is
without cleaning services by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Strikers also won symbolic support Tuesday from the Los Angeles
County Board of Supervisors, which voted 3-2 to back their effort
after union head Mike Garcia pleaded for their support.
</P>
<P>
   Contracts between Service Employees International Union Local
1877 and the 18 cleaning companies who hire the janitors expired
Friday night. No new talks were scheduled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
