<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Milwaukee Mayor Elected To 4th Term  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Mayor John Norquist won a fourth four-year term
Tuesday, defeating a downtown businessman who targeted Norquist's
record on crime, taxes and keeping jobs in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Norquist had 56 percent of the vote to George Watts' 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates spent about $1 million on the campaign, with the
50-year-old Norquist running upbeat ads showing him jogging around
Milwaukee streets and closing up drug houses alongside police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   Watts largely played to the right of the Democratic mayor in
this Democratic city, questioning his dedication to local
businesses and law enforcement. Watts challenged Norquist's
assertion that crime in Milwaukee is going down and called for the
ouster of the police chief.
</P>
<P>
   In one TV commercial, Watts read off a list of Milwaukee's ills,
such as the recent closing of a leather plant. Asking what Norquist
did about the problems, Watts looked up at a silent mannequin of
the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   About 125 miles to the northwest in the small town of Tomah, Ed
Thompson, the younger brother of Gov. Tommy Thompson, beat
incumbent Mayor Bud Johnson 1,179 to 909.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel like I'm king of the world,'' said Ed Thompson, 55, who
has been a professional poker player in Las Vegas, a prison cook, a
snow plow driver, and a boxer in ''Toughman'' contests.
</P>
<P>
   He said he decided to run for mayor after his supper club, Mr.
Ed's Tee Pee, was raided for allegedly operating illegal video
gambling machines. Thompson settled out of court and agreed not to
operate video poker machines for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said he hoped to whittle down Tomah's $32 million debt
and sounded ready to continue his campaign to legalize tavern
gambling, which he says would allow competition with Wisconsin's
tribal casinos.
</P>
<P>
   The governor did not campaign in Tomah for his brother.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
