<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Madagascar Cyclone Creates Homeless  </HEADLINE>
By KATYA ROBINSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANTANANARIVO, Madagascar (AP) -- Cyclone Hudah has created a
desperate situation in northern Madagascar with 100,000 people
homeless and in need of shelter and food, aid officials said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is really a disaster. No houses are untouched. There is
no power. The winds were so strong there are no trees,'' World Food
Program spokesman Salha Halado said Tuesday after returning from a
survey flight over Antalaha, the northeast town where Hudah made
landfall on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, residents of northeastern Madagascar picked through
the wreckage left by the cyclone and fashioned makeshift shelters
from the debris of their former homes that had been ripped apart by
the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Relief officials worried about possible food shortages because
the storm also destroyed food storage warehouses and access to the
area was limited.
</P>
<P>
   Hudah charted a devastating course across the Indian Ocean
island Sunday night and Monday, killing two people. About 100,000
people in Antalaha, the heart of the country's vanilla growing
region, were thought to have been left homeless by the storm, the
National Disaster Committee said.
</P>
<P>
   The cyclone, now downgraded to a tropical storm, was over the
Mozambique Channel on Tuesday, moving slowly towards Mozambique
where flooding from torrential rains and an earlier cyclone left
699 dead and drove hundreds of thousands from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Hudah was expected to land early Wednesday morning in northern
Mozambique, the South African Weather Bureau in Pretoria said
Tuesday evening. The storm was gaining power as it crossed the
Mozambican Channel, and it was expected to bring heavy rains, the
bureau said.
</P>
<P>
   Hudah was not expected to cause as much damage as previous
storms, but there were fears of more flooding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
