<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rangers 12, White Sox 8  </HEADLINE>
By JAIME ARON, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Rafael Palmeiro hit a three-run homer in
the first inning and added an RBI single in a seven-run sixth,
leading the Texas Rangers past the Chicago White Sox 12-8 Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight game, Texas got big production from the
guys that came over from Detroit in the Juan Gonzalez trade.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Catalonotto started the winning rally with a two-run homer
that tied the game at 6, reliever Francisco Cordero (1-0) picked up
the victory and opening-day hero Gabe Kapler went 3-for-5 with a
double and a steal.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Greer continued the sixth-inning comeback with a bloop RBI
double off reliever Bill Simas (0-1), then scored on Palmeiro's
chopper up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   David Segui's RBI groundout with one out and the bases loaded
made it 9-6. Kapler appeared to have ended it with a roller to
third base, but Paul Konerko's throw to first was so wide not even
6-foot-5 Frank Thomas could get a glove on it, allowing two more
runs to score.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox went ahead 4-3 by getting six hits in a
seven-batter span off Rangers starter Rick Helling. The first three
hits were doubles and the fourth was an RBI triple by Chris
Singleton.
</P>
<P>
   Singleton singled home a run in the fifth, upping the lead to
5-3, but Texas got the run back on an RBI single by rookie Ruben
Mateo. The hit chased Chicago starter Kip Wells, a Houston native
and Baylor product looking to win in his first big league game in
his home state.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas had an RBI single in the sixth that again gave the White
Sox a two-run cushion. Then, after Chicago was down by five, Carlos
Lee hit a two-run homer in the seventh that cut the deficit to
11-8.
</P>
<P>
   Wells' nerves showed early as he walked two of the first three
batters, then hung an 0-1 breaking ball to Palmeiro and saw it end
up 431 feet away in the upper deck in right field.
</P>
<P>
   He settled in a bit, but lost control again in the fourth and
walked the Nos. 8 and 9 hitters with two outs. In 4 1-3 innings, he
gave up four runs on four hits and tied his career-best with six
strikeouts. He also walked six.
</P>
<P>
   Helling, who led the majors with 41 homers allowed last season,
got through the order once despite tossing many high, hittable
pitches, but it caught up to him in the fourth. He allowed four
runs on seven hits in 3 1-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Cordero allowed Chicago's runs in the fifth and sixth, but got
the win thanks to Texas' rally in the bottom of the sixth. He also
gave up three hits in his 1 1-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Ivan Rodriguez drew a full-count walk for the second
straight game, despite his vow Monday to walk even less than the 24
walks he had last season. ... Jeff Abbott, who came into the game
4-for-6 against Helling, had the hit that knocked Helling out of
the game. ... Singleton seemed to have stolen second base on
Rodriguez, but it didn't count because Carlos Lee interfered with
the Gold Glove catcher for the last out of the second inning. After
swinging and missing strike two, Lee's follow-through caught the
back of Rodriguez's right shoulder.
</P>
</TEXT>
