<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Episopal Bishops Disagree on Gays  </HEADLINE>
By LEON DROUIN KEITH, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE ARROWHEAD, Calif. (AP) -- During a five-day retreat that
ended Tuesday, 135 of the nation's Episcopal bishops agreed to
disagree over the issues of ordaining homosexual priests and
blessing gay marriages.
</P>
<P>
   The members of the House of Bishops discussed but did not take
any official stand on the matters during the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Griswold III, presiding bishop of the Episcopal Church,
said the 2.5-million-member U.S. denomination will maintain its
tradition of respecting dioceses' rights to make their own
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Participants at the retreat admitted there was tension between
conservative and liberal clergy, but said frank group discussions
helped create an atmosphere of respect.
</P>
<P>
   Gay issues have created a rift between liberal and conservative
Episcopalians, as they have in other denominations. Some dioceses
have ordained gay priests and blessed gay marriages, even though
the church's parent group, the worldwide Anglican Communion, called
homosexuality ''incompatible with Scripture'' two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The rift widened in January when two American priests who oppose
homosexuality were consecrated as bishops in Singapore -- without
church approval -- by two conservative bishops.
</P>
<P>
   Griswold said the church is taking no action against the
priests, but added that they ''may very well be the beginnings of
another breakaway church.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is expected to be a focal point during the triennial
General Convention in July in Denver. Bishop Fred Borsch of the Los
Angeles diocese said one reason the House of Bishops did not issue
a resolution on the issue of homosexuality was because the
convention is so soon.
</P>
<P>
   The General Convention has final authority on matters of
doctrine and policy. It is composed of about 300 members of the
House of Bishops and about 800 clergy and lay people.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.ecusa.anglican.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-04-00 2358 </TRAILER>
